<HEADLINE>The advantage of airline time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Little has a point in discussing the often ill-understood north-south
aspect of time zones. Those who cross five 1-hour zones at high speed in flying
from New York to Glasgow may suffer jet lag. Those at the South Pole who walk
round all 24 zones, or through some them, in a few seconds report no adverse
effects.
I am not quite sure what he means by astronomical time. I understand that
observatories either work in universal time (UT), or in local time. That is, an
observatory has a UT clock synchronised with clocks in every other observatory,
so making the earth just one time zone.
In local time Glasgow would be about four minutes later than Edinburgh. That
system abolishes zones (or more correctly creates an infinite number) because
it takes its local noon to be when the sun is due south. That system also
existed 150 years ago when travel was by slow stagecoach.
Trains moving at 60mph made it inconvenient for Glasgow clocks to be different
from those in Edinburgh and they imposed Railway Time that turned the UK into
one time zone. Larger countries like the USA did not always do that and so
there are inconsistencies.
Recently I received a 1996 diary that has a time-zone map of the world. I see
that China from east to west has only one time zone. Just beyond its northern
border, Russia, between the same meridians, seems to need three. Clearly there
will be towns close together in large countries where the zone changes and
there is a difference of one hour in the clocks.
What is the difficulty with Britain having a different time zone from
continental Europe, especially since we have a distinct boundary that does not
produce adjacency disruption?
However, I think it may be an advance to have airline time. Aircraft travel 10
times as fast as trains and so should need bigger zones. It could be an
advantage to have airline time that was the same all over the world. Airports
would have two clocks, airline time and local zone time. From starting the
journey until the destination, airline time would be observed.
There would be no such thing as an international date line so timetables would
be much simpler. Airport notices would advise those leaving the airport other
than by air to adjust their watches to local zone time.
Chris Parton,
40 Bellshill Road,
Uddingston.
</TEXT>
