<HEADLINE>A closed mind</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN your leader headlined Scotland: the way ahead is clear, you state, ``In
assessing the conflicting claims there is one constant, and that is the
importance of the Union for all Scots'' (December 1).
That is the sentence that displays a closed mind. It is the Union that
separates Scots from the oil resources in their waters, the Scots from their
own parliament, and therefore Scotland from direct access to the rest of the
world.
The ending of the Union, which has brought benefits in the past without doubt,
would free Scotland and allow it to prosper and take its rightful place among
the new nations in the world, its future dependent solely on the efforts of its
citizens.
William D Brown,
Dunvegan,
Achscrabster,
Thurso.
</TEXT>
