<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Personal attacks out - so where's the fun?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Speaker yesterday made a suggestion which could undermine parliamentary
democracy as we know it in this country. Nolan and Scott are small beer
compared with this.
Miss Boothroyd has found as she attends functions around the country and meets
ordinary people - which, in this case, means all those who are not MPs - that
they are ``sick and tired'' with the personal attacks that go on in the Commons.
She thought they were right, and would be looking for exchanges to concentrate
on policies in future.
The goody-goodies and the sycophants gave a little cheer. The rest were silent,
presumably appalled at the prospect of one of the fun bits of being an MP
vanishing.
Nolan is making it more difficult to earn an extra bob or two, and now one
might be prevented from being rude to the other side.
Miss Boothroyd's remarks seemed to come under the heading of an observation
rather than a ruling. However, she already had made a pre-emptive strike.
Mr Don Touhig (Islwyn - Lab.) attacked the Government's plan to develop a
``fast track'' for schools to go on to grant-maintained status. Welsh Education
Minister Rod Richards responded that Mr Touhig's leader already had ensured a
fast track out of Islington local schools for his son to attend a
grant-maintained establishment.
The Speaker told him sharply to answer the question and not attack another
Member. Some Tories exchanged startled glances. Mr Blair's perfectly legitimate
decision to put his son's educational interests first had seemed to them a
useful illustration of the difference between policy and practice which they
discerned in Labour.
It might be argued that it is not so much the invective as its quality that is
turning off those citizens Madam Speaker meets.
Disraeli's calling the entire Treasury bench ``exhausted volcanoes'', Churchill
describing Ramsay MacDonald as the ``boneless wonder'', Denis Healey describing
a Geoffrey Howe attack on him as like ``being savaged by a dead sheep'' - are
these and other jewels in the crown of parliamentary debate to be banished?
Their like have admittedly temporarily disappeared.
Is this intervention from the chair to leave us with nothing but talk like
yesterday's ``outward divestment'' from Mr Paul Flynn (Newport West - Lab.),
meaning firms and jobs leaving an area.
Mr John Butterfill (Bournemouth West - Con.) rose to seek the Speaker's help.
His intention to bring in a summertime Bill has brought him such a heavy
postbag that he cannot cope. Bodies supporting his Bill have offered him
secretarial help. But would he be caught by the new Nolan rules and be regarded
as their paid advocate if he accepted and perhaps not be allowed to proceed
with his Bill?
The Speaker said that this was a grey area and she could not anticipate what a
committee which has yet to buckle down to clarifying matters might decide.
Mr Dennis Skinner (Bolsover - Lab.), a man whose name springs to mind when
parliamentary rudery is mentioned, suggested that if Mr Butterfill did not have
enough time to deal with his postbag he ``should pack in those moonlighting
jobs he has got''. Mr Butterfill grinned, the Speaker decided that did not
constitute a personal attack and we moved into the Budget debate and the new
era of politeness to all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
