<HEADLINE>Bare bait</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n A RATHER self-admiring article in new intellectuals' magazine Prospect
informs us that the Russian Playboy is going great guns, introducing
sophistication, argument, and the most restrained of nudity into a hitherto
rather trashy market. After all, Cindy Crawford on the cover of issue two is
actually concealing her breasts with her hands, rather a vogue among American
superstars at the moment (for example Demi Moore and Janet Jackson).
One Russian author not so far tempted to contribute to the magazine is
Alexander Solzhenitsyn, perhaps put off by the publications which share the top
shelf with Playboy; SPID-Info, for example (or Aids-Info), evolved very quickly
from a sort of public service publication to an extended Readers' Wives and
letters forum covering everything from incest to shepherd dogs, it says here.
Women make up one-quarter of the Russian Playboy's readership, the highest of
all the world's Playboys, apparently, which editor Artyom Troitsky puts down to
having ditched the traditional Entertainment for Men slogan in favour of Food
for Thought - and Fun for All. Here's hoping they weren't expecting recipes
inside, then.
n AND, from Prospect again, come Hillary Clinton's reflections on 20 years of
marriage to Bill. He proposed more than once, it seems (she was initially
reluctant to marry a man who was ``going to build his life in Arkansas'' - boy,
was she wrong, or boy, did she get to work on him), but what finally swung it
was the house he bought as a surprise for her - it was ``only 1000 sq ft and
had no air-conditioning, but it did have a big attic fan, a screened-in porch,
a living-room with a beamed cathedral ceiling, a fireplace, and a big bay
window''. Nice to know romance isn't dead and that the Clintons ``love each
other more now than when we married''. One thousand square feet, for all you
cynics, is about the size of a one-bedroom tenement flat.
n HAPPY 10th birthday to the San Jai project, set up in Garnethill, Glasgow, to
advise and counsel immigrant Chinese families, organise social events, and
bring awareness of a different culture to the new country. Latterly it has
worked on domestic violence, family breakdown, and opportunities for Chinese
children.
Andrew, 14, says they supported him with problems he could not talk through at
home, a service many second-generation children would appreciate. ``I have also
been able to relax there as all the people at the project can understand what
it's like growing up in Scotland as a member of a Chinese family.'' Many happy
returns.
n IT'S not the kids who spend too much time gazing into computer screens; it's
their mums, according to a survey by US company CompuServe Inc, which provides
on-line services such as tax guidance to more than 3.6 million subscribers.
Women in the survey were likely to be college graduates, married, aged 35 to
54, and with a household income of $70,000, and spent more than half their
eight hours of free time each week gazing through the on-line services.
Far from indicating a generation of go-getting hot computer mamas, however, the
women were looking for information which would help their children and their
families, especially as the majority of them had the job of sorting out the
family finances. Perhaps Pop was too busy watching the ball game; plus ca
change . . .
n CHRISTMAS requests from readers of Gardening Which? December issue range from
the ambitious (a brand-new garden!) through the down-to-earth (a bag of
manure), to the very stuff of dreams itself (a handsome young gardener). Only
one hopeful correspondent wrote in with this suggestion. The most popular gift
choice was garden-centre gift vouchers, no doubt nestling alongside those
luxurious handkerchiefs in the Christmas stocking.
n AND in case all this talk of Christmas seems a bit previous, Easter is upon
us already; Nestle Rowntree has already announced that the theme of its 1996
Easter range will be more choice - the range will include a staggering 33
different sorts of egg, including the new After Eight, Matchmakers, and Aero
egg. Kids' favourite last year was the Smarties egg, says Nestle.
n BOOTS is hiring out TENS machines for women who want to try alternative pain
relief during labour. BabiTENS will cost #23.50 per calender month, and should
be picked up two weeks before your due date, available in major stores
throughout Scotland.
</TEXT>
