<HEADLINE>#14m gift comes of bitterness</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York
ANNE SCHEIBER retired as a US government auditor during the Second World War,
bitter about never having been promoted.
Living frugally and investing wisely, she built her $5000 savings into a stock
portfolio valued at her death this year at $22m (#14m). Her last act was to
bequeath the fortune to New York's Yeshiva University to help women overcome
discrimination.
``Elation would be an understatement,'' said Dr Norman Lamm, Yeshiva's
president.
College administrators had never heard of the benefactor, who lived as a
recluse until her death in January aged 101.
Scheiber's gift was born of bitterness, her lawyer said, because she felt that
despite having a law degree she was held back for 23 years at the Internal
Revenue Service simply because she was a woman. She retired in 1944.
``This grew on her year after year,'' attorney Benjamin Clark said. ``She was
very much embittered while employed at the IRS.''
Clark, who met Scheiber in the mid-1950s, said she lived alone for decades.
``She was the loneliest person. I never saw her smile,'' he said. ``She was
very distrustful . . . she didn't want anybody to know what she had.''-AP.
</TEXT>
