<HEADLINE>Latest violence again targets Russia Chechen car bomb kills 12</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LAWRENCE SHEETS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Grozny
A POWERFUL car bomb killed at least a dozen people in the capital of Russia's
rebel Chechnya region ahead of parliamentary elections later this month.
Many fear the attack may be the start of a spiral of violence in the run-up to
the polls.
The bomb ripped a big crater in a street outside the offices of the Russian
regional administration in central Grozny.
One of the victims, an elderly woman, was hurled against the wall of a
neighbouring building by the blast, eyewitnesses said. Russian officials said
children were among the victims of the explosion, the biggest for months.
Some sources said as many as 18 people were killed, but estimates varied
because local people had hurriedly removed the bodies to bury them before
sunset, in line with local Muslim tradition. Up to 60 people were believed to
have been hurt.
``The aim of the terrorist act was to scare the people of the republic in the
run-up to the elections,'' Russian State Television said, quoting a statement
by the Moscow-backed Grozny government, whose offices were badly damaged in the
blast.
Russian television said a column of troops was ambushed on its way out of the
region last week and the Moscow-installed leader of Chechnya Doku Zavgayev,
escaped with minor injuries when his motorcade was attacked in Grozny last
month.
Moscow is making preparations for Chechnya to take part in a Russia-wide
parliamentary poll on December 17 and also to vote for a new leader for the
war-torn region.
Some ordinary Chechens have already said they will not go to the ballot box
because they are afraid both of rebels, who still control big pockets of the
region, and patrols of heavily-armed Russian troops.
Several candidates have put their names forward for the Chechen leadership
poll, but rebel leader Dzhokhar Dudayev, hiding out in the towering mountains
to the south of the tiny North Caucacus region, has condemned the election as
illegal.
His supporters say the presence of Russian troops, who flooded into the region
one year ago to try to stop it splitting from Moscow, means the poll cannot be
fair.
They have threatened to disrupt voting which they say is a provocative attempt
to spark a civil war.
Police sealed off the bomb-wrecked area of Grozny and used sniffer-dogs to make
sure there were no more explosives amid the rubble of twisted cars and
shattered glass, bricks and metal from neighbouring buildings.
``This act against the peaceful population, victimising women and children,
cannot be justified,'' said Oleg Lobov, Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
representative in Chechnya.
``The murderers will have to answer before the law,'' he said in a statement
carried by Itar-Tass news agency.
Russian officials have predicted a surge in violence in the run-up to the poll
but have dismissed suggestions that they should be cancelled owing to security
risks in the republic, where a five-month ceasefire is hanging by a
thread.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
