<DOCNO>GH951205-000006</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000006</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU introduces sports boycott against Nigeria</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN Secretary Malcolm Rifkind tonight welcomed a ``tightening of the
screw'' by European governments against the dictatorship in Nigeria.
He was speaking in Brussels after EU foreign ministers extended their protest
against the executions of author Ken Saro-wiwa and eight other human rights
activists by cutting off all formal sporting contacts with Nigeria.
The ministers also decided to expel Nigerian military personnel from the
regime's embassies in EU capitals, withdrawal their own military staff from
member state embassies in Lagos and widen existing visa restrictions to include
all civilians deemed to be in contact with the regime of General Sani Abacha.
Mr Rifkind told a news conference: ``This is a further tightening of the screw
against the Nigerian regime.''
He said the new measures were intended to be a ``clear indication'' to the
regime that the EU expected steps to be taken to restore democracy and human
rights.
EU governments have already banned arms sales to Nigeria and clamped down on
visas for officials linked to the regime.
However today they again stopped short of freezing Nigerian assets in Europe or
imposing an oil embargo - both measures considered impractical without wider
backing through the United Nations Security Council.
Such sanctions would in any case require evidence of a threat to international
stability - and another stumbling block is that Nigeria itself is currently a
member of the Security Council.
Mr Rifkind explained that the move to end formal sporting contacts would
prevent national sports teams from the member states going to Nigeria or
receiving visiting teams from the country.
Meanwhile, Immigration Minister Ann Widdecombe defended plans to send back to
Nigeria democracy activist Abiodun Igbiuidu, who claims he faces persecution
and torture at home.
Mr Igbiuidu, a member of the Campaign for Democracy in Nigeria, had his
application for asylum refused and his case is now undergoing judicial review.
If that fails, he will be deported to Nigeria next weekend.
Miss Widdecombe said his claim had been thoroughly examined by the Home Office
and an independent adjudicator.
``He has lost his appeal. Therefore I feel we have no option but to deport
him,'' she said.
Claude Moraes, of the Joint Council for the Welfare of Immigrants, said: ``We
don't believe Mr Igbiuidu's case has been looked at objectively.
``We believe that in view of the recent executions of opponents of the Nigerian
government, he may be in physical danger should he be sent back.''
Brussels
</TEXT>
</DOC>
