<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kashmir hostages enter six months in captivity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar
TWO Britons and a German held hostage by the shadowy Al-Faran militant group in
Kashmir entered their sixth month in captivity today with no sign of an end to
the crisis.
``We have been appealing to the abductors to release the hostages before
Christmas, but it is all in their hands. They have not made contact with the
government for the last week,'' said government spokesman K B Jandial.
This is by far the longest hostage crisis involving foreigners in Kashmir. Two
Swedish engineers working on a power project in the valley spent 97 days held
by the Muslim Janbaz Force in 1991 before escaping.
Britons Paul Wells and Keith Mangan and American Donald Hutchings were
kidnapped on July 4 along with American John Childs, who escaped. Dirk Hasert
of Germany was taken hostage four days later.
Norwegian Hans Christian Ostroe, also kidnapped on July 8, was found beheaded
on August 13.
The Western tourists are known to have suffered stomach and eye ailments, and
Hutchings is believed to have frostbitten feet.
Al-Faran, unknown before the kidnappings, has demanded the release of 15 jailed
separatists. India has refused to bow to the militants' demand and has ruled
out a rescue operation for fear the hostages might be killed.
Al-Faran broke off contact with Indian authorities several times after weeks of
fruitless negotiations. The longest gap was 52 days before November 9.
On Saturday Al-Faran asked the All Parties Hurriyat (Freedom) Conference, a
political umbrella group of separatist organisations in Kashmir, to mediate in
the crisis.
The Hurriyat Conference turned down the plea and reiterated its appeal for the
unconditional release of the hostages.
The four Westerners have been periodically sighted by Kashmiris as the
abductors lead them through isolated villages and were last sighted a week
ago.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
