<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>no headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
You have to hand it to President Clinton for the panache, tact, empathy, and
political sophistication of his visit to Britain and Ireland.
He was alert to all the sensitivities and did not make a false step. In
Northern Ireland that was a triumph in itself.
The president's tour de force has left a deep impression on the public mind in
these islands. His carefully balanced words to the people of Northern Ireland
were much more acceptable to everyone than the nationalist bias which has
coloured some of his administration's attitudes and antagonised Ulster's
Unionist majority.
Does the visit mark a shift in the US stance on the peace process? Has the
White House started listening to Whitehall as much as to Dublin?
It will be a long tramp still to a peaceful settlement of our differences in
Ireland. In this year, though, when the 50th anniversary of the end of the
Second World War was commemorated in London, Washington, Belfast, and Dublin,
the President's visit symbolises the shared heritage of the peoples of Britain,
Ireland, and the United States.
Together we have unequalled potential for peace, stability, and democracy in
the world when we unite in friendship for a common purpose.
Desmond McGimpsey,
4 Brandon Grove,
Bangor, Co Down,
N Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Orkney aloof</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY do politicians and others assume that everyone in Scotland longs for a
Scottish parliament? This assumption is very far from the truth, as a
referendum would prove.
I belong to the Orkney Islands which until 1468 were part of Norway;
history-conscious Orcadians certainly have no wish to be dominated once more by
the Scots.
In spite of the safeguards specified in the Deed of Impignoration (1611) our
native rights were filched away, our language (the Norn) was abolished, and we
were reduced to penury and slavery.
In the words of a distinguished Orcadian historian: ``Right down to the Union
with England (1707) Scottish dominion could only be regarded as a curse''.
The long years of oppression had eventually broken the spirit of the islanders,
and, though our links with Norway are still strong, our loyalty to the British
crown is not in doubt.
That any sensible person should wish to be governed in any way by the
quarrelsome Scots beggars belief (witness the recent illegal shenanigans of
postal workers in both East and West); for, in the event of a Scottish
parliament, overwhelming power would be wielded by the Central Belt.
What has happened to the old truism, ``United we stand, divided we fall''?
Ruby Leslie,
27 Lambaness,
Kirkwall, Orkney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sixty killed as airliner crashes in Cameroon</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 60 of 78 passengers and crew were killed when a Cameroon airliner crashed
into a mangrove swamp as it attempted to land in the Central African country's
commercial capital, Douala.
The Boeing 737 was on a scheduled flight from the city of Cotonou in Benin,
which has been playing host to heads of state at a summit of 47 French speaking
countries.
The meeting ended today and dignitaries from the summit were said to be on the
doomed flight.
Most of the passengers were from Cameroon but there were also said to be a
number of Europeans and other West Africans on the flight.
Fishermen in dugout canoes were the first to reach the wreckage of the Boeing,
which came down in the swamp in pitch darkness last night, complicating rescue
efforts.
``Rescuers, essentially fishermen, did not reach the disaster site until an
hour after the crash,'' said an airline official.
The army, joining the rescue effort, pulled out six people alive, among them
the pilot, co-pilot, and a stewardess. Several people were still unaccounted
for.
Five of the survivors, including the stewardess, were taken in critical
condition to local clinics.
A privately-owned helicopter hovered above the crash site about two miles from
the runway, directing a beam of light over the swamp to help rescuers.
The cause of the crash was not immediately known but airport officials said the
pilot first tried to land then aborted the attempt, apparently owing to
problems with the undercarriage.-Reuter.
Douala
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deer culling backed by peers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS for taking the law on the management of wild deer in Scotland forward
to the next century were given their second reading in the Lords yesterday.
The Deer (Amendment) (Scotland) Bill gives revised powers to the Deer
Commission for Scotland - a new name for the Red Deer Commission - and widens
its scope to control marauding deer to cover serious damage to the natural
heritage and threats to public safety.
The commission will be empowered to authorise out-of-season shooting in certain
circumstances.
Scottish Office Minister the Earl of Lindsay, who insisted that welfare was
central to the Bill, said: ``Deer are our largest wild land mammal and there
are no natural predators. They therefore need effective management to allow
them to live in harmony with their habitat and other land uses.''
There are some concerns on the Tory benches and elsewhere about the powers
being given to the new commission.
For Labour, Lord Carmichael of Kelvingrove said everyone accepted that
something had to be done but there was uncertainty over whether the Government
had managed to get the balance right.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pressure grows to limit Diana's role</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIME Minister John Major was facing growing pressure last night to limit the
Princess of Wales to a charity role on the world stage.
Influential back bench MPs were showing a wariness bordering on hostility -
believed to be reflected in the Cabinet - to the princess's wish to become a
roving ambassador.
The role of the Princess of Wales is expected to be high on the agenda at this
evening's routine weekly meeting between the Queen and Mr Major.
Buckingham Palace and Downing Street were sticking yesterday to the strict rule
of silence governing all palace audiences, but MPs believed it was
inconceivable that the issue would not arise.
Back benchers were swift to demand a strict limit on the official role for
Diana sanctioned by the Government.
Dame Jill Knight, vice chairman of the Tory back bench 1922 committee, cast
doubt on
Continued from Page 1
the princess's ambassadorial skills.
``It really is not enough just to smile at people and pat them on the head,''
she said.
``I am quite sure she has a talent to comfort people and make them feel better,
but if you are going to be a diplomat, you have got to have many years of
experience.
``Diplomatic relations can be extremely delicate. It is extremely easy to
offend when you don't mean to, to say the wrong thing when you don't mean to.''
Mr Bill Walker, a senior Tory MP, said: ``Her first duty should be to her
children. A woman should be looking after her children's interests. I don't
think enough attention has been paid to their needs.''
The Southend-east MP, Sir Teddy Taylor, was one of the few MPs prepared to come
to Diana's defence.
``She can achieve friendship and understanding with foreign leaders without
getting involved in politics,'' he said. ``It would be very sad if that great
asset was to be lost.''
The princess expressed her desire to be a ``queen of  hearts'' among ordinary
people as well as an ambassador at large during her astonishing BBC TV
interview two weeks ago which laid bare the painful details of her marriage
break-up.
Labour MP Andrew Mackinlay plans to table a series of questions asking Mr Major
to clarify the princess's future role.
He said: ``We have a right to know what is going on. I am considering raising
the issue with Mr Major in the Commons at Question Time tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
