<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pleas by doctors and police rejected Limit cut on drink-driving is ruled out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government yesterday rejected a call by doctors' leaders to cut the
drink-driving limit by almost half.
The British Medical Association had written to Transport Secretary Sir George
Young calling for the alcohol limit to be reduced from 80mg per 100ml of blood
to 50mg. This would bring Britain into line with other European countries and
greatly reduce the risk of accidents, the BMA said.
However, while the Government turned down the BMA, its stance was welcomed by
the traffic standing committee of the Association of Chief Police Officers in
Scotland (Acpos), which announced that breath-testing this year is up by 26%
for the first 10 days of the Scottish police forces' drink-driving campaign.
The association said that 15,255 motorists had been breath-tested compared with
12,024 last year. Of this number, 317 had given positive tests compared with
295 last year. The positive breath tests represented 2.07% of motorists stopped.
Speaking the day before the Government launches its #1m Christmas
anti-drink-drive campaign, Transport Minister Steven Norris said the public
accepted the present limit.
He said: ``There is no point in setting the (drink-drive) limit at zero or any
other figure if in the end people simply ignore it.
``Eighty milligrams is the kind of level people accept. They think it's
sensible. At that level, we have the best drink-drive record in the Western
world.
``There isn't actually any link between the actual legal limit and the number
of drink-related deaths in some countries in western Europe.''
Former Tory Roads Minister Peter Bottomley, MP for Eltham, said drink-driving
had been cut to probably the lowest level in the Western world.
``This has not happened because of a change in the law. Drink-driving has been
reduced, especially among young men, because of a change of culture.
``To save the remaining 500 lives lost each year through drink driving - down
from 1800 in 1978 - we all need to offer alcohol-free drinks to drivers, make
sure that as passengers we choose alcohol-free drivers, and that as drivers, we
decide in advance whether we are driving or drinking.''
The call to cut the limit was made jointly by the BMA and the Parliamentary
Advisory Council for Transport Safety (Pacts), a cross-party road safety
pressure group.
In their letter to Sir George Young, the BMA and Pacts said: ``Research
evidence indicates that the relative risk of driver involvement in road traffic
accidents is increased significantly at a blood alcohol level of 50mg/100ml.''
A BMA spokeswoman said: ``We are not trying to ruin people's fun, but being
killed by a drunk driver can also wreck your Christmas cheer.
``All the evidence suggests that reducing the alcohol limit would make a big
difference to the number of fatalities and injuries.''
The BMA was supported yesterday by Mr Ian Mackinnon, Acpos traffic secretary
and assistant chief constable (traffic) in Strathclyde. He said: ``The
committee is pleased to note the stance taken by the BMA in calling for a
lowering of the limit.''
Last week, Acpos called for a lowering of the blood/alcohol limit to 50 at the
launch of the 1995/96 Scottish police forces' festive drink-driving campaign.
Police chiefs in Scotland said the reduction would have prevented 213 serious
accidents and saved #183m in Scotland between 1988 and 1993.
Meanwhile, police in Strathclyde have breath-tested almost 10,000 drivers in
the first 10 days of this year's campaign. There were 129 positive tests
compared with 115 last year.
A police squad has carried out 3100 tests since it went into operation on
November 27 and, so far, a total of five drivers have been found positive.
``Of the five who proved positive, all were tested between 8am and 10am,'' said
officer in charge, Inspector John Fenemore. ``This underlines our warning to
people about the morning-after effect - that is, the danger of driving the
morning after a night of drinking alcohol.''
q A survey yesterday showed that Britain's roads were among the safest in the
world, with the number of cars increasing but deaths from accidents falling.
From the mechanical breakdown insurance company Warranty Holdings, the survey
showed that Britain had 6.7 road deaths per 100,000 population, compared with
Portugal, the least safe country, which had 33 per 100,000.
q Owners of new vehicles will be given more flexibility in deciding the date of
the first MOT test, under plans laid before Parliament yesterday.
The proposals will allow owners to have their vehicles tested up to one month
before the third anniversary of a vehicle's first registration.
The plans will remove the need for owners to apply on the anniversary of the
vehicle's registration to avoid being penalised.
</TEXT>
