<HEADLINE>UN urged to end Rwanda mission</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UN urged to end
Rwanda mission
UNITED NATIONS: Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali has proposed that the
UN pull out its 2100 troops and observers in Rwanda later this week because the
Kigali government no longer wanted them.
The government had claimed the Unamir mission ``does not serve the real needs
of Rwanda'' and it could not remain without its consent, he reported. The
mandate of the Unamir mission ends on Friday. It was not certain whether the
Security Council would accept his advice as donor nations, troops contributors,
relief agencies and Rwanda's neighbours want Unamir to stay.
King has stroke
WASHINGTON: King Fahd of Saudi Arabia has suffered a stroke and has had
treatment from a specially flown-in US medical team, US officials said. The
72-year-old monarch was said to have been partially paralysed but was ``doing
well''.
Coach guilty
STUTTGART: Czech-born figure skating coach Karel Fajfr was yesterday given a
two-year suspended sentence for sexually abusing one teenage female skater in
his care and beating another.
Mandela is Santa
PRETORIA: Greenland has awarded South African President Nelson Mandela the
title of International Santa Claus of the Year, for his work on behalf of
children. Prime Minister Lars Emil Johansen unveiled a life-size sculpture of a
smiling Mandela in a red and white fur-lined Father Christmas costume. His
President's Children's Trust will receive the #60,000 prize money.
Islanders flee
PLYMOUTH: Government offices moved to the north end Montserrat yesterday and
many children were let out of school a week early as the island's volcano
continued to rumble. About 4000 residents from the island's southern end
settled into temporary quarters to the north in the second big evacuation since
Chances Peak roared back into life in July after 100 years.
Raiders strike
NAIROBI: Bands of armed attackers killed 18 people and drove off more than
40,000 animals in raids on three remote villages of northern Kenya, according
to police and a local MP. About 4000 raiders reportedly took part in the attack
in Turkana district.
Frying tonight
NEW DELHI: The Delhi High court allowed Kentucky Fried Chicken (KFC) to reopen
its New Delhi outlet yesterday, quashing an closure order imposed on the
American fast food chain by the city's municipal corporation. KFC has been
targeted by the country's main Hindu opposition party, which opposes opening up
the Indian market to foreign consumer goods.
Sex slave plea
SEOUL: At least 1000 nuns marched to the Japanese embassy in the South Korean
capital Seoul yesterday to protest against Tokyo's refusal to apologise
formally to women forced to serve as sex slaves during the Second World War.
The group demanded Japan pay compensation to those victims still alive.
Deadly flood
GRENOBLE: A teacher was drowned, four children were missing, and two children
were injured after a river suddenly flooded in the French Alps. The children
from a boarding school in Grenoble were on a nature-study trip walking on the
bed of the Drac river when its level rose, apparently owing to release of water
from a hydro-electric dam.
Crib record bid
STOCKHOLM: The small southern Swedish town of Nybro is trying to build the
largest Christmas Nativity crib in a bid to make the record books. The creche
has 1910 figures, 679 angels, 114 villagers, 43 soldiers, and countless oxen,
asses, and camels.
</TEXT>
