<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Children seized by  man with fake gun</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN with what turned out to be a fake gun took a classroom of children
hostage at a Paris primary school yesterday before surrendering to police after
a two-hour siege.
All the youngsters were freed unscathed, a police chief said.
The man, in his 30s and armed with a fake pistol, was ``someone who simply
wanted to make himself seen and heard'', he said.
``Negotiations took place with the individual and he gave himself up. There was
no use of force.''
The man rang the doorbell at Louis Aragon school in the north-west Paris suburb
of Clichy, put his gun to the woman caretaker's head, and took 30 children and
their teacher hostage just as the school day was about to end.
Jessica Adigery, a six-year-old pupil, said: ``He came into the classroom and
told us to stick our hands up. Then he said to put our hands on our heads. Then
he said to put our hands down and get on with our work.''
Police said the attacker freed seven of the children after 75 minutes, and
negotiators began talking to him while police commandos took up positions
around the school. ``He released the children in good condition. The teacher
managed the situation very well. It's a happy end after a big fright,'' said
the spokesman.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
