<HEADLINE>Scots to rely on Irish in fish war</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIEEuropean Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
OPPOSITION Euro-MPs rounded on the Scottish Office last night when it was
disclosed that Scottish fish farmers were left to rely on the Irish and other
governments for EU help in the salmon war with Norway.
The Irish, supported by the French, Swedes, and Finns, have taken the lead in
formally requesting European Commission intervention against alleged dumping of
salmon by the huge Norwegian fish farming industry.
The Scottish Office - representing 5000 workers in a struggling industry worth
#250m a year in sales - has so far declined to make a formal request for help
from Brussels. ``We are considering our position,'' a spokesman said last
night. ``We have been in very close touch with the industry and we are closely
monitoring the situation.''
The Commission will not act in the absence of an official request from a member
state. An Irish Government spokesman said last night: ``We have sent in a
letter asking for urgent action. It is a formal request.''
The Irish Government also led the way at talks with the Commission last week
when a Scottish Office official was stranded at home by an airline strike.
Irish officials have complained privately at a lack of support from the UK.
Dr Allan Macartney, SNP fisheries spokesman in the European Parliament,
denounced the Scottish Office's approach. ``Three cheers for the Irish,'' he
said. ``Why are our people not taking similar action?''
Labour's fisheries spokesman, Mr Hugh McMahon, said: ``I can't understand why
the Scottish Office is not being more aggressive about this. They should be in
there punching their weight.''
</TEXT>
