<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Political figures join tribute to Lord Home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADING political figures were among a congregation of about 600 at St Giles'
Cathedral in Edinburgh yesterday for a service of thanksgiving for the life of
former Conservative Prime Minister Lord Home of the Hirsel, who died in October.
Together with representatives of the royal family, they heard the Duke of
Buccleuch, in his address, speak of Lord Home - who was aged 92 when he died -
as a man of charm, intelligence, wit and ``a sense of service to others.''
The Duke said that Lord Home - Prime Minister from 1963-64 - had climbed to the
top of the ladder in his field ``without ever using his rivals as steps.''
He said Mr Harold Wilson, who succeeded him as Prime Minister, had said he was
the most honourable person he had come across and did not think he had an enemy
in the world, while Mrs Thatcher had called him ``the wisest man I've ever
met''.
``Tributes to great politicians are customary, but they have seldom been so
deepy sincere,'' the Duke said..
Among those who attended the service were Lord Whitelaw, who was deputy Prime
Minister during Margaret Thatcher's leadership, former Defence Secretary and
former Scottish Secretary Lord Younger, and the present Scottish Secretary, Mr
Michael Forsyth.
Mr Forsyth was accompanied by other members of the Scottish Office ministerial
team, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, Mr George Kynoch and Mr Raymond Robertson.
Sir David Steel was among a number of politicians from the Opposition parties.
Lord Younger read extracts from Lord Home's biography, The Way The Wind Blows,
and the 23rd Psalm to the tune of Crimond, a favourite of Lord Home's, was sung.
Lord Home's son, David, and one of his three daughters, Caroline, gave
readings, and prayers were led by the Most Rev. Richard Holloway, the Bishop of
Edinburgh, and the Rev. Gordon Tams, vicar of St. Mary's and All Souls,
Coldstream, where Lord Home was buried.
The blessing was given by the Right Rev. James Harkness, Moderator of the
General Assembly of the Church of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Challenge to Heseltine on Budget impact</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Our Political Staff</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday challenged the Government to admit that the average family
would be worse off as a result of the Budget.
The Cabinet was in a state of ``considerable confusion'' over the Budget, the
Opposition claimed.
Party deputy leader John Prescott wrote to Deputy Prime Minister Michael
Heseltine urging him to admit that the Budget changes now mean a typical family
is #670 a year worse off than in 1992.
Mr Prescott asked Mr Heseltine to confirm the true picture in a Commons debate
today.
In the letter, Mr Prescott said: ``Last week, senior Ministers were claiming
that, as a result, the average family would be #9 a week better off next year.''
However, Mr Prescott said Conservative Party chairman Dr Brian Mawhinney had
conceded when interviewed at the weekend that this was not the case and the
Budget would only be responsible for a small percentage of that figure.
Labour leader Tony Blair tonight will expect his MPs to abstain on the
Chancellor's 1p tax cut, while the Liberal Democrats will vote against it.
The SNP yesterday challenged the other Opposition parties to support it in
voting for a Budget amendment which would allow VAT on fuel to be reduced from
8% to 5%. It also wants support in voting against the increase in petrol duty
and the 1p income tax cut.
SNP leader Alex Salmond said last night: ``If our amendment is selected, we
call on all Opposition MPs to join with us in voting for our proposal which
allows VAT to be reduced to the European minimum of 5%.
``By tabling these amendments, the SNP is signalling its clear intention to
divide the House at the end of the Budget debate.''
In yesterday's continuing Budget debate Shadow Health Secretary Harriet Harman
accused Tory right-wingers of wanting to see an end to the National Health
Service as a free service available to all.
She clashed bitterly with Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell, who said the Budget
continued the real-terms growth in spending on the health service.
Former neuro-surgeon Sam Galbraith (Strathkelvin and Bearsden - Lab.) condemned
the Private Finance Initiative as ``privatising'' the NHS.
In Glasgow, a contract concerning the care of the elderly had been let. Now
changes were needed but the health authority was ``locked into'' a long-term
contract.
Leader Comment...............14
</TEXT>
