<HEADLINE>The ironing bored press on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Despite the invention of fabrics which should have made the iron obsolete, this
household chore remains. DEEDEE CUDDIHY talks to women who get all steamed up,
and a man who thrives on it.
WE ALL know now that whoever said new technology would cut down on paperwork -
and it was probably someone who went on to make a fortune  was talking complete
nonsense. But what about that other great lie of the twentieth century: the
claim that man-made fibres would mean never having to say ``iron'' again?
The whole point of drip dry was being able to wash something and then wear it
without doing anything tedious in between.
So why is it that, all these years after the launch of that first miracle
fabric, I still meet people - women, actually, if I'm being perfectly honest -
who complain about the huge piles of ironing they have waiting for them at
home?
Janice, for instance, a new woman if ever I met one; Sheila, so naturally
undomesticated that her husband does all the shopping and cooking; busy, busy
Barbara who admitted she even irons her children's socks!
Liz, thank goodness, didn't let me down. She was out at a union meeting when I
phoned but her daughter assured me: ``Mum never irons although my dad sometimes
does if he needs a shirt.'' But she revealed there was a rebellious cousin in
the family who ironed everything ``including her knickers''.
Although brought up to appreciate the finer points of a well-turned-out
organdie bedspread (my sister and I had a twin set - with curtains to match), I
had my eyes opened to the tyranny of ironing when a friend showed me how the
severe shaking of every item of clothing as it is taken from the washing
machine, prior to being hung up to dry, will reduce wrinkles to virtually
nil.
``And what can't be dealt with in that way isn't worth owning,'' she declared.
Since that day, our iron has rarely been taken from the cupboard. In fact, it
was last used 11 months ago to remove candle grease from a black wool jacket.
Admittedly, ironing isn't anything like the chore it was in the days of
Upstairs Downstairs when big houses employed a full-time laundry maid and there
could be as many as a dozen different irons in the fire to cope with such tasks
as crimping, gauffering, and plaiting, not to mention smoothing out the
master's breakfast newspaper.
But despite the invention of fabrics which should have made irons and ironing
obsolete, there still seems to be a whole lot of repassage going on.
Raymond Trainer is one of an increasing number of people who not only wash
dirty linen for a living but iron it as well.
A former marketing and advertising man, Trainer was a regular customer of the
cunningly named, Glasgow-based company Iron Lady, and likes the service so much
that he decided to buy it. Turnover has more than doubled in recent years with
domestic laundry accounting for around 40% of the current business.
TRAINER says: ``We have 70 regulars who we pick up from and deliver back to
each week. They range from single business people and couples, families where
both partners work, the disabled and elderly - even students who chip in
together to have a bag of 15 items of laundry washed and ironed for #17.75.''
Six women handle the ironing side of the business and one of the perks of being
the owner of the company, Raymond points out, is that you get your own laundry
done for free. ``My wife hasn't picked up an iron for years,'' he added.
Raymond maintains that the industrial, hand-held irons they use provide a
finish which is superior to anything that could be achieved at home with a
domestic appliance.
Even so, for those people who continue to insist that clothes must be pressed
but prefer to do it themselves, there are some irons on the market today which
look as if they could do everything short of actually folding the laundry up
and putting it away in your drawers.
The latest edition of a well-known superstore catalogue includes, among a
selection of three dozen irons, the #128 Ultraglide Elite incorporating
vertical steam facility ``ideal for suits, curtains and delicate items such as
silk on hangers''.
For #79 there's the power injection model with turbo feature and electronic
pump and, at #57.50 there's the chic, black Rowenta Guardian iron which offers
10 levels of variable steam.
And for those people who can't bear to be parted from their irons even when on
holiday, the same catalogue offers a choice of three travelling models which
can be folded up and tucked in beside all your easycare bikinis and T-shirts.
</TEXT>
