<HEADLINE>Playing captain would turn the clock back Kite intends to be on the ball</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<FLAG>golf and golfers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOM Kite, newly appointed as leader of the 1997 US Ryder Cup team who will
attempt to retrieve the bauble from Europe at Valderrama, has indicated his
ambition to do so as the playing captain - a function last fulfilled as long
ago as 1963 by Arnold Palmer.
Perhaps this would be the appropriate moment for the US PGA to introduce a
sanity clause as a condition of their invitation to Kite. For one thing, in
Palmer's day the match was not only no contest. Britain and Ireland, then
alone, were as resistant to defeat as tissue paper to rising damp.
But Kite alone should not be mocked. Severiano Ballesteros also is on record
that if, as is widely expected, he is made Europe's captain for the first match
on this side of the Atlantic to be held outside the United Kingdom, he would be
equally enthusiastic about assuming the dual role.
Now then. Kite is 45 years old. By the lightning surfing of the Internet for
which this computer-driven mind is renowned, by the time he arrives in Spain he
will be two years older. Similarly, Ballesteros, currently 38, will have joined
the ranks of the 40-somethings.
But that is not all. Kite, who has career earnings on the US Tour of some #6m -
second only to Greg Norman, whose arrival in America conveniently coincided
with the escalation of prize-money to stratospheric levels - took 104th place
on this year's money list, his worst finish since 1973, when he turned
professional.
Scarcely to be outdone, although Ballesteros won the Spanish Open last May, the
Spaniard finished No.33 on the European order of merit, his second-worst
position. Ballesteros played in his eighth Ryder Cup match mainly on the
strength of his performances in the late 1994 tournaments. Kite, not
surprisingly, never did make it to Oak Hill.
Ballesteros in in the middle of a five-month respite from the tournament grind
- a decision which, given the sharp decline in his game, may have seemed
justified to him, but whose validity will be proved only after he has returned
to the fray. So prolonged an absence may not prove to be the cure he craves.
The fact is that the state of both their games, by their own high standards,
deserves the dismissive phrase memorably used by a Texas politician to describe
the office of Vice-President of the United States: ``Not worth a bucket of warm
spit.'' By 1997, impending seniority will be closing in on Kite; on
Ballesteros, who knows what.
Kite says: ``The main job of the captain is to make sure the players are as
comfortable and relaxed as they can be, so that they can concentrate on the
golf and not get caught up in the hoop-la that surrounds the match now.'' Quite
so. How, then, can a captain expect to do the equivalent of walk and chew gum
at the same time?
``I will,'' Kite declared, ``consult the last eight American captains to get
the feel of the problems they encountered.'' They were Dave Marr, Jack Nicklaus
(twice), Lee Trevino, Raymond Floyd, Dave Stockton, Tom Watson, and Lanny
Wadkins - all of whom were, of course, non-playing and more than content to
be so.
The last playing captain here - and he led only home countries' sides - was Dai
Rees, who began four successive combinations of the task as long as 40 years
ago. Apart from that rare nugget among the dross, victory at Lindrick in 1957,
the outcome was never less than utterly predictable and consequently the match
was nothing like the stressful occasion that it has become.
Certainly, all a far cry from the third of the 15 Ryder Cup matches this
correspondent has attended. In 1971 players, officials, media, and some few
supporters filed almost apologetically on to the same aircraft at Gatwick for
the journey to St Louis, where the ritual evisceration was duly performed. No
more.
It's all Concorde for the players, and those and such as those, oppressive
organisation, and protection of razor-wire impenetrability round the team
hotel. Brad Faxon, of the American side, wrote of this September's experience:
``In my room all my clothes for the week were laid out on a bed. There was a
day-planner with my name on it.
``Inside was a list of exactly what we had to wear, what we had to do, and
where we had to be every minute of every day. Even my trousers were numbered.
When I got to the Oak Hill club I discovered that each player was allocated
five lockers. Only five?''
Now, the Ryder Cup match has, thankfully, been rescued from certain oblivion to
become a successful occasion, subject to huge media attention, and generating
great financial rewards for the two organising bodies. Therefore, the very idea
of playing captains is laughable and should not be difficult to resist - if
only to protect the incumbents from being consigned to padded cells.
</TEXT>
