<HEADLINE>Leeson ordered to reveal cash-in deals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAILED Nick Leeson was today considering whether to appeal against his
six-and-a-half year sentence.
As the rogue trader was trying to become accustomed to prison life in
Singapore, his London lawyer was said to have been handed a court order to hand
over all documents linked to the collapse of Barings.
Legal sources in Singapore said Stephen Pollard, Leeson's London-based lawyer,
was served with a court order on Saturday requiring him to produce all
documents linked to Baring's #860m collapse. The order was by lawyers for Price
Waterhouse, the liquidators of Baring Futures (Singapore).
The order would allow the liquidators to examine all documents related to
Barings or related to deals made by Leeson, his wife Lisa, or Mr Pollard over
Barings.
The sources said the aim was to gain information, and there was no suggestion
Mr Pollard had acted improperly.
The papers and documents would include any that provide evidence of assets,
contracts, and arrangements entered into by either of the Leesons or their
agents for the sale of any book, television, newspaper, or screen rights, the
sources said.
Media reports have suggested that Leeson's story could form the basis of a film
featuring Hugh Grant.
Leeson recently signed a book deal for #450,000 giving his side of the story
and there have been numerous unconfirmed rumours of other lucrative contracts
with newspapers around the world.
Singapore's white-collar crime bureau, the Commercial Affairs Department of the
Ministry of Finance, has not ruled out further charges against others involved
in Barings.
Leeson, meanwhile, has until a week tomorrow to decide whether to appeal
against the harsher-than-expected sentence handed down by Judge Richard Magnus
in Singapore on Saturday.
A spokeswoman for his Singapore-based lawyer, John Koh, said today: ``There is
no decision on an appeal. At this point, it's too soon.''
There was widespread speculation before his sentencing that Leeson had struck a
plea bargain deal requiring his close co-operation with the prosecuting
authorities in return for a relatively short sentence.
On Saturday, Leeson and his advisers were clearly shocked by the length of the
jail term.
However an appeal is considered unlikely. Leeson would have to demonstrate that
the sentence was ``manifestly excessive'', and he could have received a 14-year
sentence.
Singapore
</TEXT>
