<HEADLINE>New Euro-row looms on veto</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN will find itself on a fresh collision course with Brussels today when
it is singled out as the only hardline defender of the national veto.
Ministers are determined to resist any moves at next year's Inter-Governmental
Conference to extend majority voting and erode Britain's power to say ``no'' to
Europe.
The Government's isolation on the issue will become clear when a draft agenda
for the 1996 Euro-summit is published today.
Meanwhile Tory splits on Europe are set to be reopened when defeated leadership
contender John Redwood launches a campaign to rally businessmen against a
single currency.
He is to publish a pamphlet setting out the arguments against economic and
monetary union (EMU) next week.
</TEXT>
