<TEXT>
THERE is no battle between crofters and windsurfers over access to Crossapol,
Travee, The Maze, Balevoulin, Balephetrish and Gott Bay - six major sailing
areas on Tiree.
The only problem exists at the Green, Comaig, where an ancient right-of-way to
the shore and Comaig harbour has suddenly been gated and fenced.
The problem of erosion of Tiree's coast is centuries old - the main causes
being the wind, the sea, and its tides. Marram grass has helped to secure the
machair's soil but only considerable investment and landscaping can secure the
beaches. Perhaps the ``ambivalent'' local factor and councillor could initiate
a land erosion scheme similar to the successful one at Findhorn on the Moray
Firth.
Windsurfers are undoubtedly putting a considerable sum of money back into the
local economy. This is evident through the improved prosperity on the island.
The high cost of getting to Tiree by ferry from Oban means that a ``cheap''
holiday is out of the the question. Therefore most windsurfers spend at least
10 days on the island necessitating frequent visits to the island's stores.
Tourism is the key to a bright future for Tiree, a future in which crofting and
windsurfing coexist happily in a mutually respectful way within Tiree's unique
environment.
Alasdair T Matheson,
2 Rowan Park, Carrbridge,
Inverness-shire.
</TEXT>
