<HEADLINE>McKean tips Roache for top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS:
JUST before the bell, during the 800 metres at last summer's Scottish track
championships, the unthinkable happened - a young Scot had the temerity to
burst past the leader, Tom McKean, challenging the six-time national champion
to the long run for home. Nearly 300m further on, 19-year-old Des Roache was
still in front and McKean had dropped out, clutching a calf muscle.
Though Roache missed out on a medal, the Clydesdale youngster had shown a
healthy contempt for elders' reputations, perhaps explaining why he collected
the AAA under-20 1500m titles indoor and out, and ended the season as Britain's
top-ranked runner of his age at 800m, 1500m, and the mile.
Yesterday, these credentials won him a #1000 bursary, the biggest of nine made
in a range of sports by Scottish Friendly. And if Roache was a little sheepish,
that was explained by McKean's presence at a ceremony where the teenager, with
a certain inevitablity, was dubbed the next Tom McKean. ``You can't call me the
new McKean,'' dismissed Paisley University student Roache with healthy realism.
``I hope one day I can get to Tom's level. But he has been there and done it.
I've still got to get there, never mind do it.''
McKean himself was generous: ``He's a very talented boy, with a good coach, but
it will depend to some extent on the Scottish public. They are not renowned for
getting behind their athletes. He'll need help, decent sponsorship, or he won't
make it.''
It was the former world and European champion's first public athletics
engagement since failing to make Britain's world championship team earlier this
year. The scars of rejection, not just by Britain, but by Scotland, are still
tender. But do not write McKean's international obituary yet: ``I'm still
training, and very fit - I'm saying no more than that.''
Roache is no stranger to misfortune himself. Clubmates have referred to him as
Mecanno Man, after three metal pins he carries in his right knee, since an
injury curbed promising football talents five years ago.
``The pins have never given me any problem, except that the knee gets a little
stiff in winter. I'll probably be stuck with them and be an arthritic old
man,'' he said.
Roache travelled to the European Junior championships in Hungary this year with
a personal best of 3min. 44.98sec. for 1500m, and high medal hopes.
However, when well placed in a very physical final, two runners behind him
clashed, and one stumbled, raking Roache's right Achilles tendon so badly that
he collapsed.
It was thought to have been ruptured, and he returned home in plaster. Although
he escaped the worst, he was out for seven weeks, missing the rest of the
season.
``It was all very disappointing. It was frustrating to lie there and realise
gold was won in 3-45, and bronze with 3-47.''
He will use the #1000 for altitude training in South Africa this winter, hoping
to win a place in the under-23 Europa Cup.
He is already Britain's fastest over two laps at under-23, and Brian
McAusland's Clydesdale squad, the best men's middle-distance group in the
country, should ensure that he gets the chance to maximise his undoubted
promise. Other Scottish Friendly Assurance bursaries (#250 each):
Lynsey Ann Graham (water-skiing), Bianca Hopkins (trampoline), Sarah, Jenny
Blamire (both table tennis), Gillian Fraser (skiing), Kirsten Dyce (athletics),
Gordon Jamieson (fencing), Kirsti Buchanan (archery).
q KAREN Macleod's Atlanta Olympic hopes may have been blown by a faulty time
clock.
The Scot finished second in Sunday's California Marathon in Sacramento,
credited with 2hr 34min. 23sec., behind the American winner Michaela Reger
(2-32-45).
Maria Trujillo (USA) took third with 2-34-46, while England's Julie Colby was
fourth in 2-38-25.
But times on the finish clock, and on Macleod's own watch, suggest she ran
faster, and if not amended officially, the #2000 prize she collected will be
scant consolation.
Three marathon women will go to the Olympics, and the third quickest UK
contender, US-born Suzanne Rigg, has 2-34-21 to her credit - just two seconds
faster than the Skye woman, who was fourth in last year's Commonwealth Games.
A photograph of her crossing the finishing line, underneath the clock, will be
sent by a US journalist and used in a bid to establish her correct time with
selectors - or at least persuade them she and Rigg should race over the same
course for the third Olympic spot behind Liz McColgan and Marianne Sutton.
</TEXT>
