<HEADLINE>Economically-united leaders seek Major meeting</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE leaders of the largest unionist and nationalist parties in Northern Ireland
are to seek talks with the Prime Minister on the future of the province's
economy.
Ulster Unionist David Trimble and Mr John Hume of the SDLP agreed the move at
the end of a meeting yesterday, which both described as constructive and very
positive.
As the peace process moved in to a new phase following President Clinton's
visit and Mr Major's twin-track agreement with Irish premier John Bruton, the
meeting was the first between the two sides for more than six months and
signalled a determination to move forward together on the economic front.
Although there is SDLP opposition to Unionist proposals to set up some sort of
assembly as a move towards all-party talks on the future of the province, they
are united on what steps are needed to beef up the social and economic
structures in the wake of the terrorist ceasefires.
The two sides are to meet again before Christmas and meantime will press Mr
Major for a meeting.
Both Mr Hume and Mr Trimble were upbeat when they emerged from last night's
talks, at which more new proposals were agreed.
Mr Hume said: ``Enormous international goodwill now exists to this part of the
world and it means we can work together to translate it into real benefits for
our people in terms of inward investment.''
Mr Trimble said the main focus of the discussions was on the economy, though
wider political issues were touched on.
``We have, after an understandable hiatus, resumed meetings and we are
determined, particularly on economic matters, that we shouldn't simply be
reactive and passive and letting the Northern Ireland Office and other people
set the agenda,'' he said.
q The Rev Ian Paisley slammed down the phone to end an Irish radio interview
yesterday after saying he was refusing a talks offer from the Dublin
Government.
The Ulster Democratic Unionist Party leader halted the interview with the
words: ``We will put every obstacle in the way for the south to get their own
way in the north.
``We will resist it, have you got the message? Right, that's good. I'm glad you
have got the message.''
Mr Paisley earlier said he would not answer invitations to discussions from
Ulster Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew and Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring
under the terms of the new twin-track basis for the Northern Ireland peace
process.
q Two men were being questioned last night over an arson bid at a house which
has been attacked 55 times already.
Mr Stephen Lismore claimed police were not doing enough to protect them from
Loyalist paramilitaries whom he claimed were trying to drive them out of the
house at Blacks Road, near Dunmurray, West Belfast.
</TEXT>
