<HEADLINE>France decides to rejoin Nato's military structure as advance guard arrives in former Yugoslavia British troops spearhead  peace mission</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH troops touched down in the former Yugoslavia last night to spearhead a
massive Nato peace-keeping operation.
The huge Nato commitment was given an important boost last night when France
decided to rejoin virtually all the alliance's military structures.
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette was expected to announce the move
today at a rare joint session of alliance Foreign and Defence Ministers,
diplomats said. ``France is essentially coming back in,'' said one delighted
alliance source.
RAF Hercules C-130 transport planes landed in the Bosnian capital Sarajevo and
the Croatian port of Split yesterday, carrying key advance parties and
equipment.
A group of 56 troops from 7 Signals Regiment will set up a communications
network for the headquarters of the Allied Rapid Reaction Corps, which will
command the operation on the ground from Sarajevo.
The RAF's Mobile Air Movements Squadron was flown into Sarajevo to establish a
vital air bridge to the city.
More than 120 staff officers from the ARRC headquarters arrived to prepare the
ground for the arrival of the bulk of the 2500 staff under the command of
Lieutenant General Sir Michael Walker.
Several hundred US soldiers loaded equipment in Mannheim, Germany, ready to
travel by train to Hungary, where a staging post is to be set up for the
20,000-strong American contingent on its way to northern Bosnia.
Over the next 10 days, an ``enabling force'' of more than 2000 troops will
arrive in Bosnia to build up the infrastructure for the 60,000-strong force.
Command of the operation is expected to move from the United Nations to Nato
and Lieutenant General Walker around December 20.
The British signallers, who boarded their aircraft at RAF Bruggen in northern
Germany, were looking forward keenly to the arduous task ahead.
``I'm ready to go, it's my job,'' said Lance Corporal Raymond McGrath.
Most knew the problems they would face, as they had already taken part in
UN-led operations in Bosnia. ``I have a wife and two kids here, it's rough to
be away at Christmas, but it's part of the job,'' said Lance Corporal McGrath.
Nato forces will be given much more robust rules of engagement than the UN,
which will allow troops to open fire first to protect themselves, and will
operate under a single chain of command to remove indecision.
The order for the main force to move will come after the official signing of
the peace accord in Paris next week, and a subsequent meeting of the UN
Security Council.
However, the bulk of the British force, including Challenger tanks and AS90
self-propelled howitzers, will not start to deploy until early January.
The ARRC will have three divisions, commanded separately by Britain, the US,
and France.
France's decision to rejoin Nato's military structure came after intensive
talks between French President Jacques Chirac and US President Bill Clinton.
Paris decided to take up a seat at the alliance's defence planning committee
(DPC) and its military committee.
France left Nato's integrated military structure in 1966.
Nato sources said De Charette, who will make the announcement in the opening
speech today, will stop short of full reintegration, saying Paris would decide
at a later date an ``appropriate role''.
``The fact is that by rejoining the DPC and the military committee, they are
almost as good as there. It is a recognition of the reality,'' said an alliance
souce.
He added the French decision was a shot in the arm for co-operation on the
ground in Bosnia. ``Paris realises that to be part of the game you have to be
in there politically as well as militarily,'' he said.
q An international ``pledging'' conference for donations towards the
reconstruction of Bosnia has been postponed ``because we are nowhere near
knowing what is required'', Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said last night.
A date in early January is now on the cards for the critical stage in the
restoration of peace in the former Yugoslavia - a worldwide gathering, in
Brussels, of countries deciding what they can afford to give towards the
rebuilding of war-torn territories.
Mr Rifkind outlined to his colleagues the details of this week's international
conference in London, which will signal the start of the practical moves to
implement the peace accord.
More than 40 countries and 52 delegations, including the United Nations and the
World Bank, will be at the meeting to establish priorities for putting the
peace plan into operation.
Leader Comment - Page 14
</TEXT>
