<HEADLINE>Murphy child wins ruling</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE US Supreme Court refused yesterday to shield the tabloid newspaper the
National Enquirer from an invasion-of-privacy lawsuit by actor Eddie Murphy's
illegitimate son and the boy's mother.
The justices let stand rulings that a California jury should decide whether the
newspaper report was ``newsworthy'' and therefore unassailable.
The Enquirer reported in 1992 that Murphy and Tamara Hood had a two-year-old
son, Christian Edward Murphy. It reported that Murphy bought a #250,000 house
for the boy and his mother; established a $1m trust for him; and initially sent
Hood child-support payments of #1300 monthly.
Murphy, who previously had denied having any more illegitimate children than a
young girl he had acknowledged fathering, never challenged the article, but
Hood sued.
A state judge threw out her invasion-of-privacy claim, ruling that the Enquirer
had a right to publish the truthful story. However a California appeals court
reversed part of the judge's ruling and reinstated part of the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
