<HEADLINE>Forsyth accused of `talking up the Nationalist vote'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044645</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday accused Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth of ``fanning the
flames of separatism to save his own political skin'' as the row raged over his
comment that Britain could face break-up by the year 2002.
Mr Forsyth last night returned the taunt with interest, accusing his opponents
of a ``shoddy, personal attack,'' and claiming that Labour policies offered
victory via the back door to nationalists who could not win the argument for
separatism ``in a straight and honest fight.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond remained sanguine, claiming it was his party which now
was dictating the political and constitutional debate in Scotland, while
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said that only the ``unholy
alliance'' of Tories and Nationalists would break up the UK.
Mr Forsyth had remarked on weekend television: ``It may well be that by 2002
we'll be looking at an independent Scotland'' - a remark which echoed the Prime
Minister's recent observation that an independent Scotland would be ``viable.''
The Scottish Secretary's words had been seized on with glee by the SNP and
regarded with something approaching horror by Shadow Scottish Secretary George
Robertson, who consistently has proclaimed himself a Unionist who believes that
only devolution can halt the demands for separatism.
Mr Robertson yesterday narrowed the focus of his attack by linking the comments
explicitly to Mr Forsyth's efforts to save his highly marginal Stirling seat at
the next General Election.
He wrote to the Scottish Secretary saying he was ``appalled'' to see him
``playing fast and loose with the Union in what was obviously a desperate
attempt to talk up the Nationalist vote.''
He added: ``As you are well aware, a slight last-minute surge in the
Nationalist vote at the last election was the only thing that prevented the
Labour Party candidate from taking your Stirling seat.''
Mr Robertson claimed that, with Tory poll levels plummeting in Scotland, Mr
Forsyth had calculated that the only way of saving his political career was to
talk up the SNP to split the anti-Tory vote.
He wrote: ``You are obviously resigned to your party's defeat, but are prepared
to fan the flames of separatism in order to save your own political skin.''
Claiming that Labour would never do anything to jeopardise the Union, Mr
Robertson said: ``To stoke the fires of nationalism with these crude
frighteners not only debases the office of Secretary of State - it threatens
the very future of the Union himself.''
However, Mr Forsyth said last night: ``It is Labour's foolish proposals which
would saddle Scotland with a tartan tax and put our caring services in
jeopardy, as their funding would continue to be determined at Westminster,
where our voice would be diminished. These proposals are what threaten the
break-up of Britain.
``The Nationalists cannot win the argument for separation in a straight and
honest fight, but Labour has created an opportunity for this by the back door,
following the acrimony and dissension which their ill-thought-out proposals
would provoke.
``I did not invent the tartan tax. George Robertson did. Anyone who aspires to
hold the important office of Secretary of State for Scotland should be capable
of defending their policies without indulging in shoddy, personal attack.
``This is a battle for Britain and for Scotland's place in it. It is high time
Mr Robertson realised what is at stake.''
Mr Salmond said: ``Every time the Scottish constitution is discussed, the
independence option emerges ever stronger. The Labour and Tory parties sought
to marginalise the SNP on St Andrew's Day, but all they achieved was to show
how their Unionism unites them.''
While Labour said only devolution could save the Union, the Tories said
devolution would hasten the onset of independence. Mr Salmond said voters would
react by short-cutting this and voting for the SNP.
For the Scottish Liberal Democrats, Mr Jim Wallace said: The only thing that
will lead to the break-up of the UK is the unholy alliance currently being
forged by Michael Forsyth and Alex Salmond. But however much the Nationalists
and Tories may work together, this will not alter the fact that the majority of
Scots want their own parliament within the UK.''
</TEXT>
