<HEADLINE>The prospect of nationhood</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044646</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORMAN Hogg may possibly be aware of the fact that for over 100 years the
Labour Party has had a policy for a Scottish Assembly.
Given that after all this time his own party is only now setting out its stall
as to how this assembly should operate, it is rather churlish of him to
criticise the SNP for placing its vision of an independent Scottish parliament
before the people after 61 years (November 28).
The SNP vision of a real Scottish parliament has of course been a matter of
record for many years. The fact that the party chose St Andrew's Day to launch
its vision has obviously upset Mr Hogg greatly.
His display of sour grapes may indicate that he is worried that some people in
Scotland may draw comparison between what Labour is offering compared to the
SNP.
Using a footballing analogy, the SNP is offering Scotland a chance to play
among the elite of Europe. The Labour Party believes that the Scottish people
do not deserve to be given this status.
The prospect of nationhood for Scotland dwarfs any Labour/Tory contest about
who is going to rule in the UK for the next four or five years. The past may
belong to Labour in Scotland but the future belongs to the Scottish people
being represented independently inside the European Community.
Jim Finlayson,
26 King Street,
Newport-on-Tay.
</TEXT>
