<TEXT>
IA SCOTTISH Office spokesman is quoted (November 27) as saying that no
objection to the proposed Skye Bridge toll regime was made at the local public
inquiry held in January 1992.
This is hardly the truth. The bridge Order had by that time been signed, but
there were very strong objections made to the charging of tolls. Sixteen out of
20 community councils were totally opposed to tolls of any kind, and three of
the four others accepted a minimum toll regime reluctantly, as did the district
council.
A petition with over 7500 signatures, out of a Skye population of then under
10,000, was collected against the proposed tolls.
Highland Regional Council expressed its disquiet over the proposed tolls, and
even the Government's own appointed recorder at this inquiry said the tolls
were too high and should be reduced.
As usual the Scottish Office chose not to listen to local people, but continued
to say it was consulting locally. Can we have an assurance that it will listen
to the new Highland Council?
Councillor Gavin Scott Moncrieff,
Dun Flodigarry,
Staffin, Isle of Skye.
</TEXT>
