<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Keeping peace in Bosnia Doubts over American presence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044648</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 60,000 alliance-led troops who intend to keep the peace in Bosnia have
several significant advantages over their hapless predecessors who arrived
under the flag of the United Nations. Most importantly, they actually have a
peace to keep, at least for the moment. The crucial error of the United Nations
leadership was to imagine that it could in some way impose a peace as well as
keeping one. This lunatic idea was given flesh by Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali in a report to the summit meeting of the Security Council in
January 1992. Boutros-Ghali even suggested the formation of peace-enforcement
units under his command, an idea which senior figures in Washington could not
tolerate. The United States will supply a significant part of the new
peacekeeping force and while this is welcome as a sign that the efforts of the
Western alliance may now acquire some coherence, there are enough doubts
lingering over the American presence to cause concern.
President Clinton has made clear his own determination that US troops must be
involved in the peacekeeping process. He is right to say that it is not
logically or morally consistent for the United States to have made the peace
and then to withdraw and let allies police it. To allay fears back home he has
laid down ground rules which ensure that if his troops are attacked they will
respond with overwhelming force. That might make the civilians feel more
content, but skilled troops determined to press home an attack can cause
considerable damage and many casualties before they succumb to that
overwhelming force. Nor is President Clinton absolutely clear on the length of
time that US troops will spend in Bosnia. The objective is to withdraw the
troops within a year which, as many people have noted, may have some connection
with the presidential election.
These issues should not be seen as carping. President Clinton knows perfectly
well that he has managed the peace negotiations with aplomb and deserves credit
for the achievement. He knows equally well that opinion polls show a majority
of Americans opposed to sending American troops to Bosnia and that any hint of
a repetition of the events in Somalia could devastate his chances of
re-election. He is taking a principled risk and, in essence, that is what the
leadership of the United States should be about. In that context the problems
of his Republican opponents are thoroughly deserved. Senator Dole and his
cronies are in the exquisitely difficult position of opposing the deployment of
troops but finding it impossible to press home their position for fear of being
seen to deny support to the troops who will go to Bosnia. They have recovered
their position a little by drafting strict controls on the deployment but
nothing they can do will disguise the faintly nauseating nature of their
unprincipled isolationism.
Aside from military matters, the vital task of the alliance, but particularly
of the Americans, is to make Serbia's president, the unappealing Slobodan
Milosevic, honour his commitments to the peace agreement. In essence this means
that Milosevic must be pressured by all means available to force his Bosnian
Serb allies to abide by the terms of the Dayton agreement. If he does not do
this he should be told bluntly that sanctions will stay in place against his
regime. The Bosnian and Croatian parties to the agreement should also be told
firmly that they must adhere to Dayton, or else. This is not a time for
delicate niceties; too much is at stake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
