<HEADLINE>For sale: a little piece of England</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Stone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044649</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As Forte's share of the Savoy goes up for grabs, Chris Stone reflects on the
hotel's snob value
AFTERNOON tea at the Savoy does not seem to have quite the same ring to it as
the Ritz and, indeed, the latter is pricier at #17.50 against the Savoy's
#15.95 and it is often necessary to book further in advance. But the tea is of
equal quality and has remained so even after the Fortes effectively took over
the running of the show after fierce opposition from the old guard D'Oyle Carte
family loyalists led by Sir Hugh Wontner.
He served for more than 50 years until his death as chairman in 1992 and
famously saw off a hostile takeover bid in 1953 by Mr Charles Clore, a famous
retailing magnate of the time, and Mr Harold Samuel, then chairman of Land
Securities property company.
Another Savoy stalwart was old Etonian former managing director Giles Shepard
who remarked of Forte when it was attempting to take control of the hotel,
``the stewardship of the Savoy could not be entrusted to a vast combine which,
among other things, runs service stations on the main arterial roads''. The
somewhat sneering and, one has to say, snobbish approach to Lord Forte and his
son Rocco by the Savoy establishment could hardly have been more eloquently
expressed.
Forte, in fact, never did gain full control of the Savoy Group (which takes
three other hotels, Claridges, Connaught and the Berkeley); the two-tier share
structure introduced by Wontner saw to that. But it did gain 68% of the shares,
if only 42% of the votes, enough to considerably expand its role and dictate
the running of the group.
Now, Forte, under bid pressure itself from Granada, is putting its share stake
up for sale, a quite extraordinary move when one considers that it took a
13-year battle from 1981 for it to reach the influential position it now holds,
even if full control still eluded it. Lord Forte, who proposed to his wife in
the Savoy and spent part of his honeymoon there, will have to bite the bullet,
though, in these perhaps more pragmatic times.
It was felt, again by the establishment, and no doubt by some of the regular
customers, that the appointment of Ramon Pajares as managing director of the
hotel group, the first foreign MD in the hotel's history, would mean the
lowering of standards and an undermining of the hotel's reputation in a
relentless search for profits.
He, though, insisted that he would improve the standards but at the same time
cut out wastage. The old guard would have argued that with a hotel like the
Savoy, shareholders were not primarily interested in making money but in
sharing in its traditional and historic ways.
There have been changes, some of which would undoubtedly have brought
disapproving sniffs from Sir Hugh Wontner and perhaps the D'Oyle Carte family.
The hotel was created in 1889 by Richard D'Oyle Carte, the legendary
impresario, as a result of the success of his Gilbert and Sullivan operas.
Changes include the closing of the group's purchasing departments for meat and
vegetables. The centralised wine-buying operation has also gone, including the
departure of Mr Giles Townsend, the wine buyer and son of Group Captain Peter
Townsend. The Savoy's in-house printing operation has also been shut.
These changes, it has to be said, do not appear on the surface at any rate to
have caused any damage to the Savoy or deterred its clientele which tends to
stay loyal.
The American Bar, the famous Grill Room, as well as the River Restaurant
continue to attract their regular customers. Nor has the Savoy become any less
what some people might regard as stuffy and others traditional. There still has
to be a certain amount of dress decorum, and paying in cash, at least in some
parts of the hotel is considered distinctly infra dig. One famous City
journalist, years ago, upon leaving the Grill room was reputed always to get
the head waiter to sign for him.
The Savoy is very much a hotel for business occasions. It always was and places
such as the substantial River Room, the Beaufort and seven private rooms named
after Gilbert and Sullivan operas, accommodate from six to 100 guests.
And the Savoy can certainly boast that it has played and continues to play host
to film stars and celebrities generally. There was an occasion when this
particular journalist was sorely tempted to forget an especially stuffy
business conference and head off instead to interview Shirley Maclaine to whom
a kind and thoughtful member of the staff had directed me.
Another time, an excited visitor ran up to the actor holding court in the
foyer, screaming ``Peter O'Toole!''. Richard Harris did not try to dissuade
her. The American actress Elaine Stritch was so enamoured of the Savoy she
lived there for many years, presumably on reduced terms.
certainly a new broom is sweeping through the hotel but not neccessarily to its
detriment though only time will tell whether all the changes are positive. In
the meantime various deals are on offer for those who have the inclination and
can afford it and can include dinner and dancing in the River Restaurant or
pre-theatre supper in the Savoy Grill at #330 for two on the first night and
#240 for each additional night.
It is not quite like the early days of grandeur which included the flooding of
a courtyard for a party given by champagne millionaire George Kessler with
Caruso singing from a gondola, later transformed into a beautiful ballroom
where Pavlova danced. But the Savoy remains essentially the Savoy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A pinch of salt with the promise of politicians</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Hume</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044650</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT since the late President John F Kennedy came out and clarified much which
had previously puzzled by walking tall at the Brandenberg Gate and admitting to
startled Germans ``Ich bin ein Berliner'' - a type of doughy bread roll, the
Prussian equivalent of the bap - have I winced so much for an American on the
make.
Few have the talent to sell a heavily clocked old banger with panache and make
the victim feel privileged to be stuck with the wreckage and politicians are
not to be counted among their number. Best advice for them is ``don't give up
your day job'' and stay away from the used-car lot.
Alas, few do and thus, exposed these past few days to retread rhetoric,
clapped-out policies, and dangerously loose thinking toshed up as this year's
chrome-plated winner, my toes have curled so tight they may never unfurl.
The cringe factor was triggered when President Bill Clinton told the
inhabitants of the Republican capital: ``I feel like a real `Dub' today.''
Voters in America with Irish connections, please note. ``A real Dub''.
As also, please note, those synagogue goers who might bolster his chances of a
second term in the White House after seeing their President wearing a yamulka
at the funeral of Yitzhak Rabin. Pay attention to those with only a slender
grasp of life's verities who applauded his thinly veiled ``whop ass''
admonition to American troops setting off for Bosnia. They, too, now know where
to put their cross on the ballot paper without counting the cost of the body
bags.
Such behaviour as we have seen recently from Whitewater's ``boy most likely to
succeed'' is, I imagine, no more calculated to raise a laugh or give offence
than is the long-established habit of American film makers to flag the obvious
for those contributing to their box office receipts who may have spent their
most taxing school days at the back of the class doing arcane things with
raffia.
I refer to that strange Hollywood addiction to splash every film sound-track
with cue music...... a Brigadoon skirl when a Scot walks into frame, a
rollicking Left Bank squeeze of the accordion when a Frenchman appears centre
right, and so on.
What fascinates as much as it repels is the sheer crass lack of sensitivity to
others' sensibilities. If it is Tuesday it must be Germany therefore lederhosen
and who gives a sauerkraut if you pulled them on with the wee flap at the back.
New World naivety can be charming, home-spun grits and beans manners in the
style of The Waltons bringing a sympathetic smile to the face of even the most
cynical in much the way that a pyjama-clad, sleepy eyed tot will be indulged
when he strays into a dinner party and asks if the fat man with the red face
sitting next to his mother is likely to explode.
But Presidents should know better. And so should we. In all the best westerns
the cavalry comes to the rescue, the renegades are routed, and the good guy and
his gal ride into the sunset with the benign blessing of John Wayne...... all
passion, and ammunition, spent. But real life does not come in two reels with a
Cornetto in between.
Real life is intractable political and budgetary problems at home, plus Newt
Gingrich giving you a bad time, thus the imperatives of survival represented on
the world stage as the beacon of world peace. I have visited too many war
graves - yes, in the Falklands too - to buy that crock of selfless service.
The image may be ``as seen on TV'' but we do not have to buy. The revved-up
promise of politicians, especially Presidents and Prime Ministers, should be
taken with a pinch of salt, the small print checked, the bargain beneath the
Simoniz closely scrutinised for rust, dents, and filler.
Why, given their common line with tradesmen who assure that their intervention
is necessary solely because of the botched job of the chap who went before, do
we pay any attention to politicians?
Why, even yet, do we not tell them that they have been rumbled, the game's a
bogey, and that we know their power broking has ephemera as its stock in trade?
Perhaps we are, after all, suckers for salesmen...... even those from whom we
would not buy a used car.
More people in this country now play the National Lottery than intend to vote
at the next General Election. Could it be they believe that with the lottery
they have at least a chance, however slender.
The low level of public esteem in which politicians have for some time been
held - be they the late bread roll, the incumbent ``Dub'', our very own
soap-box orator from Brick Lane, the entire Italian Cabinet or assorted EC
finaglers - does not augur well for a healthy political future. How can it all
have come about?
Meantime, not yet at the front line of joined-up political thought but already
big on fearless self exposure, with the Irish problem sorted, Bosnia done and
dusted, the Middle East no longer problematic and Spain brought on side, where
next for Bill Clinton to slay dragons?
Clearly, given the traditional flexibility of presidential genealogy, he is
unlikely to shrink from claiming kinship with the troubled French, pressing the
flesh in Paris, and telling them: ``I feel like a real Gauloises today.'' He
might be offered a light, perhaps win a few votes back home on Walton Mountain.
But should we care?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
