<HEADLINE>Rabin widow may go into politics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JEFFREY HELLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044651</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jerusalem
THE widow of assassinated Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin held open the
possibility today that she would embark on a political career.
``I am not saying yes and I am not saying no at this stage,'' said Leah Rabin,
67, in a television interview.
``I hear about it everywhere,'' she said about speculation she might run for
office. ``It seems to me everything is still terribly fresh and painful and it
is not the time to deal with what will happen later.''
Public debate on the issue was touched off by her daughter Dalia Ben-Artzi
Philosof, who said her mother had the qualifications to be a leader in her own
right.
Such talk, Mrs Rabin said, ``embarrasses me very much'', although she thanked
her daughter for the thought.
After the assassination Mrs Rabin was outspoken in her criticism of the Israeli
right wing, which she accused of fostering an atmosphere of hate that led to
the killing by a religious Jew.
In the interview, a month to the day after her husband was killed, Mrs Rabin
said she could not shake the memory of his final moments as they left a Tel
Aviv peace rally.
``It is as if I pushed the pause button on the video and I see the same
picture, which always appears before my eyes. I am walking down the stairs,
just as we did, happy and filled with satisfaction and joy at what had happened
at the rally a few minutes earlier.
``Now there are three shots and I see him fall - and they told me it wasn't
real,'' she said, referring to the initial confusion after the shooting.
``In retrospect, I know that at that moment he was almost clinically dead. This
picture does not leave my eyes.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
