<HEADLINE>Stepping out on the road to recovery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen Mother left hospital yesterday, 18 days after her hip operation.
The 95-year-old looked in good health as she walked with sticks from the King
Edward VII Hospital for Officers in London's Marylebone.
She was wearing a royal blue dress suit with matching jacket and floral trim.
She smiled and waved at photographers from the steps of the hospital,
accompanied by a matron and a nurse who later presented her with a posy of
yellow flowers.
She then stepped, without help, into a black and brown Daimler, waving to
onlookers as the car left for Clarence House accompanied by her lady in
waiting, Lady Margaret Colville.
A Clarence House spokeswoman said: ``She is very well.''
The Queen Mother was last seen in public at the Ritz Hotel last month, hours
before being admitted to hospital for the operation to replace her right hip.
At her last public engagement at the Royal British Legion festival of
remembrance service, she was able to walk only a few yards with the aid of two
sticks.
A Buckingham Palace spokesman said yesterday: ``She has made satisfactory
progress and is being allowed home.''
She has no public engagements in her diary and is not expected to be seen in
public again until the royal family gathers at Sandringham for Christmas.
It is hoped that she will be able to attend the Christmas Day church service.
She will need continual care and exercise, and to keep mobile for her hip fully
to recover.
</TEXT>
