<HEADLINE>Kirsty Scott examines calls for a cut in the drinks-driving limit as the Government unveils its festive campaign `One for the road' row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044653</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER festive season, another gritty drink-driving advert, but as the
Government unveils its latest PR ploy to reduce alcohol-related accidents, it
is still cold-shouldering a growing clamour for legislative change.
This week, those at the sharp and often bloody end of the debate - the police
and medical officials - have called for a near halving of the legal drinking
limit from 80 milligrammes of alcohol per 100 millilitres of blood to 50
milligrammes.
It's the first time they've come out with such a clear-cut call and it comes on
top of stronger evidence that even a small amount of alcohol impairs ability,
and a growing public perception that drink-driving is a social evil.
But the Government has refused to budge. Today it takes the wraps of its new
Christmas anti-drink-drive campaign, a day after Transport Minister Steven
Norris insisted the existing limit worked and was palatable for the public.
Department of Transport officials repeated the same line yesterday. ``First and
foremost, the only safe level is zero,'' said a DoT spokesman. ``Our position
has been for many years, don't drink and drive and we have been extremely
successful over the years with our campaigns in changing people's attitudes.
Most people in the UK now agree that drink-driving is socially unacceptable . .
. but we don't want to risk losing public support if the public perceives the
50mg limit as being too low.''
But there are some in the medical profession who believe now is the right time
to take advantage of the public's distaste for drink-driving and tighten
restrictions. They point to studies which show that drivers' reactions are
impaired by up to 20% for two hours after drinking, even though their
bloodstream levels were below the current legal limit.
Dr Keith Little, a consultant in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary's accident and
emergency department who deals with the aftermath of drink-driving accidents,
believes the Government has the ideal opportunity to crack down on
drink-driving.
``Things have improved progressively and there has been a change in attitude
out in the community, but we still have a significant number of people involved
in road accidents who have been drinking and driving.
``We would like a nil level but we realise that that is not practicable. Any
reduction would be desirable to try to utilise the public's changing attitudes,
something like half of the current level. I think the public would be ready to
accept that.''
But the DoT remains resistant to such ideas. ``Public perception is the key to
this being a successful campaign,'' said the DoT spokesman. ``What we don't
want to do is risk that level of public support by changing to a limit which is
not necessarily justified. We're not convinced the support would be there. The
thing that matters here is those being hurt and killed on the roads, and only
2.5% of drink-driving accidents involve levels of 50mg to 80mg.''
The British Medical Association, in calling on the Government to reduce the
limit from 80mg to 50mg, pointed to the rest of Europe, where many countries
have taken a stricter stance. France, Belgium, Finland, the Netherlands,
Norway, and Portugal have 50mg limits; Sweden and Poland meanwhile have a 20mg
limit; and the limit in Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, and Romania is zero.
A Scottish spokeswoman for the BMA said she felt the time was right to apply
added pressure for change, but the BMA was not confident of being able to shift
the Government. ``As with tobacco, you're up against vested interests aren't
you?''
The Automobile Association has said its position is a little difficult because
it believes a lowering of the limit would overstretch police resources, but it
acknowledges that the police and public see lowering the limit as a positive
step.
Dr Little, meanwhile, won't need to watch the launch of the new Government
advert today to get an idea of the impact of an alcohol-related accident. He
sees enough of it on a regular basis.
``Like the 18-year-old drunk driver who bent down to pick up a can of beer
which had spilled in the car and lost control of the vehicle, killing his
friend who was in the passenger seat,'' he said. ``Or the individual with five
other people in the car who drove straight into a tree at 60mph to 70mph. Or
the five-year-old girl brain-damaged for life by the drunk driver who left the
road and struck her full on as she walked along the pavement. So it goes. It's
just endless.''
</TEXT>
