<HEADLINE>Eight school projects passed on by region</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EIGHT school projects worth nearly #9m are being passed to new unitary
authorities by Strathclyde region, because it does not have time to make the
necessary legal commitments before it is abolished on April 1 under local
government reorganisation.
The projects, including a long-awaited #2m upgrading at Oban High School, were
the cause of concern to local members at yesterday's private meeting of the
region's Labour group.
Some fear projects in their areas could fall by the wayside as unitary
authorities grapple with acute financial crises in their early days of
operational existence.
Other projects on the list are:
q.Rockfield Primary, Oban, dining hall extension - #640,000;
q.Notre Dame R.C Secondary, Glasgow, extension - just over #1m;
q.Glasgow secondary schools' science laboratories upgrading - #600,000;
q.Our Lady of the Annunciation and St Mirin's R.C Primaries, Glasgow, upgrading
- #1.2m;
q.Harthill/Benhar Primary School, Lanarkshire, replacement - #1.85m;
q.Tinto Primary School, Lanarkshire, extension - #300,000;
q.St Bride's R.C High School, East Kilbride, upgrading - #1.22m.
The Labour leader, Councillor Robert Gould, explained: ``We can't legally
commit these projects in the time available. These will be left to the
succeeding authorities to deal with.''
According to a senior council official, all eight would continue to be
developed in terms of preparing drawings, tendering documents, and acquiring
sites.
But a council source warned that Scottish Office plans to provide block capital
allocations to councils rather than to individual services made it more
difficult to confirm that any particular project in education would get
precedence over, say, a project in social work.
The source added: ``Councils might not only face competition from other
authorities for resources, they might also be competing with other services
within their own authority.''
Meanwhile Labour councillors have agreed to go out to consultaion on the
proposed closure of Garthamlock Secondary School, Glasgow, which is less than
40% full and needs #780,000 of urgent repairs following a fire in May.
They also agreed to invite the Greater Easterhouse Redevelopment Company to be
part of that consultation.
</TEXT>
