<HEADLINE>Norman now knows score</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGLAS LOWE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044655</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SEVE Ballesteros, as a brash youth of 17, once gave voice to his opinion the
night before the first round of the Spanish Open at La Manga that it was
impossible for a professional golfer to score in double figures at a single
hole. His audience recoiled in horror at this tempting of the fates and, as
they suspected, it was not long before he had to eat his words.
At the ninth the next day he ran up an 11, having been out of bounds twice,
later finding water and then sand.
Greg Norman is the latest to discover that, in his own words: ``Golf is a very
humbling game.'' At the weekend he, too, scored an 11, at the fourteenth of The
Lakes course in Sydney in the third round of his own Greg Norman Classic,
having hit four shots into water from the same spot.
There is a kind of perverse pleasure in knowing that the world No.1 is capable
of descending briefly into the domain of the hacker. It would be more true to
say that we empathise. We know all about the bushes, trees, ditches, and
waist-high rough that lie in wait, especially for those who have just thought
they have cracked the game at last. The golfing gods know, you know.
My favourite source of comfort after such harsh lessons in reality is to dip
into Chris Plumridge's ``Book of Golf Disasters and Bizarre Records''. There,
in addition to the Seve story, you will find that the highest known score at a
single hole is 166. It is a barely believable tale of supreme idiocy.
Those who recorded this performance by an American woman in 1912 on the
sixteenth at Shawnee Country Club were kind enough to omit her name, though
there was a saving grace. The competition was a qualifier with the same number
of entrants as qualifying places so all she had to do to succeed was to post a
score, any score.
The ball she was using, it seems, was capable of floating and when it went into
a large water hazard from her tee-shot, she commandeered a boat and played most
of her shots from the vessel before finally moving the ball on to dry land. Why
she never took a penalty drop is not recorded.
That particular course also claimed the record for the highest score by a
professional, as recorded in the Golfer's Handbook, in the 1927 Shawnee Open.
At the seventeenth, Tommy Armour, who had won the US Open the week before, lost
count of the number of balls he hooked out of bounds and thought it might have
been a 21, but he erred on the safe side and called it a 23.
There were a few quiet disasters in this year's Open Championship at St
Andrews, most memorably Jack Nicklaus's 10 at the fourteenth.
The official annual of the tournament is just published and at the back you
will find hole-by-hole scores of every competitor. The eclectic worst at each
hole over the four days by the 159 players came to 123, or 51 over par.
</TEXT>
