<HEADLINE>Expedition wins new look at shipwreck</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044656</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #2m expedition to re-examine the wreck of the biggest British vessel lost at
sea was announced by the Government yesterday.
The expedition should clear up the 15-year-old mystery of the Teesside-built
bulk carrier MV Derbyshire, which went down in a typhoon off Japan in 1980 with
the loss of its British crew of 42 and two wives.
The decision follows a report on the Derbyshire from former Master of the
Rolls, Lord Donaldson.
``I have concluded that the likely cost of such an examination, although large,
is fully justified in the light of the potential benefits to ship safety,''
said Lord Donaldson in his report.
An official inquiry into the disaster in 1987 said the weather was probably to
blame but families of the crew, trade unions, and shipping experts have long
argued that the disaster was caused by structural defects.
Lord Donaldson was asked to make a fresh assessment following a #380,000
union-financed expedition which located and photographed the ship's wreck last
year.
Describing the loss of the Derbyshire as ``one of the great unsolved mysteries
of the sea'', Lord Donaldson said the case for a fresh expedition was ``not
only made out but is compelling''.
Transport Secretary Sir George Young said the European Commission had agreed to
share the cost of the expedition, although he added that Lord Donaldson had
been so persuasive that the UK Government would have stood the cost alone if it
had had to.
#2m inquiry - Page 5
</TEXT>
