<HEADLINE>Danger signals for divers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan MacDermid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alan MacDermid reports on a new hospital lifeline
for underwater casualties
Divers are in danger of being lured to their deaths by the siren call of the
computer. They wear them on their wrists, like a jumbo-sized digital watch, and
they are programmed to tell a diver how much time he has left down below, to
the second.
This slavish regard for accuracy may be one reason, says a West Highland
doctor, why Scotland's newest hospital has established itself in a few short
months as one of the busiest treatment centres in Britain for divers with the
bends.
The wrecks along the west coast are a magnet for amateur divers from all over
the UK, but since March nearly two dozen of them have also sampled the delights
the Lorn and Islands Hospital in Oban.
Their first port of call was the recompression chamber at Dunstaffnage Marine
Research Laboratory on the other side of town, after which the majority would
go on to spend a day or two convalescing at the hospital, sometimes returning
to the chamber for a repeat procedure.
The symptoms, which vary in severity - from itching and joint pains to
paralysis - are caused by gas bubbles accumulating in the diver's tissues as a
result of the hyperbaric pressures of the deep. Too rapid an ascent causes the
bubbles to expand before the diver's system has had time to clear them.
Their treatment is undertaken by Dr Gordon Murchison and Dr Colin Wilson, two
local GPs who also work as anaesthetists at the hospital and have made a
specialty of diving medicine.
Every self-respecting diver now wears one of the new generation of computers on
his or her wrist. Costing several hundred pounds, they can be programmed
through desk-top PCs from tables which correlate air use, depth, time, gas
mixture. The most sophisticated will monitor the diver's exertion rate and feed
it into the time-left information that can be called up at the touch of a
button. Afterwards the data can be downloaded into the PC to keep a detailed
log of each dive.
To listen to these specifications is to wonder how divers managed before
computers came along. For some, though, it is perhaps all too simple. Dr
Murchison said: ``The number of divers we are treating has gone up and up with
the use of these computers. A lot of them are using algorithmic tables which
have not been proven in practice.
``More and more fancy equipment and not enough expertise and training are
leading some of these people into trouble. Because they are so precise divers
maybe put too much reliance on them, using up all the time they have been
quoted, whereas divers working out times for themselves using traditional
tables might come up with, say, 55 minutes, and stay down for 50, allowing a
margin for something going wrong.''
The outcome of these events, Dr Murchison notes, is added expense for the NHS -
though at local level it is perhaps more of a money-spinner than a burden.
Jonathan Best, chief executive of the Argyll and Bute NHS Trust, which runs the
new hospital, pointed out: ``Most of the divers are from down south, so they
are treated as extra-contractual referrals. That means we bill the patient's
host health authority - #750 a night for observation only, and #1300 per case
if there is treatment involved.''
Divers, however, are not the only business the rest of Britain sends to his
door.
``Our busy time is in the summer months, when the population multiplies
threefold,'' said consultant physician Dr Allan Henderson, a Londoner who came
to Oban last year.
Among the more exotic cases he recalls was one of swordfish poisoning, which
causes vomiting, diarrhoea, intense flushing and collapse (in the patient, not
the swordfish).
``It had been imported and gone off. Apparently it builds up a lot of
histamine,'' said Dr Henderson. The bad news for the restaurant concerned is
that the patient was a Glasgow solicitor.
For local people, though, the #16.5m hospital is an asset they have awaited for
39 years, replacing five old hospitals on separate sites. It is currently a
two-week home-from-home for Mrs Jean Graham, 35, headmistress of the village
school at Minard, near Inveraray.
She has been receiving respite care after being diagnosed in March last year as
having multiple sclerosis. She is remarkably cheerful, given such a cruel blow,
but clearly misses her husband, her little boy, Gordon, aged three, whose
photograph sits by her bedside, and the other 22 children in her charge at
Minard.
</TEXT>
