<HEADLINE>Siberian blast cuts snow odds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044659</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S time to look out the long johns and the thermal vests again. After one of
the mildest autumns this century, weather forecasters last night gave warning
that snow, frost, and bitter winds from Siberia will start arriving today.
Eastern areas of Scotland and England will be hit first, with anything from a
mild dusting to ``significant accumulations of snow on the hills''.
A spokesman for the Glasgow Weather Centre said the east coast of Scotland
would get biting winds developing during the day. ``It looks like the cold air
will hit the west by the end of Tuesday. We will be shivering for the rest of
the week.
``Overnight the temperatures will drop to -1C or -2C with the wind coming
straight from Siberia.
``It is going to feel bitterly cold.''
The big chill is likely to continue all this week and bookmakers William Hill
have cut the odds on a White Christmas from 10-1 to 8-1 after a string of
punters laid bets.
British Rail, which was caught out in 1991 with the ``wrong kind of snow'', is
confident that it will cope with any weather problems this week.
European-style powdery snow brought the network to a near standstill in
February 1991, with BR chiefs saying that they were more used to the slushy
``British'' snow.
Railtrack said it had a plan to make sure the points remained operational,
using points heaters which automatically come on in low temperatures.
As an extra precaution, staff would be checking the points in forecast ``cold
spots'' to ensure all was well.
A spokesman said: ``We also have de-icing trains and snow ploughs standing by.
``We will certainly do our very best to keep services              running.''
The RAC warned motorists not to get caught out. A spokeswoman said half of the
three million breakdowns attended by the organisation last year could have been
avoided through regular servicing and maintenance of cars.
``It's the first icy blast of winter which catches many motorists out but
forward planning can help keep the wheels turning in the cold,'' she said.
The RAC is urging drivers to check anti-freeze, wiper blades, batteries, and
tyre pressures, to listen to weather forecasts, and to slow down.
</TEXT>
