<HEADLINE>Margaret Vaughan looks on as the Tories fight openly among themselves over the very soul of their party French lesson prompts Clarke to raise stakes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Magaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044660</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUTRAGE is spreading in France at plans to push through radical welfare reform.
A wave of strikes has already broken across the country. Right-wing Prime
Minister Alain Juppe has staked his credibility on social security reforms
which he claims are needed to allow France to meet conditions for European
monetary union in 1999.
The strikers' grievances spread into the private sector. The country, now in
crisis, is close to paralysis.
Aides say the Government wants talks with union leaders but will not compromise
in its aim to get rid of the welfare deficit of almost #8000m a year. The trade
unions, despite being riven by rivalry, are determined to wreck government
plans which include social security cuts, lower pensions, cuts in the rail
network, and privatisation of telecommunications.
When even the Gaullist newspapers are stirred to draw extravagant parallels
between the current turmoil and such fateful dates as the French Revolution of
1789 and the 1968 uprising of students and workers, it is clear that the
proposed radical overhaul of France's welfare state has tweaked a touchy nerve.
The demand for a sacrifice may jeopardise the survival of M Juppe's Government.
If there is a political lesson for Britain in the current chaos across the
Channel, then it will be drawn from two separate strands of the argument that
has propelled the country into turmoil. For both right and left wings of
Britain's Conservative Party may draw parallels to suit their case.
Yesterday the manoeuvring for control within the party broke the surface. The
fierce internal row over the Conservative election manifesto, and the fight for
the soul of the party, emerged into public view.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke is heading a campaign to prevent any further moves to
the right over Europe and any further erosion of the welfare state.
John Redwood, meanwhile, the right's leader-in-waiting, signalled his intention
to break the fragile truce on Europe by mounting a campaign to persuade
businessmen to rally against a single European currency. He is to publish a
pamphlet arguing against economic and monetary union.
So both left and right of the Tory party can find arguments from the French
chaos to support their case.
Mr Clarke faces claims from right-wingers that the #3000m reduction in planned
Government spending left too little room for bigger tax cuts. They want a
commitment to big cuts in welfare spending to be included in the election
manifesto. But look, he may say, at the result of such an assault on the core
values of welfare provision in France.
He has already indicated that he will stand firm in resisting demands from the
right for cuts in benefits. He regards tax reductions as a lower priority than
maintaining spending on services such as health and education.
Those who favour a root and branch retrenchment of the welfare state are, in
his words, living in cloud-cuckoo-land. ``I win more votes and I safeguard more
votes by putting it into public services,'' he argues.
His decision to raise the stakes in the battle for control of the Tory party,
by branding nationalist right-wingers as nutters for wanting to erode the
foundations of the welfare state, is seen as a signal of his intent to emerge
as a leadership contender after the election.
It is matched by his determination to halt any further slide in European policy
towards the Euro-sceptics. Mr Clarke is viewed as one of the survivors of a
Tory generation which embraced the post-war settlement.
For him, surely the main argument to be drawn from the strike-ridden French
experience under a dry right-wing government is the danger of bucking a public
consensus in favour of decent welfare provision.
From the politician he views as the chief inhabitant of cloud-cuckoo-land, John
Redwood, the drive is to secure a pledge in the election manifesto ruling out
Britain's joining a single currency in the lifetime of the next Parliament,
which, on one hand, seems to assume a Tory win but is actually some sleight of
hand indicating where he would take a reborn party under his leadership, after
it loses.
As an advocate of a minimalist state, favouring private pensions and an
insurance system to replace public health care, the jettisoning of social
security payments in favour of personal protection plans, the lesson he will
draw from the French experience will be the perils of striving for monetary and
economic union.
Redwood is to launch his pamphlet campaign just three days before the European
summit in Madrid, where talks will take place on next year's Inter-Governmental
Conference on the future of the European Union.
With the Prime Minister fighting a rearguard action to hold his party together
on Europe, sealing the leaks by ruling out a single currency in this
Parliament, but making no public declaration on joining the European monetary
union at a later date, it is hardly the most helpful time to sustain such an
assault. The silence of the Euro-rebels, bought by fudge and nudge, may be
shattered.
The fate of the Maastricht Treaty's goal of a single European currency by 1999
is being played for higher stakes on the streets of France this week. The wave
of strikes is a response to an assault on welfare reform. It is at the same
time a crisis over Europe.
President Jacques Chirac's call for two years of austerity to cut public
deficits was followed by Prime Minister Juppe's overhaul of the debt-laden
social security system. This coincided with tax increases and rising
unemployment.
If the French Government falls, with some observers predicting a snap election
and polls showing two out of three people sympathising with the strikers, it
will have resonance far beyond the picket lines of Paris.
</TEXT>
