<HEADLINE>Exiles' reign may not last much longer Hopefuls urged to take stepping-stone to cap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044661</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer has sounded the clarion call for the
inter-district championship, which gets under way tomorrow, with a reminder
that international reputations will be made and broken over the next four weeks.
Telfer, a long-time proponent of the theme that the district scene is the
natural stepping-stone between club and country, said yesterday that the series
of matches, which reach a climax on December 31, will be the proving ground for
a number of players aspiring to international selection.
The championship, unsponsored and unloved in many quarters, is particularly
significant this year because it may well be the last.
Next season, when Scotland will be represented in the new European Cup
competition - with ties to be played mostly, if not exclusively at weekends and
before Christmas - an already overcrowded fixture card indicates that something
has to go, and the prime candidate for the chop is the inter-district series.
The current championship, with the Exiles defending the title amid a backdrop
of speculation as to their continued survival, also takes place amid the
ongoing debate as to whether club or district sides will be Scotland's
representatives in Europe.
The SRU currently favour the district route for the unarguable reason that they
would be stronger than club sides. However, the added complication is that it
remains to be seen whether or not English clubs who might also be involved in
Europe will release their Scottish players to play for rivals in the lucrative
competition.
In fact, when this very point was put to Newcastle's Rob Andrew and Sir John
Hall last week - vis-a-vis the availability of the likes of Gary Armstrong and
Doddie Weir - both executed a neat side-step with the declaration that it was
much too soon to say.
On one point there is no debate. For the continued well-being of the national
side, Scotland cannot afford to lose the Exiles or, more particularly, the
expatriates' recruitment network which has thrown up a host of individuals over
the years who have laboured effectively in the national cause.
Symbolically, the Murrayfield photocall which brought together Dave McIvor,
Stuart Reid, Fergus Wallace, and Jim Hay - representing North and Midlands,
Edinburgh, Glasgow, and the South - was without a representative from the
Exiles. Nothing sinister, just a by-product of travel difficulties and
competing commitments, but the absent Exiles might well be a precursor for the
future.
This year's championship, which kicks off with games tomorrow between the
Exiles and Edinburgh at Richmond, and North and Midlands versus Glasgow at
Kirkcaldy (7pm), has already been diminished to an extent by competing
premiership interests.
The opening game, between the Exiles and the South which should have been
played on Sunday, was cancelled and is, apparently, to be re-arranged at a
later date.
Additionally, the North and Midlands clash against Exiles on Sunday, December
17, is likely to be hard-hit because the contingent of Stirling County players
in the N and M side have their championship-deciding game against Heriot's FP
the previous day.
Similarly, Edinburgh's game against the South could well be affected, although
in this case any Herioters involved in the Edinburgh side might well consider
the district game to be of more value to them than the club game.
Nevertheless, Telfer yesterday hammered home the fact that, so far as the
international selectors are concerned, the district championship is one not to
be missed.
``Given that this is a year of transition, with a number of senior players
having retired from international duty, the selectors will be taking a
particularly keen interest.
``On the principle that many are called but few are chosen, the championship is
therefore the proving ground for a number of players aspiring to international
selection,'' he said.
</TEXT>
