<HEADLINE>Windsurfing on Tiree</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TIM Arkless's response to my recent article about windsurfing on Tiree makes it
clear that he is well aware of the conflict between ``unscrupulous'' elements
in his chosen sport and local interests.
I reported the events concerning the rights of way issue as accurately as they
were related to me, although it subsequently appears that the local council has
taken a hand to try to establish the exact position on the issue. Does this not
rather emphasise the strong local feeling on the issue?
I could have added further incidents, with names and addresses supplied, where
locals were disgruntled by some rogue elements within the visiting windsurfing
community. I did try to make it clear that not all windsurfers are implicated.
Mr Arkless appears not to have grasped the Hebridean use of patronymics. He
erroneously refers to Willie MacPhail of Clachan Farm - known to islanders as
Willie Clachan - as Mr Clachan. This has caused some considerable mirth locally.
As to his economic argument, renovating ``ruins'' for seasonal residents does
indeed provide a welcome boost for local builders and provide much-needed
mainly winter accommodation on an island where housing is a major problem.
However, locals find it virtually impossible to compete with incomers when it
comes to buying these ``ruins''.
The same amount of work would be available to island builders if locals were
able to compete, in hard cash terms, in the housing market.
Garry A MacLeod,
Shore Cottage,
Scarinish, Isle of Tiree.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
