<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turning the tables in style</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sally Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044663</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
All too often the experience of dining out in an Indian restaurant is a much
too hasty affair. The food may well be excellent, but if the service is on the
brisk side and the atmosphere and ambience are not conducive to relaxation, the
evening can be ruined.
This is frequently the case in city centre restaurants where you feel as if you
are on a conveyor belt, and where there is little opportunity to form a
relationship with the staff or indeed the chef before it's time to leave, often
feeling over-full.
At New Amritsar International things are decidedly different. The restaurant
was well established at Kirk Road in Bearsden but it is now undergoing an
exciting metamorphosis. It has been completely refurbished to form an intimate
and flexible dining space suitable for parties large or small, or an intimate
tete  tete.
A soft and subtle decor is combined with attractive new artwork, tables and
chairs designed for style and comfort have been imported from Italy, and the
impressive horses of white Carrara marble which form the restaurant's dramatic
centrepiece symbolise the highest aspirations of the management.
Fresh flowers, pot plants and candles all add to the ambience and there are
many little personal touches and an attention to detail which is refreshing in
these hurried days when elegance is sacrificed for turnover.
Hot towels after your meal are one of these little luxuries, as are sorbets to
cleanse the palate, but most importantly, owner Manjid Singh has recruited a
highly committed staff whose aim is to give discreet and sensitive service and
to get to know customers personally. This staff is truly international, and
includes two young Italians whose expertise is on the wine side, two Spaniards,
a Turk, and maitre d'hotel, Jaffa Fallahi, who is Iranian.
Being in a residential district like Bearsden is an advantage for a restaurant
like Amritsar. Cities can be depressingly impersonal, but since many people
don't want to have to travel into town to eat, a local establishment has the
opportunity to build up a relationship with its clientle and get to know them
personally. And of course if the food is good and everything else is right,
people will want to keep coming back.
Jaffa Fallahi feels this personal relationship is very important, as is a
philosophy of creating a relationship with the community. He also believes that
the chef should get to know his customers too, and their likes and dislikes.
Amritsar International is fortunate that it has a chef who is not only highly
skilled in Indian cookery, but who is equally at home with French sauces and
has a particular interest in seafood and game. His new European menu is
adventurous and varied, and will be seasonal, another refreshing new idea in
Indian eating on offer at Amritsar.
Buffet nights such as are planned by Amritsar International make good sense
because they introduce new tastes and styles of cooking to people shy of
venturing into the unknown. They encourage diners to be a little more
adventurous and give chefs the opportunity to present new dishes which
complement one another. There is a great variety of cuisine in the Indian
sub-continent and much of it is unknown even to inveterate Indian food
consumers like the citizens of Glasgow and its environs.
Amritsar International's buffet evenings will feature Indian regional cooking
from the Punjab, Kashmir and other parts of the sub-continent.
Chef Mussawar Naqui was born in Lahore but has spent a good part of his life
travelling, picking up ideas and skills and in Glasgow, which he assures me is
his last stop, a splendid Glasgow accent. He is equally at home with Sauce
Bearnaise or Chicken Tikka, and cooking is not just a job for him. He loves it.
He believes that Indian food in Glasgow is not so much ethnic as national like
lasagne and spaghetti. It's different from London's Indian food, but better,
more ethnic and contantly developing.
I can especially recommend Mussawar's Mussels a la Ostende, delicious titbits
in a light batter served in a pastry shell.
These, combined with Amritsar's Special Starter Mix with piquant accompanying
sauces are a meal in themselves. Leisurely starters, of course washed down with
wine, set the tone of the meal and also give the chef time to freshly prepare
main dishes to order.
Beware the food that comes too quickly. The restaurant runs a busy take-away
service with a 20% discount on menu prices. You can phone in your order and you
can even be ultra-lazy and opt for home delivery.
Amritsar encourages children on Sundays for special family evenings, but
children under 12 have a 30% reduction on all menu prices at all times.
New Amritsar International is taking bookings now for excellent value Christmas
lunches from 11th-24th December, for a special Christmas Fayre Festive Dinner
from 4th-24th December (children half-price), and for Christmas Day Dinner.
For the curious, Amritsar is a city in India, in north-west Punjab, centre of
the Sikh religion and site of a shameful massacre in 1919 by British troops of
unarmed supporters of Indian self-government. Better remembered for its famous
golden temple.
</TEXT>
