<HEADLINE>Refusing to pay Skye tolls</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WAS interested to read the article on the challenge to the authority of the
collector of tolls on the Skye Bridge (December 1).
It is now nearly seven weeks since a score of us refused to pay the toll on
that wet, windy opening night of the show. So far over 400 occasions of refusal
to pay have been reported to the Procurator-fiscal in Dingwall, in whose
territory the alleged offences took place. So far none of the alleged offenders
has been prosecuted.
All these reports have been passed to the Crown Office in Edinburgh, where they
are no doubt receiving due thought and consideration.
Surely, if the Procurator-fiscal and the Lord Advocate were legitimately able
to convict us, they would have done something about it by now?
Skye Bridge Ltd claims that over 36,000 users have paid the tolls so far. If
the lawyers you quote are right and prove in court that the collector has no
warrant to do his business, then there is going to be an awful clamjamphrie as
Sir Iain Noble and his company refund the decent folk who have so far paid up
in ignorance!
Further, if Skye Bridge Ltd has no warrant to collect money from the public, it
certainly has no right to delay motorists while it searches for police to
caution them.
Police, toll-men, and management have shown great forbearance and courtesy in
dealing with the complicated procedures required for us to record our dissent.
It would cause far less trouble to motorist, toll-man, and police if we simply
handed in a card bearing name, address, and a signed statement of refusal to
pay.
Peter J Findlay,
Lochuanagan,
Fort Augustus,
Inverness-shire.
