<HEADLINE>#2m examination of British vessel lost off Japan Mission to explain carrier tragedy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN expedition to try to solve one of the sea's great mysteries and improve
international shipping safety was announced yesterday by the Government.
No fully satisfactory explanation has been made for the loss of the 169,000
tonne Teesside-built bulk carrier MV Derbyshire.
All 42 British crew members died together with two wives of crewmen when the
ship went down in a typhoon off Japan in September 1980.
An official inquiry into the disaster in 1987 said the weather was probably to
blame.
But families of the crew, trade unions, and shipping experts have long argued
the disaster was caused by structural defects in the vessel.
In the last 15 years, 149 bulk carriers have been lost at sea.
Fresh evidence from a union-sponsored examination of the wreck last year led to
the setting up of a new assessment of the Derbyshire situation by the former
Master of the Rolls, Lord Donaldson.
In a report published yesterday, he concluded that the case for a second
examination of the wreck was ``compelling'' and Transport Secretary Sir George
Young yesterday ordered a #2m expedition.
Sir George said the European Commission had agreed to share the costs of the
examination, which would take place either in next spring or in spring 1997.
Lord Donaldson came to no firm conclusions about the cause of the tragedy.
But he did say it was ``a realistic possibility'' that there could have been a
fracture at bulkhead 65 on the vessel followed by a separation of the two parts
of the hull.
He also said that it was impossible to evaluate this probability ``without a
positive identification of the present position of the stern section''.
Later at a news conference, Lord Donaldson said: ``I am confident that an
expedition is likely to identify either the cause of the accident, or so narrow
down the probable causes of loss, that the maritime community will be able, or
in fact be compelled, to look again at design standards.''
News of the expedition was welcomed on all sides, with RMT leader Jimmy Knapp,
whose union had helped support last year's expedition, saying it was ``a
disgrace it had taken the Government 15 years to act''.
Labour transport spokesman Graham Allen said the mystery surrounding the
sinking had been ``very unsatisfactorily handled so far'', adding that the
families of those lost in the disaster had been ``let down by the Government''.
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock said: ``The persistence of those
who have campaigned for further investigation is to be strongly commended.''
He described the death toll from bulk carrier disasters in recent years as
``appalling''.
The ships' officers' union, Numast, said the Derbyshire controversy was ``a
scandal which has dragged on since the ship sank''.
The union's general secretary, Mr Brian Orrell, went on: ``A sorry saga of
cover-ups and whitewash has hung over the case for far too long.''
Marion Bayliss, who lost her husband, the Derbyshire's chief officer, in the
tragedy, said yesterday: ``I would like to know what happened - how my husband
died.''
She told BBC Five Live's Nationwide programme: ``If nothing is done, my husband
and the other 43 people aboard died in vain.''
Doreen Hutchinson, who lost her son and daughter-in-law, told the programme:
``A further examination of the wreck may help to save others. We want to know
the truth.''
The Derbyshire was one of six identical ships. It was when one of the sister
ships, the Kowloon Bridge, broke in two after running aground off Ireland in
1986 that it was decided to hold an inquiry into the Derbyshire loss.
Sir George said that he envisaged an expedition involving manned or unmanned
submersibles which would go down to photograph the wreck, which lies at a depth
of about 4100 metres.
Lord Donaldson said he did not contemplate any part of the ship being raised,
save for the possible cutting off of a small piece of wreckage which could be
examined later.
</TEXT>
