<HEADLINE>School sums prove tricky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Barclay McBain</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>appointments and education</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Graph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The costs of educating Scottish pupils vary enormously. So what does
yesterday's balance-sheet report
tell us? Education Correspondent Barclay McBain looks for the facts behind the
lack of nuances
THE local school is one of the biggest businesses in many communities, the
Scottish Office Minister for Education, Raymond Robertson, said yesterday. He
was speaking on publication of the latest Parents' Charter- prompted swathe of
education statistics about the costs of Scottish schools.
We've already had this year's examination results, and after school costs will
come attendance and absence tables, as well as information telling us what
pupils do after they leave school - almost a business in itself.
So does it amount to death by a thousand indicators? Or is there life in all
these pointers to schooling? Mr Robertson certainly thinks so. Publishing facts
and figures about school costs had led, he said, to a growing awareness of the
costs of running a school and of the importance of value for money,
particularly when headteachers were taking responsibility for the vast majority
of school-based spending under devolved school management.
Yesterday's report is an introduction to the complex area of school costs, and
it carries 13 health warnings about interpreting the figures. But that did not
stop Mr Robertson from drawing attention to areas where the figures do not
stack up, at least superficially. He chose to highlight the higher per-pupil
costs of secondary schooling in Lothian region - as much as #7523 - compared
with Fife, at most #3071.
This, he said, was due to local policies, which in Fife's case means a
long-term commitment to large, well-utilised secondary schools. Of its 19
secondaries, Fife has only three with rolls of fewer than 800 pupils. The
Minister's reference to Lothian has more potential to mislead, since the school
with the quoted highest cost, Wester Hailes Education Centre, is one of several
community highs to which Lothian is strongly committed but which require high
budgets to offer programmes of extended provision, including wide access for
adults, and to address the needs of the deprived areas they serve.
If Mr Robertson finds a problem with these comparative costs, the solution from
his point of view seems to be close at hand, since it is clear from the first
year's budget guidelines for the new unitary councils that they will find it
extremely difficult to find the finance to maintain the social strategies which
have underpinned their whole policy framework for the last 20 years.
As the report points out, you will need to delve elsewhere for the many nuances
determining school spending which lie behind the raw data. The report shows
that, in primary schools, the average per pupil cost has gone up from #1656 to
#1724, while in the secondary sector it has risen from #2658 to #2708.
The tables show that Holyrood Secondary in Glasgow once again has the lowest
average cost, while the most expensive is Sanday Junior High School in Orkney.
However, another Orkney school - North Walls Junior High - would certainly have
had the highest per pupil cost but for the fact that its tiny roll exempted it
from inclusion in the tables.
The individual school calculations used in the document are based on the
budgeted running costs for financial year 1995-96. These include staff,
premises, supplies and transport costs, plus examination entry fees. Pupil
figures, however, relate to rolls at September 1994, which can differ
significantly from the anticipated rolls at September 1995 on which authorities
base their actual budgets.
Some of the most important factors which have to be borne in mind when
examining the tables include:
q.Bigger schools have larger total running costs, although they can spread
their costs over more pupils.
q.Large schools offer staff savings because of a higher teacher-pupil ratio.
q.Schools with rolls well below capacity tend to have higher overhead costs
because fixed costs, such as rates and heating, apply irrespective of the
degree of building use.
q.The age and condition of buildings affect expenditure on repairs and
maintenance.
q.Some education authorities provide extra staffing and resources to schools
serving areas of deprivation.
The danger in the raw data is therefore that, lifted straight from the page, it
does not compare like with like. Nor do any apparent discrepancies in cost
between schools of similar roll and age of building necessarily imply lack of
financial efficiency. Indeed, most schools already have a high degree of
responsibility for managing their budgets and by April next year this will
apply to all schools under DSM.
Much more useful guidance on using the school costs information is provided in
the foreword to this year's report by the retiring HM Senior Chief Inspector of
Schools, Mr Nisbet Gallacher. ``In order to make useful judgments,'' he
explains, ``school costs need to be set alongside other key indicators such as
the quality of the learning and teaching, pupils' progress, the ethos of the
school, attendance and, for a secondary school, examination results and the
destinations of its leavers.'' This not only places school costs within a
proper context but diminishes their significance as raw data. It also offers an
acknowledgement from the Scottish Office that no single set of statistical
information - including the annual report on examination results - offers a
complete picture of the quality of a pupil's school experience.
In this respect the current research on added value, funded by the Scottish
Office, which is seeking to determine what a school adds to the pupils it
inherits, appears to offer the best way forward.
</TEXT>
