<HEADLINE>Atherton is unbeaten</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044668</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAGNIFICENT Mike Atherton was the hero of England yesterday after masterminding
cricket's version of the Great Escape.
He scored an undefeated 185 to lead his side to a remarkable second Test draw
against South Africa at The Wanderers.
And, when Atherton and courageous partner Jack Russell hugged each other and
saluted their cheering team-mates, he had been batting for 11 hours in all.
Keeper Russell, holder of a new world record after taking 11 catches in the
match, was only a short way behind his skipper in the order of outstanding
merit and they deservedly shared the man-of-the-match award.
Russell frustrated the South African bowlers for close on five hours while
contributing 29 to an unbroken sixth-wicket stand of 119. They survived a
chance apiece, but deserved the luck that came their way.
Atherton's innings - his ninth Test century and biggest yet - will go down as
one of the great rearguard actions. He offered a half-chance on 99 - Gary
Kirsten failing to hold a sharp catch at short leg off Allan Donald's bowling -
and he lost Robin Smith after 75 minutes of the morning session.
Although Atherton finished short of a double hundred, he had posted the highest
Test score at Wanderers, with the help of twenty-eight 4s and earned himself a
permanent place in cricket's hall of heroes.
When England resumed on 167 for four, the victory target of 479 could be
forgotten, but hopes of a draw remained so long as Atherton survived.
The skipper took nearly an hour to add the 18 runs required to complete a
century spanning 259 deliveries.
But Smith was clearly determined to be positive if the opportunity presented
itself. He hit eight boundaries but his attempt to add a ninth gave South
Africa the breakthrough.
Donald tempted the Hampshire batsman into a cut which was not properly
controlled and Pollock held a well-judged catch moving in from third man. That
ended Smith's 44-run contribution to a stand of 87.
South African tails were up, and Russell was lucky to escape next over when
gloving an attempted pull against Brian McMillan into no-man's land between
short leg and square leg. Then Meyrick Pringle failed to hold a waist-high
return catch when Russell tried to play through the leg-side.
After lunch, Russell knuckled down in his own inimitable fashion to give the
captain great support. At one stage after tea, with spinner Clive Eksteen
bowling, Russell was surrounded by six close catchers. But his response to that
over-crowding was to pull a short ball from the left-armer for 4.
Taking into account the home side's second innings, Atherton had been an
ever-present on the field for 19 hours when the match finished. Scoreboard:
SOUTH AFRICA - First Innings 332
Second Innings 346-9 dec
ENGLAND - First Innings 200
Second Innings, overnight 167-4
M A Atherton not out ................................185
R A Smith c Pollock b Donald .....................44
R C Russell not out ....................................29
Extras 34. Total (for 5) .........................351
Fall: 5-232.
Did Not Bat: D G Cork, D Gough, A R C Fraser, D E Malcolm.
Bowling: Donald 35-9-95-2; Pringle 23-5-52-1; Pollock 29-11-65-0; McMillan
21-0-50-2; Eksteen 52-20-76-0; Cronje 3-1-2-0; Kirsten 2-2-0-0.
OTHER SCORES
Pakistan A 214 (Shakeel Ahmed 62; D W Headley 6-73) and 154-4 (Shakeel Ahmed
73); England A 332-6 dec (J E R Gallian 153, I D K Salisbury 86, N Hussain 43;
Athar Laiq 3-84, Mohammad Zahid 3-91). At Rawalpindi. Match drawn.
Tasmania 335-4 and 273-5 dec (A Daly 62no, R Tucker 60no); Sri Lanka 369 and
160-2 (C Hathurusinghe 61no). Tour match in Launceston. Match drawn.
q PAKISTAN salvaged some pride by beating Australia by 74 runs in the third and
final Test in Sydney yesterday after a mesmerising performance by leg-spinner
Mushtaq Ahmed. He claimed four wickets to lift his tally for the three-Test
series to 18 as Australia collapsed for 172 in their second innings.
The tourists had been beaten by huge margins in the first two Tests. Scores:
Pakistan 299 and 204; Australia 257 and 172 (M A Taylor 59; Mushtaq Ahmed 4-91;
Waqar Younis 3-15).
