<HEADLINE>French leader stands his ground over cuts as labour organisers urge private sector to join protest Juppe and unions dig in over strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN CHALMERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
PRIME Minister Alain Juppe stood his ground in a bitter confrontation with
trade unions today, vowing to press ahead with an overhaul of the country's
welfare system despite mounting unrest and widening strikes.
At an emergency meeting of his Cabinet, the conservative premier said there was
no question of holding a referendum or dissolving Parliament to settle the
crisis provoked by his controversial plans for reform and austerity.
Government spokesman Alain Lamassoure told a news conference after the meeting
that Juppe felt the strike action had now reached its peak.
``If we hammer home a number of truths often enough, the vast majority of
French people and many of those on strike today will realise that there are no
grounds for a strike,'' he said.
However trade unions hardened their stand, urging private sector workers to
join striking public employees and calling for mass demonstrations in big towns
and cities tomorrow.
Today's strike action hit the transport sector hardest, causing record traffic
jams around Paris. For the second successive week there were no trains, buses,
or Paris Metro services and thousands of electricity, gas, and postal workers
remained on strike.
Juppe's government stuck to its guns, insisting it would not back down on a
planned overhaul of social security combining higher taxes, health cost
controls, and later retirement for public employees.
The Prime Minister, who has made no public statement since last Wednesday, met
his Cabinet to discuss the snowballing unrest.
He was expected to break his silence in an address Parliament tomorrow during a
debate on a no-confidence motion tabled by the Socialist opposition.
Since the government has a four-fifths majority in the National Assembly, the
motion denouncing the proposed welfare reform has no chance of passing.
And in a boost to Juppe, an opinion poll today found that 51% of voters wanted
the government to stand firm against striking workers. That compared with an
earlier CSA poll which had shown 62% siding with the strikers.
However the French franc came under fire on the foreign exchanges today.
Dealers said financial market operators increasingly feared a long conflict
that would harm the economy and threaten government efforts to meet the
criteria for a single European currency in 1999.
Today the Paris region motorway network was saturated before dawn and by 2pm
there was a record 387 miles of traffic jams around the capital.
The government began hiring 1700 private buses to transport up to 100,000
suburban Paris commuters free but the substitute system was not expected to be
fully operational until tomorrow. A special free Seine riverboat service began
in Paris.
Six leading three-star hotels announced they were offering frustrated commuters
bed and breakfast for a big discount price.
The road chaos worsened during the day as some truck drivers joined the strike.
The Force Ouvriere trade union said some 700 to 1000 lorries were blocking or
hampering traffic on main roads around the towns of Troyes, Bordeaux, Grenoble,
Lyon, and Rouen.
Their action, along with a 24-hour stoppage planned by dockers at the
Mediterranean port of Marseilles tomorrow, looked set to disrupt freight
services further and deal another blow to the slowing economy.
In other sectors, the strike was followed by 19% of employees at the state
telephone company France Telecom, but by just 5% of post office workers.
Two unions called on secondary school teachers to join the movement from
tomorrow and employees of the airlines Air France and Air Inter were due to
start a 24-hour strike on Thursday.
The unions urged private sector workers to join public employees in protest
unless a controversial welfare overhaul is dropped.
``Now is the time, because today we are strong,'' Communist CGT union leader
Louis Viannet said. He accused the government of refusing to negotiate
seriously and urged workers to make tomorrow a ``new and powerful day of
action''.
``The Juppe plan must be withdrawn,'' he said. ``After that, we will
negotiate.''
President Jacques Chirac, saying France was at a crossroads, stood by Juppe in
a speech in the west African state of Benin, broadcast repeatedly on French
television. ``It is this path, the path of reforms too long delayed, that I
have chosen,'' he said.
In a radio interview today, the president acknowledged he was worried, saying
he was in regular contact with Juppe and was following the situation
hour-by-hour while attending a summit of French-speaking countries in Cotonou.
Socialist opposition leader Lionel Jospin called on the government to
``negotiate to find a way out and not give in to the temptation of a test of
strength''.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
