<HEADLINE>University faces contracts dispute</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LECTURERS at The Robert Gordon University, Aberdeen, are heading for
confrontation with their management over a bid to switch from national to local
negotiations.
The lecturers, members of the Educational Institute of Scotland and the
Manufacturing, Science, and Finance Union, are prepared to invoke their
disputes procedure as a result of a management proposal to introduce contracts
for new staff which the unions claim mean a 25% increase in lecturers'
workloads.
The unions are prepared to fight to retain national negotiations and have
demanded the withdrawal of the contracts which have been described as ``the
worst contract in any sector in higher education in Scotland or England''.
Yesterday, EIS national officer Marian Healy and Mr Jim Cowan of the MSF met
the management, including the Principal, Dr David Kennedy, and demanded the
withdrawal of the contracts.
Ms Healy said: ``I told them our legal advice was that they could be challenged
in a court if they were to issue these contracts to new or existing staff.
``I also told Dr Kennedy that if he wished to discuss terms and conditions of
employment for staff at RGU he must do so at the joint national negotiating
committee. He told me that negotiating machinery was no longer legal because
the employers had withdrawn in 1994.
``However, it is again legal opinion that by virtue of the fact that the
managers and unions still continue to negotiate through this forum that it is
binding and legal. For the past two years, this collective machinery, albeit
operating on a voluntary basis, negotiated pay for all universities.
``They are now going to take away our legal opinions and have their legal
people check them. Presumably they will get back to us if they think there is
some way forward.''
A spokeswoman said last night the university regretted the unions'
unwillingness to accept the proposals for changes.
Dr Kennedy said: ``Both management and unions have agreed since 1988 that there
should be a move towards parity of conditions of service and salaries in the
higher education sector. However, repeated attempts to solve the issues
nationally have met with a single response from the unions - that agreement
should be at local level.''
He said the proposed changes would bring the university in to line with all the
pre-1992 universities. Academic staff taking up new appointments will receive
30 days and 11 public holidays. Existing academic staff will continue to enjoy
50 days and 11 public holidays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
