<HEADLINE>Blair agrees to upgrade international assistance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044671</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
LABOUR leader Tony Blair has agreed to include a Cabinet-level department for
international development in the party's election manifesto, dispelling
speculation that it might join the Ministry for Women among New Labour's
abandoned policies.
If Labour wins the next election, it will upgrade the existing Overseas
Development Administration, currently a branch of the Foreign Office, into a
full Government department with a team of Ministers and a Secretary of State.
As part of the measure, Labour also would create a Commons Select Committee to
oversee the department's activities and Britain's international development
programmes.
The new department would take over responsibility for international
environmental policy - including implementation of the Rio treaty - from the
Department of Environment, and World Bank negotiations from the Treasury.
At a private meeting last month with Shadow Overseas Development Minister Joan
Lestor, Mr Blair accepted her argument that Labour should give international
assistance a higher profile.
Mr Blair is understood to have been persuaded by the absence of any political
difficulties presented by the proposal. Unlike a Ministry for Women, it would
not require new funding to build it from scratch, nor is it ideologically
contentious.
Since his election as party leader last year, Mr Blair has imposed a rigorous
control on manifesto commitments. He has criticised the Tories for breaking
their 1992 commitments and does not want to leave a Labour government open to
the same criticisms.
A behind-the-scenes committee has been established to develop the idea. It will
have its first meeting next week and will be made up of MPs, former civil
servants, and a representative from Mr Blair's office.
One source said: ``This is a personal triumph for Joan Lestor. Given that we
have dropped our commitment to create a Ministry for Women, obtaining agreement
on this new department is an achievement.''
A commitment to introduce a Cabinet Minister for Women, with a full department
dedicated to ensuring that ``women's voices are heard at the highest levels of
government'', featured in the last manifesto. It was dropped earlier this year
because it was deemed to be too costly and too politically correct.
The manifesto also committed the Department for International Development to a
steady increase in the UK's aid budget over five years, from the current 0.31%
of GNP to the UN-recommended level of 0.7%. That commitment has also survived
the review.
Last week's Budget imposed a 6.7% cut in real terms over the next three years
on the ODA's #2.1 billion spending. In cash terms, the cuts will remove #124m
from the overseas aid budget next year.
Aid agencies and Opposition parties have condemned the Government for
sacrificing Britain's contribution to international assistance programmes for
the sake of politically-motivated tax cuts.
Labour described the scale of the cuts to the ODA's budget as an acceleration
away from the 0.7% goal. Overseas aid spokesman George Foulkes accused the
Government of breaking its promise in the Queen's Speech that a ``substantial
aid programme will be maintained.''
</TEXT>
