<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Love and good vibrations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Victoria Freedman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044672</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A spiritual experience on the night of her mother's funeral changed Carole
McLean-Smith's life for ever, as Victoria Freedman discovers
CAROLE McLean-Smith is not a peculiar, little old lady who spends her evenings
in a darkened room sitting around a table with other little old ladies, holding
hands and summoning up spirits. Yes, she is in communication with those who
have passed on, or popped off, as spiritualists say, but Carole would like to
dissolve that popular image of mediums and convey to more people the beautiful
philosophy of the Spiritualist Church.
The image of the seance sitter is, indeed, at odds with this well-groomed and
very attractive fashion model who was born into a life of ease in Newlands
50-odd years ago. She was brought up to believe in God and go to church, but
spent little time pondering about religion or the reason for her own existence.
Theology had no place in her life. As a child it was filled with Brownies,
choir, and school, as an adult with modelling, motherhood (she has a son,
Richard, now 26 and an actor) and marriage (four to date). Then in 1975, while
between marriages, Carole had a spiritual experience. On the night of her
mother's funeral she was sobbing noisily when she heard her mother's voice by
the side of the bed telling her to stop crying and to listen carefully.
Her first priority, she was told, was to look after her young son properly. She
should also go to the Spiritualist Church.
``The what?''
``The Spiritualist Church, dear,'' said the mother, who then assured her
daughter she was well, happy, and had been glad to go.
``I know it sounds peculiar,'' admits Carole. ``But it was my mum's voice, and
so real and so emphatic that I wasn't frightened and I didn't question it.''
Accordingly, she gave up her career to devote herself entirely to Richard and
set about finding the Spiritualist Church, a place she had not previously known
existed. The following Sunday she approached its front door, holding tightly on
to Richard's hand, fully expecting a congregation of crackpots.
``I sat at the back, praying, that the medium wouldn't come to me with a
message.''
Carole left the church still sceptical after the display of mediumship but
uplifted by the service.
``It was beautiful,'' she reminisces. ``There was a nice opening hymn, an
address, a healing minute where everyone sat in silence and threw their
thoughts out to people in trouble, because thoughts can be powerful, positive
waves, then another hymn and 20 minutes of mediumship.''
Carole began attending regularly, interested by the messages given by the
medium, certainly, but more impressed by the ``beautiful'' sermons. Inspired,
she began to live her life spiritually.
``I was always helping old ladies with their shopping. You really go overboard
at first because you want to love everybody. It took me some time to realise
that you can love everybody but you have to look after yourself as well.'' She
was soon immersed in the philosophy of spiritualism. Simplified, it is
concerned not with religion but with the progression of the soul. Life on earth
is to work towards a more evolved soul that is kind, tolerant, non-judgmental,
and all-loving. At the point of death, the soul leaves its carriage, the body,
and continues to exist at a different vibrational level.
``I found that my friends were very interested. Some of the more Christian
people thought it was the work of the devil, but they had terrible
misconceptions. They imagined us sitting round in circles `calling up the dead'
and saying `Is there anybody there?' But those expressions are simply never
used. We don't call up the dead. They call us.''
Carole was ``called'' three years later, by which time she had resumed her
career and was working on a cruise ship.
Although immediately open to her mother's survival, Carole was initially
reluctant to believe her first contact from an unknown spirit, a male voice,
urging her to pass on a message to a young man on board who was confused about
his career.
Nevertheless, she passed on the message and afterwards found that the spirits
would often contact her when she was in the company of someone who needed help,
leading her to work in her spare time as a medium.
Nearly 20 years later Carole continues to give sittings, free of charge, for
those who are troubled or have lost a loved one. She tunes in, like a radio,
she explains, and receives voices of relatives, or personal spirit guides,
frequently accompanied by a visual image in the form of a picture.
``I think if I saw the whole person I'd run a mile,'' she admits with a laugh.
Although contact with those who have popped off can be emotional, there is
lightness too. At a recent sitting, she says, a man came back to apologise to
the recipient for disbelieving in the afterlife and all the arguments it had
caused.
She found that such contact takes away the fear of death and comforts those who
are grieving when they hear that the dead person is fine, that messages from
spirit guides offer advice and hope during difficult times. It may be that
Carole's kind, concerned, and gentle voice is a solace in itself.
Personally, she says, her beliefs have helped enormously, seeing her through
marriage to a violent man, to a man who left her in debt, and two failed
marriages. She now lives in a council flat in East Kilbride, still in demand as
a model, but working only when energy allows, for she has suffered from ME for
the past eight years.
``I've had a horrendous life, but I now view everything in a spiritual way.
I've never once said `Why me?' or been angry with my ex-husbands. I used to be
quick-tempered and stamp my foot. I had no patience, no tolerance.
``But I am now incapable of being rude. If I was bitter and twisted because of
my marriages, or resentful and rude because I've got ME, it would work against
my soul. Instead, I feel I'm lucky.''
Carole is aware that she, and other mediums, have to provide sitters with
evidence of survival for them to believe in life after death, but she is
convinced that even without contact with the departed, many would benefit from
the ideals of spiritualism and enjoy the church services.
``I want to dissociate myself from fortunetellers who are in it for the money
or do it as a party piece. Spiritualism is different. It is a guiding force,
always encouraging, always beautiful. Try the Spiritualist Church,'' she urges.
``You'll be met with love.''
q The Glasgow Association of Spiritualists is at 7 Somerset Place.
</TEXT>
