<HEADLINE>Visitors include the best Visitors include the best</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VOLLEYBALL
CITY of Glasgow Ragazzi get a first-hand look at top-level European volleyball
when they host Group 11 of the European Confederation Cup at the Kelvin Hall
this weekend.
University Club of Paris, Croatians Metalac-Olt Osijec, and Bulgaria's
Balkancar Tran Sofia are the rivals as Ragazzi rub shoulders with some of the
best talent in the game.
The University Club have won the French title 12 times and, coached by former
Dutch national team coach Harry Brokking, include Russian internationalist
Gennadi Tcheremissov and Canadian cap Bruce Edwards, as well as the two best
players France has ever produced.
Setter Alain Fabiani - rated as one of the best players in the world at his
peak - and Laurent Tillie have won a staggering 862 caps between them.
Ragazzi coach Tommy Dowens said: ``We have a 19-year-old setter Steve Linton
who can learn a lot from watching Fabiani. Our preparations have been hit by
injuries and work commitments, and we're not as well prepared as we should be.
But we'll video all the matches and we can learn a lot from this weekend.''
It is the biggest weekend ever for Scottish volleyball, with Kilmarnock playing
in Group 6 in Portugal. Also involved are hosts Castelo Da Maia, Hapoel Kfar
(Israel), and Medikemia (Hungary). Paul Carruthers, Allan Thomas and Scott
Russell, who all missed Saturday's defeat by Bellshill Cardinals, will set off
with Kilmarnock tomorrow.
</TEXT>
