<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vote on tax cut Labour abstention a mistake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044674</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW Labour has made it abundantly clear that it will abstain on the Budget vote
tonight, thereby allowing the Chancellor's 1p tax cut to go unchallenged. This
is a mistake and deeply depressing for those who believe that the task of Her
Majesty's Opposition is to oppose, not just on ideological grounds but on a
sensible analysis of the facts. That analysis has been made. Labour politicians
have enjoyed themselves over the past week picking holes in a Budget which is a
good deal more devious than it appeared at first glance. The logical extension
of their argument, for reasons which we will examine, is that the 1p cut in
income tax should be opposed. That will not happen; they will sit on their
hands because the phantoms and shadows which haunt New Labour are more
terrifying than the power of reason.
To be specific, New Labour is afraid of the reaction of the middle-class voters
which it pursues with such desperate intent. The received wisdom is that the
middle class will reject any party which puts up taxes, and by extension which
criticises tax cuts. This is a hangover from the terrible mess Labour made of
their tax proposals just before the last election, but if a whole series of
opinion polls is to be believed the middle classes would reject a tax cut if
essential services could thereby be maintained or improved. This isn't good
enough for the cynics. They believe that what people say to opinion pollsters
on this subject is reversed in the secrecy of the polling booth. That might
have been true a few years ago, but taxes and the uses to which they are put
are seen in a different light now. The link between taxes and the provision of
services is clearer than it has ever been. The middle classes (many of whom are
readers of this newspaper and who give us their views with force and
perception) are just as vulnerable as the rest of the population to the
diminution of these services. They know that tax cuts must be paid for by
cutting public expenditure, and they know equally that the derisory Public
Finance Initiative is unlikely to pour private money into provision, and that
even if it does the need for a healthy return on the investment will come back
to haunt us all.
Chancellor Clarke has argued that he did not cut taxes more energetically in
order that public services might be maintained. This is only partly true,
especially as the examples which he used illustrate nothing more than his
considerable ability for sleight of hand. The National Health Service will get
extra money, said Mr Clarke. So it will, but not nearly as much as he implied.
The actual sum is not clear but is believed to be in excess of #1billion. This
sounds impressive but is largely bogus, being composed mainly of money which
was already agreed or in last year's spending plans. Capital spending on health
is to be cut, with a Micawberish expectation that the PFI will make up the
difference. Much the same is true of education, that other plank-to-be of the
Tory election manifesto, which Mr Clarke insists will receive an extra #878m.
Again, this sounds good, but acquires the quality of ectoplasm when it becomes
evident that this comes at the cost of cuts in local capital spending or at the
expense of other local government services. Significantly, the 1p cut in the
basic rate of tax has cost the Chancellor #2billion in a full year. If he had
not made the cut that sum could have turned the illusory gains made by health
and education into genuine advances. The Labour Party should abandon its queasy
agnosticism on this matter and vote against the tax cut. In its heart of hearts
it knows that this is right. If the Liberal Democrats show the courage of their
convictions, why can't Labour?
</TEXT>
