<DOCID>GH951205-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Councils under scrutiny Watchdog set to get new teeth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044676</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SWEEPING new powers for the local goverment Ombudsman to act as a watchdog
over
council staff appointments and to investigate complaints against individual
councillors are likely to result from the latest report into the way local
authorities are run.
The report, by a special task force, was commissioned by Mr Michael Forsyth a
mere 19 days after he took office as Secretary of State and marks the latest
episode in his sometimes turbulent relationship with local authority leaders.
It diplomatically avoids making any firm recommendations but clearly points
the
way to much closer scrutiny of the actions of local authority officials and
their political masters.
However, those same masters seemed unperturbed by the report's findings,
claiming that they expose the gulf between the sweeping allegations of
Ministers and what actually happens in practice.
In addition, where the report identifies areas which could be improved they
counter that local goverment is already addressing these.
The establishment of the task force followed the setting up of a public
inquiry
into a series of allegations about the way staff appointments were made at
Monklands District Council and ``jobs for the boys'' rows over the filling of
senior positions on some of the new councils.
An inquiry is also now to take place into appointments procedures at the new
North Lanarkshire Council. An announcement about who will chair it is expected
within days.
The task force's report states clearly that ``political, family, race and
religious, or factors other than merit'' have no part to play in the
appointments process. But it adds that it is difficult to devise any method
which can entirely guarantee such outcomes.
The report also suggests that the Scottish Secretary could be given wider
powers which would allow him to act more promptly in setting up an inquiry
over
complaints against a council such as in the case of Monklands.
It also puts forward possible options for raising standards in a number of
areas including tightening up the National Code of Local Government Conduct,
simplifying the way in which councillors declare financial interests, and
improving the financial monitoring of council ``arms length'' companies.
It proposes ways of making local government more open and accessible but it
also sees little wrong with the general conduct of councils on many issues.
It was this that was seized on by Cosla's Labour vice president, Councillor
Keith Geddes, who claimed Scottish local government had been given ``a clean
bill of health'' by the task force over the mechanisms used for monitoring and
reviewing its internal conduct.
Councillor Geddes said the report suggested ways of refining and improving
systems which were already in operation.
This was in sharp contrast, he claimed, to the sweeping statements about local
government in recent months from Mr Forsyth and his Ministers which had been
based on prejudice rather than on clear analysis.
He added: ``Much of what has been suggested in the report is already under
way.
For example, Cosla is currently preparing good practice guidelines on
appointments and we are already working with the Accounts Commission as
suggested in the report.''
Mr Forsyth said he regarded it as a priority to remove unnecessary constraints
from local government but it was then all the more necessary that local
authorities had to act responsibly and be properly accountable.
The task force had identified a range of options for ensuring that a proper
framework of checks and balances existed to support this.
``Allegations made about local authorities often prove to have no substance,
therefore it is as important for the credibility of local government that this
should be shown to be the case as it is to put wrongs right,'' he said.
The report was welcomed byScottish Labour leader George Robertson, who claimed
it had given support for
key Labour demands on good local government practice.
The report - compiled by Scottish Office and local government officials along
with Ombudsman Derrick Marks and Controller of Audit Robert Black - does not
make any definite recommendations but simply lays out a series of possible
options for change in the various areas which it examined.
On the currently high profile area of staff appointments the report says some
form of external adjudication for complaints is necessary but it is not
enthusiastic about the idea of a setting up a permanent staff commission to
oversee appointments.
A possible alternative, it says, is the extension of the Ombudsman's powers so
that he could investigate complaints from people applying for jobs who do not
have access to a council's own complaints procedures.
Looking at the Scottish Secretary's own powers to act if councillors default
on
their legal duties, the report says they are rarely used and the Monklands
and
even the more recent North Lanarkshire inquiries are the only instances in
recent years where the alleged default falls into area of conduct.
One option put forward would be to allow the Scottish Secretary power to set
up
an inquiry even if a legal duty had not been breached. Another option would
give the Scottish Secretary powers to order accused councils to commission
their own inquiries but they would have to be chaired by an independent person.
The report says that the National Code of Local Government Conduct requires
substantial review taking into account ``the Seven Principles of Public Life''
drawn up by the Nolan Committee.
There is a strong case, it says, that where a breach of the code results in
maladministration, the Ombudsman should be able to investigate even if the
complaint arises from the actions of a single councillor.
Another option put forward is  that the Ombudsman's powers should be widened
to
allow the investigation of the competitive tendering process within councils.
The report states: ``We understand that there have from time to time been
allegations that authorities did not follow fair and established procedures in
awarding contracts which could not be pursued through the courts or the
Accounts Commission.''
On the issue of councillors declaring their financial interests being
restricted over voting on matters which affect them, the report states that
the
existing rules work well.
But it suggests the present legislation could be simplified, laying down a
threshhold of #1000 above which interests must be declared and a member could
not take part in discussions or vote.
A section dealing with the Accounts Commission says the evidence suggests that
corruption or financial irregularity is not a widespread problem with councils
in Scotland.
</TEXT>
