<HEADLINE>Water liabilities mean legal clash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044677</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH barely four months to go until its demise, Strathclyde Regional Council is
preparing to take the Scottish Office to court over a plan for #4m of water
services revenue debts to be borne by the succeeding 12 unitary authorities.
Although this possibility is enshrined in legislation, it appears Strathclyde
region has only become aware of it in the last week or so, and has responded
with the threat of a judicial review should the Scottish Office persist.
An angry Strathclyde Labour leader, Councillor Robert Gould, said yesterday:
``It's a late kick in the teeth and has been done without consultation. It's
putting a liability on to the unitary authorities for a service that they don't
operate.
``You would have expected, on the basis of equity, that this deficit would be
passed on to the new water authority.''
He added that if it were the Government's intention to write off water services
capital debt so that the new water authorities could start off with a clean
slate, then Strathclyde would be seeking a judicial review as to why capital
and revenue debt was being treated differently.
The #4m debt in question relates to reduced income from non-domestic water
rate, non-domestic sewerage rate, water meter charges, and water council tax.
What appears to have happened is that the consumption of water in those classes
of users has fallen. Big industrial firms are beginning to understand that
water is a costly commodity and they are taking more care over its use.
Consumption is also down because of a reduction in industrial activity.
In short, Strathclyde had budgeted for a certain levels of income from these
categories and the consumption had not met that projection.
According to council finance officials, the legislation was ``pretty silent''
on where these debts should be apportioned.
A senior official added: ``What's happening is, after discussions with the
Scottish Office, these balances are being passed to the new unitary councils
and not to the water authority, and that's where the problem arises.''
The leader of the Conservative group on Strathclyde region, Councillor Iain
Drysdale, said: ``I think this is an unfortunate situation, but if the
successor authorities are prepared to pick up the benefits of any surplus, then
these things are inevitably a two-way stretch.''
But a Scottish Office spokesperson explained: ``The legislation requires all
property rights and liabilities of the current regions and islands councils in
respect of water and sewerage to be transferred to the new water authorities.''
</TEXT>
