<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court told that abortion was illegal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONSULTANT illegally aborted an 11-week-old foetus during a hysterectomy
operation on a childless woman, a court was told yesterday.
Reginald Dixon, an obstetrician and gynaecologist at the King's Mill Hospital,
at Sutton-in-Ashfield, in Nottinghamshire, performed the abortion when he
discovered during the operation that Barbara Whiten was pregnant.
Mr Simeon Maskrey QC, prosecuting, told Nottingham Crown Court: ``Mr Dixon
carried out a hysterectomy with her consent.
``During the course of the operation, he discovered what nobody had previously
appreciated, namely that she was pregnant. He could have stopped the operation
there and then. He could have decided to go no further.
``What he decided to do was to proceed with the hysterectomy in the knowledge
that it would have the inevitable consequence of terminating the pregnancy.
``He did it without her consent.''
Mr Dixon, from Kirkby-in-Ashfield, Nottinghamshire, denies unlawfully procuring
a miscarriage, a charge brought under the Offences Against the Persons Act.
Mrs Whiten, 35, was admitted to the hospital in 1993, for the operation to cure
endometriosis, a condition from which she had suffered since 1990.
Mr Maskrey said Mrs Whiten, who had two stepsons from her husband Michael's
previous marriage, did not want children at the time but did hope to have
children in the future.
When she was first admitted to the hospital, Mrs Whiten was examined by a
doctor but no internal examination was carried out and no-one realised she was
pregnant.
Mr Dixon first spoke to Mrs Whiten as she was being wheeled to the operating
theatre on the day of her operation. He claims she asked that he remove her
ovaries in the operation because she was reluctant to undergo future surgery.
However, Mrs Whiten claims she asked him to remove them only if they were found
to be diseased.
Mr Maskrey said that on the basis of this conversation, Mr Dixon decided to go
ahead with the termination, believing she did not want to endure further
operations.
He tried to contact her husband once the operation had begun and he realised
she was, in fact, pregnant. Mr Whiten could not be found and Mr Dixon discussed
the problem with the anaesthetist and consulted Mrs Whiten's medical notes
before deciding to continue with the operation.
Her notes reported she had tried to overdose herself in 1992 and was prescribed
drugs for depression.
Mr Maskrey told the jury this decision did not constitute an emergency, which
would therefore have made the operation legal.
The court heard that in his notes on the operation and in a letter to Mrs
Whiten's GP, Mr Dixon believed he was doing what his patient wanted.
Mr Maskrey said: ``It is not a question of whether she would have wanted him to
carry out the termination but whether the law allowed Mr Dixon to carry out the
terminaton.''
The case was adjourned until today.
Earlier, the court was told that Mrs Whiten was ``devastated'' when told of the
abortion the day after the operation.
</TEXT>
