<HEADLINE>Manager worried about Dons' league form Play the game or else, Aitken warns players</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY may have been celebrating on an open-top bus on Sunday, but Aberdeen's
Coca-Cola Cup heroes might be well advised to please their manager on a more
consistent basis or they may be asked to get on their bikes.
Roy Aitken is not the kind of manager, nor was he as a player, who dwells on
yesterday's news, and the league form of his team is causing him concern.
In the wake of the defeat by Partick Thistle on Saturday, Aitken has promised
that he will radically alter his squad if the team does not come up with
championship challenging performances in the next six weeks.
``We must show more consistency in our league results,'' he said. ``We are in
fifth place and I am looking for this to be improved quickly.
``I want a squad of players I can rely on from week to week. It is up to me to
recognise the ones who can and cannot do this. If they can't meet these
standards, they are no use to this club. If they can't handle the challenge
then obviously I must bring in players who can.
The former Celtic captain, a man well used to the demands of consistent play,
went on to point out that the next six weeks of the season are vital.
``Winning a trophy showed what it meant to the city, but the cup is history
now. It is time to move on and be contending in the league and the Scottish
Cup. Players must respond and show they can take a step further.''
While he makes these observations, the Aberdeen manager also concedes that the
dallying with relegation last season left an unfortunate legacy at Pittodrie.
``It is a constant education process after what happened last season,'' he
said. ``Players have got to get into my way of thinking, which will also take
time.
``It is going to be more difficult to get them to do it over 36 games in the
league. So far I have not made major changes, buying just two players. When
things are not working out, different permutations are tried, but you must have
real strength in depth to do this. At the moment I am still building towards
this.''
He is asking for wins in his next three home games, starting tomorrow night
against Kilmarnock, to produce a greater threat to the Old Firm.
Striker Scott Booth and midfielder Stephen Glass, missing against Partick
Thistle, seem certain to return. And Eoin Jess, taken off with a thigh strain
at Firhill, is making a rapid recovery.
KEVIN Gallacher, the Scottish internationalist striker, could earn a surprise
recall to the bench for Blackburn Rovers' final Champions' League fixture
against Rosenborg at Ewood Park tomorrow night.
Gallacher, who has not appeared in the first team since injuring a hamstring in
the season's opening game, has played and scored in three junior and reserve
games and could be drafted in as Rovers are down to 12 fit experienced players
- including two keepers.
Gallacher, who has played only two games since breaking a leg at Highbury in
February, 1994, could continue his rehabilitation in today's Pontin's League
game at home to Bolton.
THE all-seater stadium being built near Paris for the 1998 World Cup finals is
to be called Stade de France, thus ending weeks of debate within the country.
The 80,000 arena is being built in St Denis, just north of the capital, to
stage the opening match and the final.
ALEX McLeish was booked in Motherwell's 1-0 defeat by Hibernian in a Premier
Reserve League match at Easter Road yesterday.
The Motherwell manager played against a strong home side which included Andy
Millen, Joe Tortolano, Mickey Weir, and Gareth Evans. Mike Renwick scored the
only goal of the game after 31 minutes.
CHRIS Myers, freed by Dundee United, is on a fortnight's trial with
Dunfermline and played last night in the reserves against East Fife.
Stephen Glass: seems certain to return for tomorrow night's match against
Kilmarnock at Pittodrie.
</TEXT>
