<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Late finish is not enough for Burns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044682</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S Richard Burns closed to within five seconds of winner Tommi Makinen,
but still had to settle for third place after a thrilling climax     to the
Rally of Thailand              yesterday.
Burns, driving a Subaru, finished a second behind Kenneth Eriksson, putting in
a storming late effort after having failed to significantly reduce Makinen's
21-second overnight lead in yesterday's early stages.
Burns, third in last month's Network Q RAC Rally, expressed his dismay at
having to settle for that position again. ``To be just five seconds from
winning and to finish third after more than 168 miles is disappointing,'' he
said.
``It's been a great battle against Kenneth and Tommi - we've pushed each other
to the limit and I've thoroughly enjoyed it.''
Makinen's triumph helped his Mitsubishi team secure the Asia-Pacific
championship manufacturers' title.
q THE Pacific grand prix team have withdrawn from Formula One for financial
reasons. The team, who in February formed an alliance with Team Lotus, have
struggled to make an impact and failed to win a world championship point during
their two years in the sport.
Pacific's managing director, Keith Wiggins, said: ``We have tried hard to
establish our position in F1, but due to the difficult financial position we
have not been able to progress in the way we planned.''
The withdrawal of Pacific - whose 1995 drivers were Belgian Bertrand Gachot and
Andrea Montermini of Italy - leaves the world championship with only 11 teams,
and 22 cars for next year.
</TEXT>
