<TEXT>
n.THE confectionary company which produced sweets such as Skullcrushers and
Munchy Maggots has gone into receivership. Choc-u-Luv, of Glenrothes, once
employed 500 people but its last 40 employees have now been laid off. ``It is
too early to estimate the level of debts but it appears unlikely the ordinary
creditors will receive any dividend,'' said provisional liquidator Graham
Ritchie of accountant Ernst &amp; Young.
n.TEXTILES group Coats Viyella has sold Compton Webb, part of its clothing
division, to a new company for around #11.6m. The company will be formed
through management buy-outs from Compton Webb and PUC, which used to be owned
by Davis Service Group.
The two businesses will be merged to form the new firm, which has received
backing from 3i, Murray Johnstone and the Midland Bank.
n.IT is all change at the top of international chemical company Courtaulds. At
the AGM on July 16, 1996, Sir Christopher Hogg will retire as non-executive
chairman and will leave the board. In addition, chief executive Sipko Huismans
is also retiring, after 35 years service.
After spending almost all their working lives in Courtaulds both men feel the
time is right to make way for their successors. Sir Christopher will be
replaced by Sir David Lees of GKN, already a non-executive director. Gordon
Campbell, currently deputy chief executive (operations) will become chief
executive.
</TEXT>
