<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Countess fails to answer the 90,000-acre question</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044685</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE direct descendant of the Englishman blamed for the most notorious of last
century's Highland clearances has been asked to hand over 90,000 acres of land
free of charge.
Mrs Betty Mackenzie put it straight to the Countess of Sutherland, whose
forebear, the first Duke of Sutherland, cleared 8000 tenants to make way for
sheep.
Mrs Mackenzie said: ``Why do you not give us the land for nothing.''
The duchess replied: ``Could you manage it?''
Mrs Mackenzie, clerk to the Skerray grazing committee, said yesterday: ``It was
an informal meeting and I thought I would take the chance to ask the countess.
After all, the estate next door at Melness has been offered to crofters for
nothing. She was very nice about it but I did not get a full answer.''
Yesterday, the countess, speaking from her London home, said: ``Yes, Betty
asked about the possibility of the crofts and crofting land being handed over
to the crofters free of charge. It is different from the Melness case, because
I have got family to consider. I have 12 grandchildren and eight of them are
boys. The rents question was a mistake and it was something I did not know
about. But everyone will be meeting in spring, when people have had a chance to
think about things.''
She insisted: ``Nothing has been ruled out.''
Last month, the 74-year-old countess stepped in to a rent row involving 130
crofters at Tongue, Borgie, and Skerray in the far north of Sutherland.
She vetoed plans by her son and heir, Lord Strathnaver, and factor Christopher
Whealing for massive rent increases.
The countess said : ``I am sensitive to local feeling.''
</TEXT>
