<DOCNO>GH951205-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cross-Dressing in the Depression, Traverse Theatre, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044687</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cruel financial pressures of the Depression tear a family apart: the father
sent to a state penitentiary, the mother to a brothel and the son to an
orphanage. The boy's sexual awakening coincides with his arrival at another
house of ill repute, the austere advice of his Boy Scout manual contrasting
sharply with the nightly chorus of bed-springs in the rooms around him. In his
innocence he falls for one of the working girls who refuses to take advantage
of him until, one way or another, true love wins out.
Not much of a story, but in Erin Cressida Wilson's poetic hour-long telling it
becomes a thing of beguiling appeal. The heightened language is beautifully
crafted, delicate and elegant; too spartan and too lucid to fall into
self-indulgence, and too much rooted in its earthy subject matter to allow it
to become whimsical.
Indeed there's a great tension between the brutal, functional language of male
sexuality at its most mechanical, and the romantic gestures of hope embodied in
typical Wilson images of melting ice, bursting cocoons and the lingering moon.
The microphones and overhead projections of Peter Mackie Burns's production
might suggest another bout of contemporary ``experimental'' theatre at its most
cliched, but in fact this is a supremely well-measured interpretation, not
afraid to be still and quiet, yet rarely losing the cool, clear momentum of the
dialogue, and getting much creative mileage from a tight budget.
I suspect it's too fragile a piece to make a long-lasting impression, but
seductive, slick and sympathetic performances from Molly Innes, Stephen
McCreadie and Joel Strachan ensure that every bit of its subtle charm is
present on the night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Look At  Me When I'm Talking To You, Theatre Royal, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044688</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAME Edna Everage's week-long sojourn in Glasgow has three distinct sections.
In matching fashion, its constituent parts can be awarded three ascending
grades. A low C mark - C for cadaver, in fact - goes to Sandy Stone, a
mouldering representative of the undead who delivers a long, rambling, and
fatally-theatrical monologue about things not being what they were when he was
alive.
Old stalwart Sir Les Patterson earns a middling B: B for his heroic capacity
for burping, for his blotchy face, and his smut-peddlar's debt to St Benny
(Hill) and St Bernard (Manning). Hurrah for Sir Les's grotesque
trouser-contortions, his sprays of spittle, and his troupe of saucily-clad
nubiles! Double hurrah for his mirthful mis-use of the word pianist and his
description of his wife's haemorrhoid treatment!
But it's a treble hurrah and a big A grading for Dame Edna, who brought last
night's opening show to a rousing conclusion. A for Australian, of course. But
A for Audience-manipulation, too. For the mischievous Dame Edna plays an
audience as a spider plays with flies: spinning gauzy webs which make mincemeat
out of the unsuspecting.
Having swiftly gauged the status of the top balcony - ``paupers'' - Dame Edna
set her sights on the stalls. Second row, woman in a red dress, wide mouth:
``Don't stand on street corners, Letterbox.'' Directing a woundingly-innocent
inquiry towards Betty from Pollok: ``Pollok? Is that as nice as it sounds?''
Dame Edna's comedy of refined cruelty reached its apogee when young Eaglesham
bungalow-dwellers Ivor and Elaine were suddenly confronted with their manifest
failings in the baby-sitting department. Dame Edna Everage? Above average.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dawson has few admirers among peers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044689</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH textiles group Dawson International has plummeted in the estimation of
its sector stablemates to become one of the UK's ``least admired'' companies.
Among the pick of the crop in Scotland in their respective sectors, according
to a poll in this month's issue of Management Today, are Bank of Scotland,
Royal Bank of Scotland, ScottishPower, and General Accident.
The survey, which takes in the views of senior directors of the 10 largest UK
players in each of 25 sectors, is based on the premise that those best
qualified to assess a company's strengths and weaknesses are the senior
management of its direct competitors.
In each sector the directors were asked to rate their nine stablemates
according to nine criteria. Companies were judged on their quality of
management, financial soundness, quality of products or services, value as a
long-term investment, capacity to innovate, quality of marketing, community and
environmental responsibility, use of corporate assets, and ability to attract,
develop and retain top talent.
March's boardroom coup at Dawson, which has just moved its headquarters from
Edinburgh to Kinross, came too late to halt its spectacular fall in the eyes of
its peers.
In 1990, the textiles group was ranked second in its sector and 48th out of the
210 companies which were then included in the survey. By last year, it had
fallen to 212th position, out of 260. This year it was the sixth-least admired
company.
Dawson, which uses golfer Nick Faldo to promote its flagship Pringle brand, was
judged to have the best products and marketing back in 1990. This year, its
peers considered its marketing worst in the sector.
On a more positive note, the Scottish clearers have grown in the estimation of
their fellows banks.
``Big four'' bank Lloyds was held in the highest regard, followed by Bank of
Scotland, the most admired Scottish company in 57th position overall, and Royal
Bank of Scotland.
Lloyds, as a result of its merger with 213th-placed TSB, will soon be
registered in Edinburgh.
ScottishPower has the respect of the electricity sector. The Glasgow-based
utility, although down from 96th to 116th position in the top 250, was the
third-most admired electricity company behind English generators PowerGen and
National Power.
In insurance, Perth-based General Accident was ranked third behind Prudential
Corporation and Commercial Union.
Although not in the top three in their respective sectors, brewing giant
Scottish &amp; Newcastle, hotels and casinos group Stakis, and engineering group
Weir were all rated highly.
Cadbury Schweppes, which this year made its largest-ever acquisition in the
form of Dr Pepper/Seven-Up, was the most admired company in the UK. Rentokil,
which came out top last year, fell to 11th position.
Troubled conglomerate Trafalgar House registered the lowest score, with Channel
tunnel operator Eurotunnel not far ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
