<DOCNO>GH951205-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Debit report on bank service</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANKS should take responsibility for their mistakes and stop blaming computer
errors, according to a consumer watchdog.
The National Consumer Council claimed yesterday that many banks had lost the
personal touch, and too often gave preferential treatment to customers not
experiencing hardships.
The council organised eight discussion groups in locations throughout England
to gauge customers' views on the financial services they received. It concluded
that there was a need for a free advice service to help people avoid financial
difficulties.
``Banks and insurance companies happily compete for new customers, but our
survey shows that their enthusiasm wanes once consumers experience money
problems,'' said council chairman Lady Wilcox.
``They provide an umbrella when the sun shines, but take it away at the first
sign of rain. We want to see the return of the personal touch to financial
services, and a new emphasis on the needs of people on low incomes and those in
hardship.''
The report says that banks should make more use of their knowledge of peoples'
personal circumstances. Customers who overdraw a day before their pay goes into
their account should not be sent a threatening letter - for which they have to
pay.
The consumer body said computers should also be programmed to ignore one-off
hiccups: ``We had so many complaints about this kind of thing,'' said a
spokeswoman.
q The Midland Bank has snubbed the Government over its plans to involve the
bank in backing student loans. Other financial institutions have also made it
clear that they are unlikely to join a new loans scheme.
They cite customer reaction and their fear of alienating students as future
customers among their reasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000082</DOCNO>
