<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ferguson seeks court ruling on match ban</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044691</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERTON and former Rangers striker Duncan Ferguson today will ask the Scottish
courts to allow him to make an immediate return to football.
Ferguson, who recently completed a three-month spell in Barlinnie for
head-butting former Raith Rovers defender John McStay, is seeking a judicial
review of the decision by the Scottish Football Association to suspend him for
12 matches over the same incident.
A full hearing of the judicial review is not expected to take place for some
time and, meantime, Ferguson will ask a judge at the Court of Session today for
recall of his suspension.
The player and his club feel that he has good grounds for challenging the SFA
ban.
Ferguson was convicted at Glasgow Sheriff Court in May this year for assaulting
John McStay during a Premier Division game between Rangers and Raith Rovers at
Ibrox in April 1994.
In October this year, three appeal court judges rejected his claim that the
sentence was excessive and Ferguson began his jail sentence.
The court was told that Ferguson had three previous convictions for assault and
was on probation for an offence when the Ibrox incident took place.
Lord Hope, the Lord Justice General, made it clear that the courts did not wish
to intervene in physical contact sports.
He added, however: ``When acts are done which go well beyond what can be
regarded as normal physical contact and an assault is committed, the court has
a duty to condemn and punish such conduct.
``A footballer who assaults another player on the football field is not
entitled to expect leniency from the court just because the incident occurred
in the course of a football match.''
The SFA ban, which had been suspended during the court proceedings, took effect
on Ferguson's release from Barlinnie last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
