<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044692</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE industrial upheaval in France could affect the draw for the 1998 World Cup
qualifiers in Paris a week today.
FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said: ``It would be foolish not to be concerned.
But the local organising committee know their backyard better than we do and
they tell us they can cope. However, if there is a deterioration of the
situation, there's likely to be a problem.''
Asked if FIFA had contingency plans to switch the draw or change the date,
Cooper added: ``All sensible organisations have contingency plans for what
might go wrong. But our plans are to stage the draw in Paris on December 12.''
FIFA delegations will arrive in France from tomorrow for meetings in advance of
the draw, which is being staged at the Louvre in the presence of French
president, Jacques Chirac.
A record 172 countries have entered the World Cup and the draw for the
qualifying competition will be televised live round the globe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firhill incident puts football in the dock again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044693</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE procurator-fiscal in Glasgow yesterday ordered a police investigation into
Saturday's Partick Thistle-Aberdeen football match in which Dons skipper
Stewart McKimmie was sent off for allegedly elbowing an opponent.
In a separate development, the Crown Office confirmed that it is considering
whether it should provide procurators fiscal throughout the country with
guidelines about incidents on the field of play.
The Glasgow fiscal's decision to ask Strathclyde Police for a report on
Saturday's game is the latest in a series of interventions by the criminal
justice system in football pitch incidents.
McKimmie, 33, was shown the red card just nine minutes into the game at Firhill
when he clashed with Partick's Callum Milne, who was booked for his part in the
incident.
The Aberdeen captain, who is a member of the Scotland squad and has won 36
caps, has been fined #500 by his club.
A spokesman for the fiscal's office said yesterday: ``We have asked the police
to supply certain information on the match at the weekend.''
The latest request from the Glasgow fiscal's office follows its demand for a
report on alleged on-field incidents at the Rangers-Aberdeen match at Ibrox on
November 11. Police inquiries into that game are continuing.
Yesterday, Aberdeen manager Roy Aitken refused to comment on police
investigations into Saturday's match.
He said the club would hold the same position it took after police inquiries
were launched following his team's match against Rangers last month.
The controversy over criminal law's relationship with sport has raged since
Duncan Ferguson made football history by becoming the first professional to be
jailed for an on-field assault on another player.
The Everton striker was released last month from Glasgow's Barlinnie Prison
after serving half of a three-month sentence for butting Raith Rovers player
John McStay in April 1994 while playing for Rangers.
Yesterday, The Herald asked the Crown Office to comment on reports that it was
preparing to issue a set of guidelines for fiscals. A spokesman said: ``The
Lord Advocate is considering whether to issue guidance to procurators fiscal
and chief constables. He intends to discuss some of the implications with chief
constables.''
Broadcaster Jock Brown, who is a sports law consultant with the Glasgow-based
Harper Macleod legal firm, said yesterday: ``I am entirely in favour of
guidelines because there is great uncertainty right now. There is also the
question of consistency among different regional procurators fiscal.
``I hope those guidelines distinguish between on-the-ball and off-the-ball
incidents, and leave the former to the referee and the SFA to sort out.''
McKimmie's red card at Saturday's Firhill game means an automatic one-match
suspension and he will miss tomorrow's Premier League game against Kilmarnock
at Pittodrie. It is understood the SFA is unlikely to punish McKimmie further,
given the immediate action of the referee and the swift response of his club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fringe lays out its table</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044694</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The fiftieth Fringe should be the biggest yet, says Mark Fisher, who learns of
a drive worldwide to encourage everyone andtheir auntie to perform
NOT content with presiding over the biggest arts festival in the world,
director Hilary Strong seems determined to make the Edinburgh Festival Fringe
even bigger. If that isn't quite her intention as she continues a programme of
international travel in the run up to the 50th birthday of the city's three
oldest festivals, it will more than likely be the result.
The Fringe has long had a practice of holding meetings every year in London to
explain the whys and wherefores of the event to would-be performers from
England. Strong's predecessor, Mhairi Mackenzie Robinson, also visited the
United States towards the end of her tenure to explain the set-up to companies
over there. In this same spirit, Hilary Strong has recognised that the further
performers have to travel, the less likely they are to understand the workings
of Edinburgh's unique free-market cultural jamboree, and she's given herself
the task of seeking out artists the world over to tell them what they're likely
to lose and gain by performing in the Scottish capital.
With 49 Fringes under our belts, it's easy for those of us living here to take
the event for granted. The Fringe is the Fringe, it happens because it happens,
and its thrill is its unpredictability. But Strong and her team working year
round know there's rather more to it than that and, without wanting to dull its
wayward spirit, they can see there's room for improvement. Strong's watchword
is accessibility - for performers and public alike - and she recognises that
the finer points of a festival that is both spontaneous and organised, that is
free as long as you pay for your place in the programme, your venue hire and
your accommodation, are not the easiest to come to terms with.
That's certainly what she found on a recent trip to Poland, her first venture
into Eastern Europe, where the culture gap makes the Edinburgh Fringe look even
more of a curious phenomenon than it already is. For the average Polish artist,
festival participation only comes about after receiving an official invitation
to perform. The idea that both the initiative and the financial risk might be
borne by the performer is hard to get to grips with.
After the penny had finally dropped at one of the Polish meetings, one
participant explained to Strong that to call the Fringe a festival was simply
too confusing to Eastern Europeans - a better description, he said, would be
that it was like going to a market and hiring a table, and the amount of money
you had to spend determined the size of table you could afford. ``We had to use
that analogy so they could understand what we were talking about,'' says
Strong. ``But although a lot of these companies find the whole thing bizarre,
many of them want to come to do it.''
Strong has identified Eastern Europe, and Poland in particular, as the place
most in need of clear information about Edinburgh. That the standard of work
coming out of this area is exceptionally high has been ably demonstrated in the
Fringe programmes of Richard Demarco and Tomek Bork of Edinburgh Venue
Associates - both of whom got involved in Strong's Polish trip. But by opening
up better lines of communication and providing the full administrative
resources of the Fringe Society itself, Strong believes that both the companies
and Edinburgh can be better served.
``The most important thing about Poland was to come away with registration
forms for companies that could then be in direct contact with the Fringe,'' she
says. ``That was achieved. I don't think there's anything wrong with puffing
the Fringe because we know that when it does work it's a great experience for
them. Most of the problems that we've had in the past relate to Eastern
European companies that have come to the Fringe without having direct contact
with us. In every situation that goes wrong it's because we don't know about it
in advance, whether it's a British company, an American company or whatever.''
On this particular trip Strong travelled to Krakow and Warsaw, meeting
representatives from theatre companies, the British Council, the Ministry of
Culture, Visiting Arts (an organisation dedicated to giving financial support
to artists journeying to Britain), and from civic arts officers. Reactions
varied from the enthusiastic to the indifferent, making Strong aware that her
role falls somewhere in-between the supportive and the proselytising. She is
not a programmer and is in no position to invite artists to the Fringe, but she
can make things easier for those who want to come, and she can sing Edinburgh's
praises to those who need to know more.
It's a policy she hopes to continue over the next two or three years. She held
one meeting in the US before this year's Fringe and she'll take the opportunity
of a private holiday in New York later this month to hold another one there. In
Eastern Europe she's got her eye on Moscow, St Petersburg, Minsk, and Kiev, and
after that she'll move on to Western Europe.
``A lot of companies from France, Germany, Italy, and Spain will take the view
that it's perfectly OK to go to the Avignon Off, but not to the Edinburgh
Fringe, and we have to challenge that view. I think it's probably the language
question. A lot of people ask me if it's a problem doing a show in a foreign
language, and the answer is no - obviously it's a slightly minority audience,
but in Edinburgh more than anywhere people are prepared to go through that.''
With all this travelling on the cards, Strong inevitably has language barriers
of her own to overcome, but she reckons she's at least stumbled upon the one
off-hand remark that can raise a smile in any language. ``The best thing was I
discovered my standard joke that works in every language,'' she says. ``I say,
`Anyone can come to the Fringe, even your auntie,' and that always gets them
laughing.''
</TEXT>
