<DOCNO>GH951205-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting to grips with corporate guidance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Aileen Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a pity, writes Stuart Paul, that the issue of corporate governance - the
way in which companies are directed and controlled - only came to prominence in
the UK in the wake of a string of well documented corporate disasters.
Remember Polly Peck? the shameful fate of Maxwell pensioners? you can add your
own favourite to this sorry catalogue.
The debate on governance was further fuelled by the role, many argue the
ineffectual role, of non-executive directors in the light of huge rises in
boardroom pay.
Are ``non execs'' an essential part of an effective checks and balances system
in the boardroom? an essential link between the shareholders and the full-time
directors who run the business? or are they simply toothless tigers picking up
handsome fees for occasional attendance?
Whatever your viewpoint the debate on corporate governance will be of interest
to everyone who is concerned that our great companies should be well managed.
It is appropriate that, following hard upon the appointment of the new
committee on corporate governance, we look at recent books on the subject. Our
reviewer is Aileen Beattie, above, director of accounting and auditing at the
Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland.
HARDLY a day seems to go by without reference being made in the press to
corporate governance issues.
However, some influential figures have recently expressed the view that
excessive emphasis is being placed on the subject, not only in the press but in
business in general. So are we in danger of losing sight of the benefits of
good corporate governance under a raft of rules and regulations?
There can be no doubt that the UK's first committee on corporate governance,
the Cadbury Committee, was badly needed to restore confidence in our corporate
governance framework, but its newly formed successor (chaired by Sir Ronald
Hampel) must tread a careful path between improvement and overkill.
In addition to any guidance which may emerge from the Hampel Committee,
directors can, of course, strive to improve their performance and understanding
of their role by recognising the importance of continuing professional
development.
Research published in April this year by the Institute of Management considers
this point. In Coming on Board - the non-executive directors' role in
strengthening boardroom leadership*, Patrick Mileham states his belief that by
definition, non-executives are generalists who should not normally view their
job as a specialist function. However, corporate governance and what one might
call advanced directorship knowledge and competencies are increasingly expected
of them.
This research revealed a strong consensus in favour of the training and
continuing professional development of all directors, but with non-executives
requiring training to cover strategy, regulatory matters and generalist
subjects.
The concept of whole board training and development was considered to be of
value, although this is likely to prove one of the most challenging areas for
those providing the training.
All in all, this is a book which any potential or current non-executive
director would find helpful when striving to identify what exactly their role
should be. It also has the obvious advantage of covering UK issues, much of the
literature is geared to the US market.
One such recently published book is, however, worth dipping into for an insight
into the American experience of corporate governance, Corporate Governance* by
Monks and Minow, though intended primarily as an academic text, is an extremely
comprehensive yet readable analysis of the subject.
The authors are well-known US scholars and activists, a combination of talents
which flow through into the book in their ability to bring the theory to life
by use of ``case in point'' examples.
The technique used is to address a theoretical issue, give an example, ask the
reader to form a view and then probe further by asking ``would your view have
changed if . . . ?'' This is a very effective way of making the reader think
about the issues rather than merely read the book. A UK version of this book
would be a useful training tool for directors.
The book also includes a chapter on international governance, which is very
much an up and coming topic. Indeed, I have recently been involved in working
for the International Capital Markets Group (ICMG) to produce a book called Who
holds the reins?*
ICMG, a joint-venture of the international bodies of lawyers, accountants and
stock exchanges, recognised that with the advancement of multinational listings
on stock exchanges worldwide and interest being taken in foreign markets by
institutional and private shareholders, there was a need to consider the
international dimension to corporate governance.
The book concludes that no attempt should be made to prescribe an international
standard for corporate governance, as the frameworks used around the world were
so deeply engrained in the cultures of the countries. Instead, major companies
should be encouraged to disclose key areas of their corporate governance
processes to enable international investors to understand the differences and
to take account of them in their decision-making.
The key to these proposals is that, to be competitive, companies need to be
dynamic and progressive. Corporate governance should not restrict such
dynamism, but rather give it direction.
Hopefully, future improvements in corporate governance worldwide will heed
this, but there is always the danger that books such as the ICMG one, which put
forward recommendations, will sit and gather dust on a shelf. Let us hope that
this will not be the case.
So, as corporate governance is still obviously alive and well, we will continue
to draw on books such as those mentioned here to help us develop our thinking
on a subject which is of importance to national and international companies
alike.
*Coming on Board by Patrick Mileham. *Corporate Governance by R Monks &amp; N
Minow. *Who holds the reins? by ICMG.
Book review is compiled and edited by Stuart Paul of the University of Paisley.
1 The Empty Raincoat, Charles Handy
2 Competing for the Future, Hamel &amp; Prahalad
3 The Naked Manager for The Nineties, Peter Drucker
4 The Ascendant Organisation, Peter Wickens
5 Great Answers to Tough Interview Questions, Martin John Yate
6 Great Scots In Business, Terry Houston
7 Company Man, Anthony Sampson
8 Investment Biker, Jim Rogers
9 Beyond Certainty, Charles Handy
10 Mindstore, Jack Black
Data supplied by John Smith and Son, Bookshops
</TEXT>
