<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Investment clients need confidence to bank on</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Business Comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044697</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the space of a few days in October, Dunedin Fund Managers lost its chairman,
its deputy chief executive, the heads of its European and Pacific operations,
and its Chicago-based marketing director.
Not surprisingly, three United States clients have upped sticks as a result of
the debacle.
Following the departure of another six fund managers yesterday, British Linen
Bank chief executive Eric Sanderson is sure there is nothing more to emerge
from what has turned out to be a Pandora's Box. Only time will tell what damage
has been done.
No doubt, Mr Sanderson will be worried by the rumblings from the board of
Edinburgh Investment Trust, which has a major stake in Dunedin. However, it
would seem any or all of the investment trusts would only seriously consider
defecting to another fund management outfit as a last resort.
With the backing of a giant in the form of Bank of Scotland, it is unlikely
that Dunedin will be allowed to fall further from grace. If it had been an
independently-quoted investment house, the dangers would have been far greater.
Mr Sanderson had to sort out the astonishing rifts which opened up as a result
of the departure of investment director Gordon Anderson and could not be
accused of having left the job half done.
The key now is confidence. Dunedin's clients need a signal that it is back on
track. The Bank of Scotland may yet have to take the bull by the horns and
expand Dunedin through acquisition.
Market fizz
THE #425m purchase of Courage by Scottish &amp; Newcastle appears to have been
timed fortuitously as the UK beer market may be struggling back to its feet.
That is despite the depredations caused by the imports through Calais. There
are also indications the pub trade is showing some growth, partly because of
the success in attracting women to themed outlets.
But there is a pronounced north-south divide. Courage volumes in the three
months under S.&amp;.N control jumped 7.5%, whereas the core S.&amp;.N operations were
up by just 1%. The net result was flat S.&amp;.N brewing profits with the #9m
uplift in divisional operating profit due entirely to Courage - and so it seems
likely to continue.
There are indications of some improvement in consumer confidence, particularly
in the South of England if the rise in Courage volumes is a reliable guide,
although that was in part weather related with outside drinking and the
availability of pub gardens much commoner, for obvious reasons, than in
Scotland.
Market reaction to S.&amp;.N's half-time results was somewhat negative, attention
focusing on the rationalisation costs which were #50m higher than expected.
That seemed more important than the #75m of annual savings, which were almost
twice initial calculations.
With a beer market share up to 30% according to some calculations and 25% on
S.&amp;.N's own reckoning, the pressures imposed on the sector by the four industry
leaders, Scottish Courage, Bass, Carlsberg Tetley, and Whitbread, will increase
the need for the smaller operators to consolidate or else change their spots to
become pub companies - Greene King and Vaux are the most likely. Bass will not
sit back as quietly as it has in the last two or three months for much longer.
And what price for Center Parcs now? Again profits were flat in local currency
terms and there seems no rush to add to the existing portfolio with little
being said about new openings. Under S.&amp;.N ownership, it has so far done very
well. Its parent's corporate strategy has been the most successful in the
industry in the past decade but it may be time to move it on.
Fiery Forte
GRANADA came out of the traps running in its bid for Forte, mostly thanks to
the dynamic strategy of its chief executive and chairman elect Gerry Robinson.
The Forte track record is scarcely a major defensive asset for a company under
siege but there may be something of a sea change under way although it is still
early days.
Forte's statement yesterday that it was putting high profile assets up for sale
is the first thing of substance it has said since the bid was announced.
However, there are still many mountains to climb and paths to follow into dense
undergrowth which may well lead to unexpected places.
It would have been fascinating to have been a fly on the wall when the decision
was taken to sell the Savoy stake. So painfully acquired over eight years as
the Forte's passport to the highest echelons, it is now to be sold to fend off
the pressing attentions of another motorway cafe owner.
Savoy now has a market value of about #230m but a street price somewhat lower,
even if the Barclay Brothers did pay #75m for the Ritz. Altogether, the 68%
owned hotel company, the roadside restaurants, the White Hart and Travelodge
businesses should raise about #1450m and will seriously dent the projected
Granada cash flow that is expected from its disposal programmne of Forte assets.
In a term that Mr Robinson may live to regret, he said that hotels were simply
repetitive business, something which patrons of the luxury end of the market
will not forget.
So far Granada has said nothing of substance - only sound bites. It will need
to seize the initiative again soon or else it could start being pushed
seriously on to the defensive.
</TEXT>
