<DOCNO>GH951205-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wife driven to stab spouse was suffering from `battered woman syndrome', appeal court told Killer `had snapped after abuse'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SARA Thornton, jailed nearly six years ago for killing her alcoholic husband,
had snapped after a long period of drunken abuse and should not have been
convicted of murder, the Court of Appeal heard yesterday.
Evidence not used at her trial showed her suffering from ``battered woman
syndrome'' which could cause someone to lose self control and act in the heat
of the moment, making her guilty of manslaughter but not murder, said Mr
Michael Mansfield QC, for Thornton.
An expert witness had stated that the wives of alcoholics ``lived on the edge
of a volcano'' and could easily snap as a result of a culmination of
provocation over a long time.
Sexual taunts - such as those levelled by Malcolm Thornton on the night he died
when he called his wife a whore and threatened to kill her if she had been
selling her body - were particularly hurtful to such women and caused deep
emotional wounds.
Thornton, 38, of Atherstone, Warwicks, was jailed for life in February 1990 for
murdering her husband, a former policeman, with a single blow from a kitchen
knife as he lay drunk on a sofa.
Her original appeal was rejected in 1991 when judges refused to quash her
conviction or even reduce it to manslaughter on the grounds of provocation
before the killing. The court held there had been no ``sudden and temporary
loss of self-control''.
However, her case was referred back to the Court of Appeal by Home Secretary
Michael Howard in May this year and she was released on bail, pending appeal,
on July 28.
The case highlighted the issue of women driven to kill by repeated abuse. Other
women convicted of domestic murder have since been freed.
Mr Mansfield told Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice, sitting with Mr Justice
Hidden and Mrs Justice Ebsworth, that Thornton's trial lawyers put forward a
defence of diminished responsibility because she was suffering from a
personality disorder.
The issue of prior provocation and its effect on her had not been investigated
fully.
In one of a series of exchanges with Mr Mansfield, Lord Taylor said that if
Thornton had snapped and suddenly lost control, one would have expected some
remorse afterwards.
Instead, she told police: ``Let the bastard die.'' She spoke also about having
sharpened the knife.
Mr Mansfield replied that, according to expert witnesses, such responses were
consistent with ``dissociative behaviour'' by someone not wishing to face
reality.
In fact, Thornton did show remorse. When told her husband had died, she said:
``Oh my God. I loved him so much.'' She told how she had tried for a year to
save him from excessive drinking and said she could not believe she had killed
him.
Lord Taylor stressed that to establish manslaughter rather than murder, there
had to be sudden loss of control - the court had said in an earlier case that
this requirement could be removed only by Parliament.
He said: ``Selecting a knife, sharpening it, and then doing the act seems more
like vengeance.''
Mr Mansfield replied that, if that was really what happened, the question arose
whether Thornton took the knife to defend herself against possible violence
from her drunken husband and then used it under provocation.
``The evidence indicates that the type of provocative conduct issued by this
victim would plainly upset, anger, and provoke a woman with a personality
disorder and with the history of a battered woman,'' he said.
The hearing continues today, when Crown counsel will oppose the appeal.
</TEXT>
