<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saluting the master of a lost art</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OF all the performers who mattered to Alexander Gibson, Janet Baker was surely
the one who mattered most. First in Cosi fan tutte, then in The Trojans and Der
Rosenkavalier, she helped him to establish Scottish Opera as a company with its
own proud personality, at a time when every production was both an event and a
triumph, and famous singers found themselves lured into roles they had never
tackled before.
Tonight Dame Janet will be back in Glasgow to pay tribute to a conductor who
clearly mattered as much to her as she to him. Who would have expected this
most serious of opera singers to be a success in comedy, turning Mozart's
Dorabella, the giddier of the two sisters in Cosi, into a portrayal delicious
in its comic timing?
Dido, in Berlioz's epic opera, was more obviously her scene, but even in this
role she startled her audiences with the sustained intensity of expression she
brought to music in which she indelibly charted the tragic queen's progress
from love to death.
As Octavian in Strauss's Rosenkavalier she portrayed, no less tellingly, a
different sort of love and Sir Alexander found that he had drawn from her yet
another of her precisely focused characterisations.
What was it - I asked her last week - that made their operatic partnership work
so well? All singers have their favourite conductors, but Gibson, she says,
earned her ``absolute admiration'' in his handling of the balance between stage
and pit. ``He looked after our voices in the most instinctive way and with a
constant understanding of their size and quality. He had this special ability
to underpin a musical line without diminishing it. It was the art of
accompaniment and it's becoming a lost art.''
Dame Janet last met Gibson in the autumn of 1994 when he was conducting a new
production of Tosca at the London Coliseum. Again, she says, she was aware of
``his grasp, his relaxed and understated control in the pit, his ability to
nurse the singers the way they should be nursed. You seldom hear operatic
conducting like it''.
His personality, she claims, was of the most special nature. ``I would have
done anything for Alex, so inspired was I by his enthusiasm. I was prepared to
make any effort to be with the company as much as I possibly could, for he had
this remarkable ability to attract people who would work for the idea rather
than for stardom.''
Does she believe he fulfilled himself? ``In many ways, yes - though after the
first years of adulation, being a prophet in your own country can place you at
a disadvantage. It would be criminal if Scotland forgot his contribution. New
faces are right and necessary, but nobody did for Scotland the things that Alex
did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McFarlane will appeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUMBARTON will appeal against the five-match suspension on keeper Ian McFarlane
imposed last week by the SFA, and that will allow the player to make a comeback
for the struggling first division side on Saturday against St Mirren while
waiting for a hearing.
The Boghead club are upset at the severity of the punishment imposed on
McFarlane, red-carded twice for the one incident against Airdrie. Referee
George Clyde reported him for allegedly headbutting and throwing a punch at
striker Jim McIntyre.
McIntyre had suggested that it was ``handbags at 10 paces,'' but the McFarlane
punishment means that he will be out for eight games.
The keeper has already served the automatic, three-match ban from the offences,
but still has the additional five matches imposed to sit out.
Meanwhile, newly signed keeper Ken Meechan, from Greenock Juniors, will play
tonight for Dumbarton as they return to Tayside to face Dundee.
Meechan comes in for 17-year-old Peter Dennison, but manager Jim Fallon
stressed yesterday: ``That decision was taken before we lost eight to Dundee
United on Saturday. We do not want to ask too much of Peter, for he is still a
young lad.
``I cannot blame him for what went on during Saturday's game. He had
experienced players in front of him, but their defending was shocking.''
Fallon will make other changes, but admitted: ``We do not have a big pool of
players so it is very difficult. I will move things around, but these are the
same players who won us promotion last season. It will be difficult going back
to Tayside so soon, but it is a different game and a different team we face, so
it is up to us to lift our game.''
Meantime, Dundee are set to hand midfielder Gary McKeown the chance to help
them go top of the first division promotion race tonight - and prove to himself
that the age of miracles has not passed.
The former Arsenal player, out for 15 months with a series of major knee
injuries, returned to the side as a substitute as Dundee won 2-1 at Paisley on
Saturday. Manager Jim Duffy hinted last night that McKeown's passing style
could be a crucial factor against Dumbarton, with Dundee needing a win to edge
in front for the first time this season.
``It would be superb to have the chance of being involved in a game like this
after what I've been through over the last couple of years,'' said McKeown.
``There were times when I wondered if I would ever play again as I lay in a
hospital bed with drips sticking out of my knee. Saturday meant a lot when I
played the second-half and my aim now is simply to try to make a challenge for
a first team place.
``There is still a long way to go in this promotion race, but going to the
front would mean the others would have to try to knock us off the top for a
change.''
And McKeown believes that could take some doing. ``We didn't play well against
St Mirren and can be more pleased with the result than the performance, because
we spent most of the time defending after I came on. But we did show
character.''
McKeown also revealed he was never allowed to feel too sorry for himself during
his injury ordeal. ``I spent a lot of time working with a couple of other lads
with long-term injuries while I was trying to get back.
``One of them - Dougie Bell - has had to give up the game and the other -
Gordon Tannock - has just undergone his tenth operation. So I really have
learned that there is always someone worse off.''
Dundee will still be without winger Neil McCann tonight, and player-manager
Duffy also is ruled out. His place in defence will go to Roddy Manley, who has
shaken off his latest knee problem.
</TEXT>
