<HEADLINE>Ticket rush for McStay's big day</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC supporters were up before dawn yesterday as they prepared to pay tribute
to one of their favourite sons.
Manchester United will be the visitors to Parkhead a week tonight in a
lucrative testimonial for Celtic captain Paul McStay and, as tickets for the
big night went on sale yesterday, queues were already forming at the Glasgow
ground.
``The first fans arrived at one o'clock in the morning,'' said Celtic spokesman
Peter McLean. ``By 8.30 the queues were stretching down the street and that was
still three hours before the tickets were due to go on sale.
``I think this is an indication of the huge emotion that Paul's bond with
Celtic provokes among supporters - and the excitement surrounding a visit by
Manchester United.''
Celtic are hoping to be given the green light later this week to open a
temporary stand at the currently two-sided ground to push the capacity for
McStay's testimonial to more than 37,000.
The 3000-seater structure has been unable to open for several weeks because it
has failed to receive the necessary safety certificates.
Tickets for McStay's testimonial are priced #12 for adults and #5 for children
and OAPs so the Scotland star looks set to rake in close to #400,000 from the
match. He joined the club on February 20, 1981.
Meanwhile, a testimonial is planned for Mike Galloway, who has recently fought
back from a life-threatening car crash during the summer.
