<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Miles and Michele prove the best</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JUDY MURRAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044703</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILES Maclagan and Michele Mair have emerged at the top of the Scottish
rankings.
Maclagan, who reached the second round at Wimbledon and made his Davis Cup
debut for Britain in July, replaces Ross Matheson as men's No.1 after a
productive year on the Challenger and Satellite circuits.
Matheson is No.2 with Jason Barnett, still chasing his first world ranking
after two years on the full-time trail, one place further back, displacing Ken
Wood by virtue of having a better British rating.
Mair, ranked 453 in the world and No.15 in Britain, confirmed her place at the
top of the women's list when she won the Du Pont national championship in
August without dropping a set, but Jennifer Duncan, the world No.935, drops to
third place behind Heather Lockhart.
The Scottish grass and hardcourt champion teamed up with Mair to win the four
nations' international in September, and despite having no listing on the WTA
computer, she has a higher British rating than the Dundee teenager.
Tayport's Nicola Payne, who tops the junior girls list for the first time,
makes her first appearance on the women's rankings at No.4.
Heading the 16-and-under lists are double Scottish junior champion Jonathan
Pankhurst and Lyndsay Reilly, who based at a tennis ranch in Connecticut.
