<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Overdose youth in critical condition</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>News Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044704</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEENAGER Craig Low, who was found unconscious on Friday morning beside the body
of his friend Paul Flynn, remains critically ill in Perth Royal Infirmary. The
two 17-year-olds are believed to have overdosed on methadone.
Search fails
A SEARCH at first light yesterday failed to locate a single-engined Piper
aircraft, which has been missing over the Mediterranean since Sunday. The
aircraft was carrying six passengers, including Briton Michael Williams and
Irishman Desmond Goomer.
Theme park jobs
LEGOLAND, Britain's newest theme park, yesterday began moves to recruit 600
workers ahead of its official opening at Easter. Park managers in Windsor,
Berkshire, will hold interviews in the New Year for seasonal jobs.
Warden stable
A SAFARI park warden, crushed by the gate of an elephant house on Sunday, was
in a stable condition in hospital yesterday. Mr William Middleton, 35, suffered
spine and head injuries in the accident at Knowsley Safari Park, Merseyside.
Woman detained
A 29-YEAR-OLD woman was being questioned yesterday after a fatal accident in
which a pedestrian is believed to have been dragged under a Land Rover for a
mile. Mrs Margaret Whieldon, 43, of Leek, Staffordshire, died at the scene of
the crash.
Missing teenager
POLICE are concerned for a teenager who went missing after he was discharged
from Ninewells Hospital, Dundee, last Thursday. Robert Fitzpatrick, 16, is
described as being 6ft 1in, slim, with neck-length straight brown hair, fresh
complexion, and blue eyes. He is believed to be in a depressed state.
Tourist injured
A GREEK tourist was injured when an all-terrain vehicle overturned and rolled
on the 3400ft Ben Wyvis mountain on Sunday. Mr Stefan Elias had been part of a
sight-seeing party of five on the caterpillar-tracked Argocat.
Late male
ONE in three men buy their partner's present the week before Christmas but
three in four woman finish their shopping at least two weeks in advance,
according to a survey by mobile phone firm Cellnet.
BT criticism
BT's policy of preventing customers from retaining their phone numbers if they
switch cable companies was criticised on the BBC1 consumer programme Watchdog
last night. The issue is the subject of an inquiry by the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission.
</TEXT>
