<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nicol turns backon Scottish title</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044706</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nicol turns back
on Scottish title
HAVING turned down selection for the recent world team event, Peter Nicol has
decided not to defend the Scottish championship at Heriot Watt University in
Edinburgh next week.
The 22-year-old is in India preparing for the Mahindra International, but his
London-based manager, Neil Harvey, said yesterday: ``Bombay is the end of a
long tour and Peter reckons he needs a rest.''
Scottish champion for the past three seasons, Nicol was on course to equal Mark
Maclean's record of four successive wins.
Having dropped in the world rankings following a summer operation, it was the
pursuit of glory in Super Series tournaments that prompted Nocol's absence from
the world event. He showed a return to form by reaching the semi-finals of last
week's Qatar International before going out to world champion, Jansher Khan.
However, failure to enter the Scottish championships without explanation to the
governing body must have raise doubts over his presence at the European
championships at the end of the season.
Ironically, his father, Pat, is the sole selector and manager of the Scottish
team.
On a positive note, Scotland's No.2, Martin Heath, another world championship
absentee, has entered the championship, which start on Friday week.
The world No.30 from Oban, who also competes in India but has been unfortunate
to draw top-seed Rodney Eyles in the first round, will be the favourite ahead
of the former English junior internationalist, Stuart Cowie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Possessed pervert' guilty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044707</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER policeman was convicted yesterday of making indecent phone calls to
women after claiming his body was inhabited by the spirit of a
nineteenth-century pervert.
While Anthony Cooper, 43, physically rang the numbers, it was the ghost of
Peter Wilson, who died more than 100 years ago, who spoke to the women,
magistrates in Hemel Hempstead, Hertford, were told.
Justices ruled out the defence case that Cooper was acting in a state of
automatism after being subjected to ``spirit attachment by Peter The Pervert''.
Cooper, of Waterdell, Leighton Buzzard, Bedfordshire, denied four charges of
impersonating a police officer and three of making indecent calls between July
and September, 1994, but was convicted on all counts.
Magistrate Malcolm Barker said: ``On what we have heard so far, we are
considering custody.''
Sentence was adjourned for reports until January 3.
Cooper, who has been married for 18 years and has three step-children, had told
the court: ``I admit it must have been me who made the calls. But I still do
not have any knowledge of them.''
He said he had experienced ``strange feelings'' after receiving burns during a
fire in 1985.
Mr David Markham, for the Crown, said Cooper's conduct was ``deliberate and
conscious''.
For 10 years, Cooper was chief of security at the Asda supermarket in Luton,
Bedfordshire. Between 1971 and 1974, he was a police constable in Bedfordshire.
Mr Markham alleged: ``Cooper used his accumulated experience to embark on a
course of conduct the object of which was his sexual gratification.''
Cooper would choose his female victims from magazine advertisements and would
call, claiming he was Inspector Harrison from Watford police station.
``He would say to the woman that she could expect a call from a pervert and
could expect to be on the receiving end of lewd and rude comments,'' Mr Markham
said.
As Inspector Harrison, Cooper told the women to keep the man talking for as
long as possible.
Mr Markham said: ``He was very plausible - some agreed to assist and he would
give them an entirely false number.
``The female would then receive a call very shortly from a man calling himself
Peter.''
The caller told one woman he was a transvestite looking for a room.
The court heard how the calls were later traced to the Asda store.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major aims to extend war grave pilgrimage scheme</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Major aims
to extend
war grave
pilgrimage
scheme
PRIME Minister John Major was mobbed by hundreds of war widows last night as he
announced plans to extend the Government-aided war graves pilgrimage scheme.
They surged forward to surround Mr Major when he made a surprise appearance at
a central London reunion for widows who have already benefited from the 10-year
programme.
Amid remarkable scenes, they jostled for position to have their photographs
taken alongside him and put their arms around him.
There were rousing cheers when the Prime Minister revealed that the scheme to
help widows visit their husband's final resting place was to be extended by a
further three years until 1999.
Mr Major paid an emotional tribute to the courage and strength of the women who
were left as young widows at the end of the Second World War.
``I hope in some small way this will illustrate in a more concrete way that
there are many people who will never forget the sacrifice that was made,'' he
said.
``This is but a small way of saying thank you for your courage, thank you for
the sacrifice your family has made.''
The decision was praised warmly by women who have joined the pilgrimages
organised for the Government by the Royal British Legion.
Mrs Dorothy Pattison, 76, of Hartlepool, Cleveland, urged widows who had not
seen their husband's graves to take advantage of the scheme.
``When you first see the grave, you simply break your heart,'' she said.
``But then there is a feeling of calm and there is no doubt it helps even after
all these years.''
Vice-Admiral Sir Geoffrey Dalton, the legion president, described the extension
of the scheme as ``absolutely marvellous''.
He said: ``It has been a tremendous success over the past 10 years. We know
that it is terribly important for these widows to visit the graves of their
husbands and also to see where they fell. Afterwards, they have this remarkable
feeling of calm.''
Over the past 10 years, more than 3000 widows and 8000 close relatives have
visited the graves of their loved ones in 42 different countries.
In the past year alone, 1375 people including 117 widows have joined
pilgrimages to cemeteries as far afield as Hong Kong and Malaysia.
The legion said demand for the grant-aided programme was still very high.
The Ministry of Defence pays seven-eighths of the total cost of a widow's trip
and, in cases of extreme hardship, the legion makes up the difference. Other
relatives go at their own expense.
Mr Major revealed that a further 20 pilgrimages were planned for 1996,
including Burma, Normandy, India, and North Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prazak Quartet, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044709</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOUGH its players look young, and though this was their first appearance in
Scotland, the excellent Prazak Quartet is within sight of its quarter-century
on the platform.
From the way it performed Smetana at last night's New Town Concert, with the
most subtle gradations of tone and changes of pace, the evidence of its mature
rapport was there for all to hear. But the uncommon positioning of the viola
player opposite the first violin, and the way both of them turned to face the
audience at moments of high expressiveness, said something else about the
ensemble: that this could only have been a Bohemian quartet, performing to the
limits of its emotional identity.
Every moment of Smetana's autobiographical masterpiece in E minor disclosed
this to the full, making the performance a wonderfully tender, passionate, and
picturesque sequence of musical reminiscences. At the climax of the slow
movement, an almost orchestral richness was achieved as the big chords were
heaved into place, but the gentler moments, as one soft theme then another
emerged from the texture, were no less astonishing and enthralling.
When a Czech quartet plays the music of one of its fellow countrymen, it does
so with fire and spontaneity. Earlier, perhaps, the Prazak had failed to bring
quite such powerful identity to Ervin Schulhoff's Five Pieces, a dance suite in
which Bartokian graininess was mixed with Stravinskian spikiness.
There was no doubt, however, about the vitality of the performance, or about
the freedom with which Beethoven's early B flat major quartet was played at the
start of the programme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prices showing signs of stabilising</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044710</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN before last week's cut in mortgage rates, signs were emerging that the
housing market was stabilising after months in the doldrums.
Prices rose last month by a seasonally adjusted 0.3%, making four months in
succession that they increased, according to the Halifax Building Society in
its monthly survey, published early this morning.
October's rise was revised up from 0.1% to 0.2%. Even so, prices are still 1.4%
lower than November last year.
The Halifax, Britain's largest mortgage lender, said the figures confirmed
``our view that house prices are no longer generally falling and remain more or
less stable''.
Last week the society cut its mortgage rate from 7.99% to 7.74%, amid
speculation that the Budget would lead to a cut in bank base rates sooner or
later. The Halifax's move has been followed by most major mortgage providers in
an effort to revive the housing market.
Figures from the Bank of England showed that growth in the narrow measure of
the money supply, M0, accelerated in November, but this was not thought to
undermine the prospects of lower rates.
``Any rises in house prices will depend on improvements in consumer confidence
which should occur as incomes are boosted by tax cuts in 1996,'' the building
society said.
``The downward trend in interest rates, signalled by the Halifax's recent
decision to lower mortgage rates, should further help to stimulate the market
next year,'' it added.
The Halifax figures follow data from the Nationwide Building Society on Friday
which showed prices rose 1.5% in November, but remained 2.2% down on a year ago.
Some economists have taken encouragement from a pick up in new mortgage
approvals recently, although it has yet to translate into lending figures.
The Council of Mortgage Lenders has cautioned that the rise in approvals may,
in large part, reflect ``churning'' - existing homeowners switching for a
better deal, rather than heralding a market recovery.
The rise in the Halifax index last month took the average house price to
#61,317 from October's #61,092. Prices paid by first-time buyers were unchanged
at #44,768. New house prices rose 2.3% in November.
M0, which covers notes and coins in circulation and bankers' balances, rose by
0.7% last month, with the annual rate picking up from 5.2% to 5.6%, well above
the Government's 0% to 4% monitoring range.
The three-month annualised rate was 5.9% and the six-month rate 6.1%. Excluding
bankers' balances, monthly growth was 0.5%, the same as in October.
James Capel's Adam Cole said: ``While the relationship between monthly M0 and
monthly retail sales is not close, today's numbers add to other evidence - such
as the John Lewis sales figures - suggesting that November should see a
reasonable rebound in retail sales after two disappointing months.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Irish competition for radio franchise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044711</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Radio Holdings yesterday gave more details of its bid to operate a
Dublin-based radio station broadcasting to all parts of the Irish Republic.
Chief executive Jimmy Gordon said Scottish Radio was competing with four
Irish-based groups for the Irish national radio franchise, which will probably
be awarded in February.
If successful, Scottish Radio hopes to put a new FM station on the air in
September, broadcasting a broad mix of music and speech. This recipe is
unashamedly based on Mr Gordon's winning formula for launching Radio Clyde more
than 20 years ago.
``It would be what Radio Clyde was before we split frequencies, a broad-based
programming with a fair amount of speech and a broad range of music, with
everything from pop to classical,'' he said.
Mr Gordon reckoned the Irish station would cost #4m to launch and would
initially employ about 50 people.
Scottish Radio has a 35% stake in a consortium applying for the licence
alongside two partners who Mr Gordon referred to as ``capital providers''.
If the application is successful, Scottish Radio will effectively run the new
station.
But first it must fend off rival bids from three Irish radio stations and a
group of Irish entertainment promoters. This will involve putting forward a
good case at public consultation hearings in January.
Scottish Radio is determined to expand outside Scotland and diversify from
radio into weekly newspapers because it has little room to expand further on
its home turf.
The Glasgow-based company, which owns Radio Clyde, Radio Forth, Radio Tay and
the Aberdeen station Northsound, bought the Morton group of weekly newspapers
in Northern Ireland for #11.2m in October. Further newspaper acquisitions are
planned and it is eager to apply for the licence for a new regional radio
station in Yorkshire.
Scottish Radio already has one toehold south of the Border. It owns 40% of West
Cumbria Radio. Last week, the company announced a 22% rise in pre-tax profit to
#5.1m. It has #8.2m of cash in the bank.
n.Daily Mail and General Trust (DMGT) has agreed with Argus Press to acquire
the Argus Business Media magazine and exhibitions business for #35m cash.
The acquisition is complementary to existing businesses of the trust which also
owns the Daily Mail, Mail on Sunday and London's Evening Standard.
Argus Business Media publishes trade and technical journals, yearbooks and
directories for a range of industry sectors and organises exhibitions and
conferences.
The unit produces 52 titles, 27 annuals and about 50 exhibitions a year. In the
year ended March 31, 1995, it made a pre-tax profit of #3.6m on revenues of
#25.3m.
</TEXT>
