<HEADLINE>Forte plans shake-up to fend off Granada</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW  WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044716</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Rocco Forte surprised the City yesterday with a plan for the fundamental
restructuring of the hotels and leisure group that would lead to the splitting
off of the restaurants business and the possible sale of the 68% stake in the
Savoy hotel.
This is the first significant movement since Granada launched an unexpected
#3300m bid for Forte and has impressed some analysts.
Granada chief executive and chairman elect Gerry Robinson immediately swung on
to the attack. He said Forte would be splitting two business that sat together,
adding that he thought the group would be worth less if it were divided up.
That is because there would be less control over the key issue of purchasing.
Forte shares eased 4p to 338p while Granada firmed 2p to 651p to value each
Forte share at 328p.
The Forte strategy to help fend off the increasingly hostile bid is to form the
Little Chefs, Happy Eater, Welcome Break, and Cote France roadside restaurants
into a stand-alone company which would be floated off.
Initial calculations suggest it could be worth about #1500m before deducting
any debt relating directly to the chains which operate in Britain and France or
anything that may be loaded on to them in the event of flotation. That could
reduce their net value to about #1000m.
Also lined up for disposal is the White Hart hotels chain, which some analysts
believe to be worth just #100m.
The biggest surprise is the decision to sell the 68% stake in the Savoy hotel,
particularly as Lord Forte and his son Sir Rocco have spent so much time and
effort while suffering many slights in their attempts to gain control.
The Forte stake is still just 42% of the votes because of the Savoy's unusual
voting structure.
The Travelodge business is also worth perhaps #100m but that may continue to be
jointly owned by the restaurants company and Forte.
On Sunday it said it sold its Lillywhites sports chain to Jeronimo Martina of
Portugal for #28m. The quarter share in the Alpha Airports aircraft food
services associate will also be sold.
q.THE man ousted from his post as managing director at the Savoy has been made
boss of The Ritz in Piccadilly.
The appointment of Old Etonian Giles Shepard as managing director was announced
last night.
Mr Shepard left the Savoy last year after a long battle with Sir Rocco Forte.
He had been in charge for 15 years. He received a #569,000 pay-off when he left.
</TEXT>
