<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ticket to top of the class</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044717</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As an innovative RSNO associate conductor scheme initiated byThe Herald grows
in shape,Michael Tumelty offers a term report
IT'S almost a year since the death of Sir Alexander Gibson, the man who founded
Scottish Opera, revivified the Scottish National Orchestra, and almost
singlehandedly triggered a renaissance in Scottish musical life.
Tonight, in a celebration of the life of Sir Alex, a gala concert featuring the
two organisations with which he was most closely associated is being staged in
Glasgow Royal Concert Hall.
Shortly after the death of Sir Alex last January, The Herald announced that it
was to promote the founding of an associate conductorship at the Royal Scottish
National Orchestra. This was intended to give a talented young conductor the
opportunity to gain invaluable experience, and a foothold in a profession that
is notoriously difficult to enter.
Such projects necessarily have a long period of gestation. And this one still
has a long way to go. None the less, it is shaping up to be a venture that will
give a young conductor a broad range of experience that will be unrivalled, and
is liable to become one of the key international opportunities for any aspiring
and talented conductor.
It is appropriate, on the day of the gala concert to celebrate the memory and
achievement of Sir Alex, that The Herald can now outline the scale and scope of
the project which is evolving.
For a start, it has grown. The Herald and the Royal Scottish National Orchestra
have joined forces with the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama (which
already has a number of conducting schemes in place). All three will
collaborate to offer a young conductor a comprehensive range of experience over
a two-year period.
The project will take the form of a competition. The working name is The Sir
Alexander Gibson International Conducting Competition and Fellowship. The case
for a competition was argued forcefully by the musicians of the RSNO
themselves, who feel that they will be able to judge potential far more readily
in that way.
The judges at the competition will include the principal conductors of the
orchestra - currently the Viennese, Walter Weller, and the Russian, Alexander
Lazarev - and Edwin Paling, the leader of the RSNO (who will also play under
each competitor).
To understand the import of the prizes on offer, it's as well to consider for a
moment that the biggest international conducting competitions tend to offer a
cash prize together with a significant engagement with a major orchestra.
The Herald/RSNO/RSAMD competition will go far beyond any of these. The post of
associate conductor will run for two years. It is felt that such a time scale
will be required to gain maximum benefits for both the conductor and the
orchestra. With the RSNO, the conductor will undertake a series of summer Prom
concerts and will be given his or her own week in the flagship winter season
series.
Additionally, the post may be used to generate some ``out of town'' work for
the RSNO in smaller venues, where the orchestra's presence has fallen away in
recent years. The conductor will also understudy the RSNO's principal
conductors, work with the chorus master, and participate in educational
projects.
The RSAMD will offer a fellowship to the conductor. The fellow will have the
chance to conduct at least one of the RSAMD orchestra's big public concerts
each session. In addition there will be opportunities with the RSAMD's wind,
brass, and big bands. The conductor will also work with the RSAMD's repertory
orchestra, a training orchestra which meets four or five times per session.
The conductor will also work throughout Scotland in outreach activities with
the RSAMD orchestra, and with the RSAMD's opera school. And there is a whole,
new, untapped area here awaiting the lucky recipient of the fellowship.
In 1997 the new Sir Alexander Opera School is scheduled to open at the RSAMD.
It will cost #5m. Over a million was already gathered when, recently, the
school was awarded #2.5m of lottery money towards its completion. The new opera
school will provide the prizewinning conductor with opportunities to work with
young playwrights and directors, as well as to give in-house and touring
performances of opera.
On top of all this, the conductor will be able to get experience at the cutting
edge of Scotland's thriving contemporary music industry, working with composers
and groups like Academy Now!, the RSAMD's specialist contemporary music
ensemble, as well as the academy's early music department.
``What's going to make this competition unique, and different from any other
competition, is the tremendous range of experience we can offer,'' says Rita
McAllister, director of the school of music at the RSAMD.
That experience will include the opportunity to study, for up to three months
in the two-year period of the post, with one of the gurus of conducting at the
St Petersburg Conservatoire in Russia, with which the RSAMD has established
strong exchange links.
Such will be the amount of work available, the comprehensive nature of the
experience on offer, and the commitment required, that the person who holds the
post will effectively be salaried for two years to work in Scotland.
As to the time scale for the venture, it is envisaged that the competition will
be held next season (1996/97) with the winner taking up the post at the start
of the season after that. Auditions are expected to be held in about a year,
and, with a lead-in period of around six months necessary, it is expected that
the ground rules for the competition will be established by next Easter.
Rita McAllister expects world-wide interest in the post and fellowship. ``There
are young conductors who are working with provincial European companies or
orchestras who are looking for the big break,'' she says. ``And the whole of
Eastern Europe is a huge potential market.''
Matthew Rooke, music director of the Scottish Arts Council, yesterday welcomed
the collaborative project between The Herald, the RSNO and the RSAMD. He said
that with the range of opportunities offered by the scheme, the project could
become ``a focal point for talent internationally''. The entire project, says
Rooke, would represent for young conductors, ``a dream finishing school''.
n Sir Alexander Gibson: A Celebration in Music, with the RSNO and Scottish
Opera. Tonight, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall, 7.30pm.
</TEXT>
