<HEADLINE>Snappers right to put Nicholl in the frame</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044718</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was one of those moments when we wondered if he was leading us towards one
of his outrageous punchlines, the kind that leaves you squirming at your own
naivete. In fact, Jimmy Nicholl was telling the truth.
``Sometimes I don't pick the team until we are on the bus going to the game,''
he said, as he treated us to one of his press conferences before a European
match, during which the Raith Rovers manager was thinking aloud about exactly
what line-up to use.
That is one of his endearing habits, even if it does not lend itself to a
mountain of information or the listening hacks. He does think so deeply about
every aspect of his job that he has actually left the team selection until he
is forced to write it down on the referee's list.
However he arrives at his decisions, Nicholl gets it right more often than not,
which is one reason he was chosen yesterday by the country's sports
photographers as their man of the year. The fact that he is well liked by most
sections of the business helps, of course, but award winners do need to be good
at their job.
Nicholl, in a relatively short space of time, five years, has established
himself as the man most likely among the younger brigade of team leaders, and
has done it with an unfashionable club which has never had this kind of success
or publicity in the past.
Winning the first division championship twice in that spell was commendable
enough, but to confirm a place in the top league at the same time as winning
their first major trophy, the Coca-Cola Cup, was far beyond the realistic
aspirations of the Fife club.
The European qualification which came with that memorable victory over Celtic
left much of the country giggling at the prospect of the wee Rovers taking on
one of the mighty names of the Continent.
After Rovers made it through a preliminary round and then the first round of
the UEFA Cup, none too impressively, the cynics were out in force, preparing to
have a laugh at the Stark's Park embarrassment when they faced Bayern Munich,
Jurgen Klinsmann, Jean-Pierre Papin, et al, in the second round.
Beaten 2-0 in the first leg, Rovers went to Germany with most Scots praying
that they would not suffer the kind of humiliation that can take many months,
even years, to overcome. It was a foolish fear. This is a better team than
anybody bar Nicholl thought. He had bomdarded us with the inevitable chatter
based on the strange uncertainties of football, the possibility of a complacent
Bayern and all the usual, whistling-in-the-dark observations that are designed
to transmit some kind of hope to the players.
It did not produce the miracle. Raith went out as expected, but there was no
deep dejection on the plane home that night. In fact, there was an
unforgettable moment in the Olympic Stadium, Munich, when every one of the
Scots present, and I include the ``neutral'' media corps, enjoyed a feeling of
deep national pride that has been a rarity for a long time.
Rovers, as recorded by the giant electronic scoreboards at each end of the
ground, were 1-0 ahead, playing really well, and seriously believing they could
do the impossible.
Those bonnie scoreboards stayed that way until half-time, at which point
Nicholl confessed afterwards that he had stopped quietly and had a good look at
them. ``I thought: this is worth remembering. It might never happen again.''
It was the very fact that he threw in the word ``might'' that is perhaps the
most revealing glimpse of his style of management. It is his supreme
self-motivation that spawns the conviction that, if players play to their own
limitations, anything is feasible.
In his Kirkcaldy stint he has produced a mixture of experience and youth that
is unafraid of any challenge. To take a team like Raith to fourth place in the
premier division, where they are at the moment, after the glorious failure in
Europe and the magnificent victory in the Coca-Cola Cup, not to mention the
first division title, demands a plethora of talents.
It is not easy to admit this but here goes: the snappers have got it right.
</TEXT>
