<HEADLINE>Forsyth calls for report as another Cornton Vale inmate is found hanged Third suicide tragedy at women's jail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044719</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth last night expressed his concern over the
third suicide death in six months at Scotland's only women's prison.
A fatal accident inquiry is to be held into the death of mother-of-two Joanne
O'Reilly, 26, who was found hanging by a bedsheet in her cell at Cornton Vale
prison, near Stirling, on Sunday.
The tragedy came only two days after an FAI into the deaths of the two other
inmates, Kelly Holland and Arlene Elliot, was adjourned until early next month.
Their suicides were the first at the prison in 10 years.
After meeting the chief executive of the Scottish Prison Service to discuss the
latest suicide, Mr Forsyth said yesterday: ``This is an extremely unfortunate
and regrettable incident. Miss O'Reilly is the third young person to lose her
life in Cornton Vale this year.
``The chief executive is taking this matter very seriously. I have asked him to
report to me on this incident once the outcome of the fatal accident inquiry is
known.''
Last night, Labour MP John McFall, Shadow Scottish Home Affairs spokesman,
called for an immediate probe by the Inspector of Prisons and said: ``An
immediate inquiry and a public report is essential.''
He added: ``This tragic death raises very serious questions about the efficient
running of the prison. The inquiry should cover all aspects of the management
and practices at the prison in order to allay public concern. The integrity of
the prison service is at stake. This must not be undermined.''
Miss O'Reilly's grieving family were too upset to talk about the tragedy but
one relative said: ``We are meeting people tomorrow to find out the full facts.
Until then, there is no comment we can make.''
Miss O'Reilly, from Nitshill, Glasgow, leaves two sons, aged six and four, who
are to be looked after by her mother.
Friends said Miss O'Reilly had been standing at a bus stop chatting to a friend
Sharon McGurn, 16, of Househillwood Road, Nitshill, last Thursday when a police
car drew up and arrested her in connection with charges of theft and failing to
appear in court.
The latest death now questions the Scottish Prison Service's ability to deal
with young people at risk despite the introduction three years ago of a suicide
prevention strategy.
Already this year there have been 16 suicides in Scottish prisons, three times
the average annual rate among the country's 44,000 prison population.
Mr John Gerrie, spokesman for the Scottish Prison Service, admitted the number
of suicides was ``very worrying''.
He added: ``One suicide in prison is one too many. The fact that rare events
sometimes cluster and that the rate of suicide among young males in Scotland as
a whole has increased is of little comfort.
``It has proved difficult to ascertain why there has been an increase in the
number of suicides in prison and no common theme or pattern has emerged.''
The SPS has already enlisted the help of Professor John Gunn, of the Institute
of Psychiatry in London, to assess ways the service can prevent suicides. His
report is due later this month.
The SPS is also installing new ``at risk'' cells in Scots prisons at a cost of
#30,000 per cell. Ten have already been completed at Aberdeen and a further 13
are in the pipeline for Barlinnie, Edinburgh, Longriggend, Perth, and Cornton
Vale.
Canvas gowns and blankets in the cells are replaced with non-tear clothes and
sleeping bags. Resuscitation equipment will be available in all halls and cells
will be free of projections which can make suicide by hanging easier.
Mr Robbie Glen, governor of Cornton Vale, said: ``It goes without saying that
everyone is shocked and upset.''
Last week, while giving evidence at the FAI into the deaths of Kelly Holland
and Arlene Elliot, the prison's deputy governor, Mr William Low, 49, said there
were flaws in the prison's current suicide-prevention policy.
He said he would like new therapeutic practices implemented and that Cornton
Vale was trying to move away from its policy of isolating prisoners if it was
felt they were going to harm themselves.
However, Mr Low, who has been deputy governor for 10 months, added that a more
therapeutic regime, involving the modernising of cells and the provision of
full-time counsellors, would drain a huge proportion of the prison's budget.
</TEXT>
