<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Terrorism accused was given a new life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044720</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN accused of terrorism charges was given #2000 to start a new life in
Scotland, the High Court in Glasgow heard yesterday.
Mr Lindsay Robb, 28, was also issued with a gun for his own protection after
witnessing an IRA murder.
His home in Lurgan, Northern Ireland, was fortified against IRA attacks after
he gave vital evidence for the prosecution.
RUC Sergeant George Forde said that after an IRA man called Duffy was convicted
of murder Mr Robb was screened by the witness protection unit and given the
#2000.
He said: ``He was given the money to resettle in Scotland.''
Mr Forde said the IRA man's defence lawyers hired private detectives to
investigate Mr Robb's background during the murder trial.
He told defence QC Mr Donald Findlay: ``This caused some concern and was
reported to the Department of Public Prosecution in Northern Ireland.''
He told Mr Findlay that screening showed Mr Robb had no criminal record.
Mr Robb, an Ulster politician who has taken part in peace talks, and five
others deny conspiring to acquire weapons for the UVF with intent to endanger
lives.
The court has heard that Mr Robb lived in Lurgan with his fiancee and their
three children and also his mother, but was also due to marry Margaret Glen of
Airdrie.
The other accused are Mr John Johnston, 49, of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston,
Falkirk; Mr Francis Hives, 45, of Prescott Road, Liverpool; Mr William
McArthur, 41, of Ure Crescent, Bonnybridge; Mr David White, 29, of Northburn
Avenue, Airdrie; and Mr Alex Davidson, 23, of Greenhill Park, Lurgan.
Advocate-depute Mr Ian Bonomy, QC, prosecuting, told the jury: ``To direct one
bullet into Northern Ireland is one too many and is a matter for the law.''
The evidence showed that Mr Robb was the go-between to get weapons and
ammunition for the UVF, he said.
``He was the organiser. You can be the main player without doing the actual
dirty work yourself.''
He said Mr Johnston went to Liverpool to try to set up the scheme where he met
Mr Hives and that Mr White and Mr McArthur went there to collect firearms.
Mr Bonomy said that Mr Davidson's arrest at the ferry terminal at Stranraer
showed ``where the conspiracy was going''.
Evidence in the case has finished and legal submissions by defence counsel are
expected to last several days.
</TEXT>
