<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clark's warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044721</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT will be a nervy night for all concerned in the Jurland Stadium, Lyon, where
Frank Clark's Nottingham Forest are asked to walk the UEFA Cup tightrope of a
one-goal lead against the club from France's second largest city.
Forest, who scored their first-leg goal two weeks ago at the City Ground with
just a few minutes of the match remaining, have mixed fortunes for tonight's
game, with Bryan Roy missing the game, although top scorer Jason Lee looks set
to return after having missed out recently with thigh and calf injuries.
A worry for the English side is that around 2000 tickets for the third round,
second-leg tie have been illicitly despatched to England.
The fear is that mindless hooligans will take the opportunity to attach
themselves to the official party of Forest supporters and could cause trouble.
French police have liaised closely with British officers from the Football
Intelligence Unit and warned of stringent action, described by the Lyon police
chief as ``oppressive.''
``We are aware of the possibility that national yobbos could come here and
cause mayhem,'' said Clark, ``but as a club there is nothing more we can do. We
have followed the guidelines and can only hope things go off reasonably well.''
However, Clark hopes to give Lyon worries of their own. ``We must be positive
whenever we can,'' said the manager, ``as another goal for us would mean they
must score three to beat us, and I cannot see them being capable of that.''
Werder Bremen, having a poor domestic season, will play host to PSV Eindhoven
tonight with high hopes of going further in the competition.
The Germans, whose form has shaded since Dutch coach Aad de Mos replaced Otto
Rehhagel in the summer, came away from Holland with just a 2-1 defeat in the
first leg, and now must fancy their chances of reaching the next round.
Bayern Munich travel to Benfica with a 4-1 cushion from the first leg.
Christian Ziege is suspended and central defender Thomas Helmer is doubtful but
the Germans should have no problems.
Barcelona, European champions in 1992, will not be over-confident in their
all-Spanish duel with Seville despite home advantage and a 1-1 score from the
first leg.
AC Milan, travel confidently to Prague after their recent 1-0 win over Lazio in
Rome for Thursday's match with Sparta. Milan defend a 2-0 lead from the first
leg.
Fellow-Italians Roma will be less confident as they take on Brondby, of
Denmark, who beat Liverpool in the previous round and won 2-1 in Denmark.
Spain's Real Betis, fresh from an inspiring 2-1 win over league leaders
Atletico Madrid, play French visitors Bordeaux, who hold a 2-0 lead, tomorrow,
while in the final game of the round, also on Thursday, Lens, of France, play
Slavia Prague after a goalless first leg in the Czech Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
