<HEADLINE>CONSTRUCTION Allen makes acquisitions in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044722</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLEN has made its first acquisitions in Scotland, with the tool hire and
construction group paying #429,000 cash for four plant hire depots.
It is buying Capital Plant Hire, which has premises in both Edinburgh and
Glasgow, and Broty Tool Hire in Dundee.
This raises the total Allen network to 84 units, to become the second largest
sector operator in Britain behind HSS.
Half-time profit jumped 31% to #3.6m on turnover 12.3% greater at #55.5m. The
impetus came decidedly from hire, where operating profit doubled to #2.22m and
should continue to show a strong performance in the current half year.
The housebuilding side is under pressure, with likely completions for the year
expected to fall by over a quarter to 315 units. However, civil engineering is
bucking the general trend, with rising profitability and is benefiting from
long-term contracts with North West Water.
Analysts expect full-year profit to rise over #1.5m to about #7.7m. The interim
dividend rises 25% to 2.5p.
the Preference terms were delayed until after the Budget in case there were
changes in legislation in the small print.
Amec has advised stock holders to reject this offer as it has the Ordinary
share bid.
A Japanese construction firm which is in a joint venture with Amec to build the
new Hong Kong airport has acquired a holding thought to be less than 1%.
That was sufficient to spark off some speculative interest in Amec which rose
2p to 101p compared with the Kvaerner offer of 100p cash. The offer closes on
December 18 unless there is a counter bid. Kaverner now owns 18.1%.
</TEXT>
