<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Funding for beef industry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044723</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #500,000 European boost for the Scottish beef industry was announced
yesterday by Brian Simpson, chief executive of the Scotch Quality Beef and Lamb
Association.
For the third year running, SQBLA successfully bid for promotional funds from
the European Quality Beef Scheme, Mr Simpson revealed when officially opening
Scotch Premier Meats' Christmas Carcase Show and Sale at Inverurie.
The exact amount is still to be agreed but is likely to be similar to the award
made last year of #500,000, he said. The Scottish industry won the award as a
result of the leading position it has developed in quality assurance on farms
and in meat plants, he added.
The additional funding on top of SQBLA's existing promotional spend of #1.3m
was utterly essential to counteract the adverse publicity the meat industry was
being subjected to, he said.
The champion beef carcase in the show was a 682lbs home-bred Limousin cross
heifer from JGS Duncan, Jacobshall, Gamrie, Banff. It was sold by auction for
the top price of #2600 to Coventry specialist catering butcher Aubray Allen.
Reserve was a Caithness-bred Charolais cross steer weighing 821lbs from WM
Fettes, Braes of Enzie, Buckie, which was sold for #1600 to Mills, butcher,
Lichfield, Staffordshire.
Pairs of Beltex cross Charollais lambs from WJ&amp;M Hunter, West Cairnhill,
Culsalmond, Huntly, took both the championship and reserve in the lamb carcase
section and sold for #120 each to Selfridges, Oxford Street, London, and #105
each to Mike Richardson, Ealing, London.
Selfridges also paid #140 for the champion pork carcase from Charles Downie,
Mains of Techmuiry, Fraserburgh, and #115 for the reserve champion from JL
Machrie, Mill of Torry, Udny.
</TEXT>
