<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish increase twice that of UK Electronics help exports to rise 23%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044724</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH exports of manufactured goods soared by 23% last year, growing twice
as fast as exports from the UK as a whole. A huge increase in shipments of
computers and electronic engineering goods was mainly responsible for this.
But exports in 1995 are likely to grow only 9% as demand from France and
Germany falls and Scotland experiences a gap in large new electronics factories
coming on stream.
These findings come from Scottish Council Development and Industry (SCDI), an
independent trade promotion body which conducts quarterly and annual surveys of
Scotland's export performance.
The SCDI annual survey for 1994, published yesterday, shows Scottish exports
rose 23.6% at current prices last year to a record #14.3bn.
This was mainly because of an 63.8% increase in shipments of computers and
office equipment and a 78% rise in the export of other electronic goods,
ranging from computer components such as circuit boards to domestic goods such
as vacuum cleaners.
Stripping out the effects of inflation, Scottish exports grew by 22.8% at
constant prices, compared to only 9.5% for the UK as a whole.
SCDI general manager Alan Wilson said the opening of several new electronics
factories geared to overseas markets gave a special boost to Scottish exports
in 1993 and 1994.
``I think we are seeing the fruit of investment in the late 1980s and early
1990s when the country was sold as a springboard for foreign markets,'' he said.
But he predicted that Scottish exports would be more in line with the rest of
the UK this year. ``It will probably be single figures,'' he said.
Ian Armstrong, SCDI's business information executive, estimated that Scottish
exports would grow by 9%.
This slowdown in export growth is already evident in the SCDI's quarterly
surveys. The third-quarter survey, published last month, showed a fall in
exports from the second quarter, with signifant declines in chemicals and
computers.
According to the 1994 annual survey, based on returns from 1120 companies, 66%
of Scotland's exports go to western Europe, where France, Germany, the
Netherlands and Italy are the largest markets.
Japan and the Far East take 13% of Scottish exports and constitute the fastest
growing overseas market. Exports to the Far East grew 38% last year,
outstripping a 28.3% rise in shipments to fellow members of the European Union
and 18.4% growth in exports to the mainly Scandinavian members of EFTA.
The United States and Canada follow in third place, with a market share of 12%.
But Scottish exports to North America grew only 5.7% last year.
This perhaps reflects the fact that many Scottish computer plants are owned by
US firms and were set up to export to Europe, the Middle East and Africa,
rather than back to the US.
France consolidated its position as Scotland's largest export market last year
after overtaking Germany in 1993. Exports to France rose 51% to #2338m, with
computers accounting for most of the increase.
The composition of Scottish exports reveals a dramatic growth in the market
share of computer equipment and other electronic goods. Together, they
accounted for 49% of exports last year, up from 42% in 1993.
The market share of traditional sectors such as whisky, with 15% and mechanical
engineering with 6% has, meanwhile, declined.
According to SCDI, the number of jobs in Scotland directly dependent on exports
increased to 121,000 last year from 110,000 in 1993.
</TEXT>
