<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hormone implants `not a threat to consumers'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN LEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044725</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE use of growth promoters in the production of meat does not pose a threat to
consumers, provided hormone implants are applied in the right dosage and at the
correct point in the production cycle. That was the overwhelming scientific
conclusion to emerge from a three-day conference held by the European
Commission in Brussels.
Ironically, however, the political message was that the EU's resolve that
European producers should not use implants was as firm as ever.
EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler set the tone for the gathering of 80
scientists and 170 non-scientific observers when he told the opening session
that, while he saw the event as a vital assessment of current science on growth
promoters, everyone should realise that the framing of future policy on hormone
usage in Europe remained the responsibility of EU institutions, not conference
delegates.
``There is no point in proclaiming loudly that hormone prohibitions in Europe
exist to appease irrational demands founded on misinformation and ignorance,''
he said. ``At the other extreme, I see no merit in insisting, without evidence,
that growth promoters constitute an unnatural and unacceptable interference
with life itself and must, therefore, damage the health of the human race for
generations to come.''
The control measures required by the prohibition of certain substances within
the EU were both burdensome and costly, he said. At times they had some very
real and brutal consequences. ``Controllers in the field are exposed regularly
to threats and violence. Convicted users of illegal substances are rightly sent
to jail and have to pay heavy fines.''
Despite such actions, there had been occasions when consumers had become ill
from eating the produce of animals treated with dangerous substances. This was
the result of an illegal trade in implants which had developed ``thanks to our
controls'', he added.
``Such stark realities place a heavy responsibility on EU opinion-formers and
decision-makers to develop a framework that will ensure essential safeguards to
consumers on health aspects, while allowing the controlling authorities to deal
ruthlessly with substances and practices which pose real risks to health,'' he
said.
However, risk-assessment measures concerning the possible impact on consumers
of hormone-raised produce were called into question by Professor Jim Bridges of
the University of Surrey. He said: ``We are still using the scientific
techniques of the 1960s and 1970s to answer the scientific questions of the
1990s.''
</TEXT>
