<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unions stand firm on single market</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044728</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the UK farmers' unions and the Irish Farmers' Association have
adopted a united front in opposing any moves towards re-nationalisation of farm
support policies.
After a ``summit'' meeting at National Farmers' Union of Scotland headquarters
at Ingliston, the unions issued a joint statement underlining their support for
a single European market for farm produce with fair terms of internal trade.
The unions identified world trade talks (GATT mark two) in the year 2000 as a
major factor which would concentrate minds on further reforms of the CAP, with
increasing pressure for the moderation of any economic policies judged to be
distorting trade.
Political pressure for progress towards accession of the eastern European
former Communist countries was also seen as a lever which would be used to
bring about changes in the CAP.
John Ross, president of the National Farmers' Union of Scotland, said that
there was absolute agreement around the table that they did not want
agricultural policy re-nationalised. ``We really do want common policies so
that there can be a common single market,'' he said.
For the immediate future - over the next two or three years - he forecast there
would be only minor adjustments to the CAP.
The union representatives pointed out that past experience had shown the
introduction of major changes could be a slow process. The accession of Spain
and Portugal had been achieved over a 10-year period as they adapted to the EU
system.
Michael Berkery, chief executive of the Irish Farmers' Association, forecast it
could take up to 20 years to integrate the central and eastern European
countries into the CAP. There appeared to be a view in these countries that the
EU would meet them half way, dropping its standards as the former communist
countries raised theirs. ``I do not believe that will happen,'' he said. ``When
we joined we had to take on board the fundamental rules of the system.''
He expected huge difficulties in assisting the former eastern bloc countries to
achieve EU standards. ``Legal ownership of land as we understand it doesn't
exist,'' he said. That, in turn, meant credit was difficult to get. ``Until
these issues are resolved they won't have the capital or the management
capability to make anything happen.''
David Evans, director of the English NFU, said the political climate in Europe
was not yet right for major changes in the CAP. Sweden and Britain were the
most prepared for these, but it should be remembered there were still reforms
to be enacted from the 1992 package, including those relating to wine and
sugar.
On current issues, the Scottish NFU president, John Ross, called for firmer
control of the cereals market within the EU as a way of helping livestock
farmers faced with high feed prices and the possibility of supply shortfalls.
``The intensive sector are major customers and need stability both of supplies
and prices,'' he said. ``We have agreed we want a well-managed, stable,
non-fluctuating cereals market at EU level.''
</TEXT>
