<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MEDIA Scottish boardroom shuffle when the chairman retires</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044729</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Television managing director Gus Macdonald will become executive
chairman next year, but a new managing director will be appointed to share the
responsibilities of day-to-day management.
Mr Macdonald, 55, will be promoted once Scottish's present non-executive
chairman, William Brown, retires at the company's annual meeting in May.
A Scottish spokesman said Mr Brown, 66, had expressed a desire to step down
some time ago, but announcement of the move had been delayed until Scottish's
strategic alliance with cable television operator Flextech had been completed.
In August, Flextech, a UK subsidiary of the US cable giant Telecommunications
International Inc, bought a 20% stake in Scottish. Flextech also transferred
its 20% stake in the Welsh ITV station HTV to the Scottish broadcaster as part
of the #64m deal.
In return, the latter undertook to provide television programming for Flextech
and its associate companies. The two partners also announced in October that
they would set up a new cable television channel for Scotland.
At that point Scottish also announced that it was planning to provide local
programming for Live TV, the cable channel of Mirror group.
The Mirror Group, publisher of the Daily Record and Sunday Mail, also owns 20%
of the Glasgow-based television company.
A sub-committee of Scottish's board is looking at who to appoint as the new
managing director.
The spokesman was unable to say what the split in duties would be between this
new appointee and Mr Macdonald in his new role as executive chairman.
But Mr Macdonald hinted that he would concentrate on broadening the company's
business activities away from its ITV franchise, where City analysts see
limited potential for future growth.
``I look forward to building on our present success as the pace of change
across the media creates opportunities for growth,'' Mr Macdonald said.
He joined Scottish from Granada as director of programmes in 1985 and became
managing director in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Asbestos case firm to appeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044836</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COMPANY which was ordered to compensate two people who contracted cancer
after playing as children near a factory is to appeal against the landmark
court ruling on asbestos.
British-based multinational T&amp;N plc was ordered to pay a total of #115,000 to
two Leeds women in the first case in which a British court ruled that a company
was liable to compensate people other than its own workers for asbestos-related
illnesses.
Mr Arthur Margereson and Mrs June Hancock contracted cancer of the chest lining
as a result of living and playing as children near the JW Robert factory in
Armley, Leeds - now owned by T&amp;N - ruled Mr Justice Holland at the High Court.
T&amp;N argues that, before 1959, when the factory closed, no-one knew that
asbestos in low doses could harm health.
Mr Margereson died in 1991, aged 66, before his claim was settled and his
widow, Evelyn, 69, was awarded #50,000.
Mrs Hancock, 59, who has been given less than two years to live, was awarded
#65,000.
T&amp;N said yesterday that the awards had been paid and the company would not
demand its money back if the appeal was successful.
T&amp;N has already paid #250m worldwide to people directly affected by asbestosis
and other related diseases.
The Leeds decision was expected to lead to a flood of cases from victims of
asbestos-related diseases who had lived near factories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory MP's friend denies any intimacy when they shared a double bed on French break</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN alleged to be Tory MP David Ashby's lover yesterday denied any physical
intimacy between them when they shared a double bed during a French break.
Dr Ciaran Kilduff, 32, told Mr Justice Morland and the jury on the ninth day of
Mr Ashby's libel action against the Sunday Times that he was surprised when he
saw their room at the Chateau Tilques, St Omer, near Calais, in January 1994.
``Somewhat to my surprise, it wasn't twin-bedded. It had one very large double
bed. I thought I had booked a twin-bedded room.
``But it had been a long, cold day and we weren't in the mood to go back down
saying `this isn't good enough, can you change it please'.
``It was an enormous bed. I would have been embarrassed to force the issue and
insist on going back downstairs to change the room. I think Mr Ashby felt the
same.''
Mr Ashby's counsel, Mr Geoffrey Shaw, QC, asked: ``Was there, as the Sunday
Times alleges, physical intimacy between you?''
Dr Kilduff: ``None whatsoever.''
The 55-year-old MP for North-west Leicestershire is claiming damages over an
article published on January 16, 1994, which said he shared a double bed with a
man friend during a holiday in Goa at the end of 1993.
He says it alleged that he was a homosexual who had misled his estranged wife,
Silvana, about the nature of his sexuality; that he had lied to the public
about having an affair with Dr Kilduff in France; and that he was a hypocrite
in having emphasised the importance of the family in his last election address.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel.
Although they accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa, they
assert he was, and is, having an affair with Dr Kilduff.
Dr Kilduff, of Westleigh Avenue, Putney, south-west London, said he became
friends with Mr Ashby, who was in the process of buying the flat above him,
when they were on the same flight to the US in September 1992.
In October 1993, he had to go ex-directory when Silvana Ashby left a number of
obscene messages on his answering machine to the effect that he had been Mr
Ashby's boyfriend for the past three years.
That Christmas, he had planned to spend his one day off from the psychiatric
wards at the Royal London Hospital having lunch with the MP.
The night before, they were about to have supper prior to attending midnight
mass when Mrs Ashby tried to burst into the flat.
``She was in a complete frenzy. She kept pointing her finger at Mr Ashby. Then
she went into his study and started ripping wallpaper off the newly-decorated
wall.''
Mr Ashby was so miserable and embarrassed by the incident that Dr Kilduff
suggested he take a few days off.
When Mr Ashby asked him to keep him company on a tour of the battlefields of
Agincourt and Crecy, Dr Kilduff agreed once Mr Ashby said it would not cost too
much as they would share a room.
Earlier, Miss Alexandra Ashby, the couple's only child, who works as a
stockbroker in Milan, said her mother could become ``extremely angry,
frustrated, furious, sometimes even violent''.
She said that over the past two years, her mother had accused her father of
having homosexual affairs with a parliamentary research assistant called Tim,
barristers named David and Tim, and another unnamed barrister.
When she was 15 or 16, her mother had accused her and a girlfriend, with whom
she was sharing a changing cabin on the beach, of being lesbians.
Her mother had been loving, caring, and protective, but she was also possessive
and jealous, said Miss Ashby.
She said a failure of communication was the basis of her parents' marriage
breakdown, in 1993, but many fights were based upon jealousy.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baby-sitter who hit child is jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Arran man who assaulted a three-month-old child because it would not stop
crying, was jailed for 15 months at Rothesay Sheriff Court yesterday.
The court heard that Mark Armit, 22, had to jump out of a first-floor window to
escape pursuing relatives.
He had been left in charge of his girlfriend's baby while its mother and
grandmother went out drinking and playing darts and bingo. The child began to
cry and he struck it repeatedly on the head, causing bruising, reddening of its
eyes, and blood clotting in its nose.
Procurator-fiscal Arthur Wheelan told the court that, when the mother arived
back at the house in Port Bannatyne, on Bute, Armit was changing the child's
nappy. When she saw its injuries, she picked up her baby and ran to a
neighbour's house and alerted her brother, who chased Armit, causing him to
jump out of the window into the street.
Armit had to be taken to Victoria Hospital, Rothesay, for treatment.
The court heard how, when police arrived at the house, they failed to get a
statement from the child's mother because of the amount she had drunk.
A doctor's examinations of the child confirmed the injuries which had cause
bleeding in several parts of its head. It was detained in hospital for two days
for treatment and observation.
Armit, of Balmore Lane, Broddick, Arran, admitted through his solicitor James
Hannay, that he had slapped the child twice and put his hand over its face
momentarily. He said he had been under stress and his temper had snapped
because of the child's continued crying.
Armit, who has been in prison for the past four months, had spent the past six
weeks in solitary confinement because of the nature of the charge he was facing.
Sentencing Armit, Sheriff J Irvine Smith said the term of imprisonment was
justified because of ``the extreme gravity and nature of the offence''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Criticism unjust, says new forestry chief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044839</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE new director general of the Forestry Commission, who only last week was
managing a large timber-supplying operation in Australia, yesterday said he was
bewildered by the criticism coming from UK conservationists about his
appointment.
Mr David Bills, 47, said he believed it could be a result of a ``very active
and quite militant conservation movement'' in Australia, which had chosen to
personalise issues in the information they had put out about the forest
industry. Forestry there is the number one issue before whales and nuclear
matters.
``It's disappointing but I can understand in the UK some confusion with all the
material coming over,'' he said when he took up his duties at the commission's
UK headquarters in Edinburgh.
Three years ago, he was elected president of the National Association of Forest
Industries, a lobby group representing 85% of the Australian industry.
Mr Bills said he felt some conservationists considered him ``a representative
of the arch-enemy''.
On the much-publicised incident involving Professor David Bellamy, one of the
first UK environmentalists to criticise his appointment, Mr Bills said he was
``totally bemused''.
He said that, in 1981, the professor took part in a demonstration in Tasmania
against the building of a hydro-electricity dam.
``The tree felling he recalls was being done by the Tasmanian Government's
hydro-electricity commission to open up a road to allow the dam to be built. He
says I was associated, which is certainly not true, and he's talking about it
as if I'm the chap who got him into jail.''
He said forest products were becoming increasingly scarce in a more demanding
world and the UK had recognised the deficits many years ago and made
``extraordinary preparations'' by doubling the amount of land under planting.
He added that society here had traditionally valued the outdoors and the access
to it.
``The real challenge, and I think it can be well met, is to integrate both the
wood requirements of the nation with the non-timber values of forestry.''
Asked about reports that environmentalists feared he might accelerate forest
sales and erode access, he said no-one had said anything to him within the
commission that indicated he was being brought in to speed up that programme.
``I suspect the conservation interests here are taking the opportunity of a
change of guard to make a point and to remind the Government that access is
important.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bulldozers close in on cairn site</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044840</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAIRN thought to be around 5000 years old is to be dismantled stone by stone
before bulldozers get to it.
It was discovered two months ago near the standing stones at Callanish, Lewis.
The site, close to Breasclete School, is in the way of road improvements. The
islands council agreed to delay work after the find but time is now running out.
A team of archaeologists are digging to unearth its secrets. The bulldozers
move on to the site in about two weeks.
The archaeologists will probably have to dismantle the cairn and rebuild it
nearby unless they can persuade councillors to divert the road.
Pleas so far to Western Isles Islands Council to reroute the road around the
site have fallen on deaf ears because of the cost.
Council spokesman Nigel Scott said: ``Historic Scotland agrees that, although
the Callanish Stones site is as important as Stonehenge in many ways, it is not
worth spending a six-figure sum to go around the cairn.''
The full council will debate the cairn's fate tonight.
The kerbed chamber, measuring eight-and-a-half metres across, was found by
island archaeologists Ron and Margaret Curtis after soil was stripped for the
roadworks close to their home.
Mrs Curtis noticed that pieces of quartz, rare in the islands, had been turned
up by a digger.
The cairn is thought to date from the same time as the 49 standing stones that
dominate the skyline on a hill a mile away.
Local historian Dr Finlay Macleod said: ``The cairn is        in line with the
main north    avenue of the Callanish   Stones.
``We don't think it was a tomb but a place where human remains and bones were
burned with charcoal. It's a mysterious place.''
Mr Curtis added: ``It would be terrible to bury it all under tarmac.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline  present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044841</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is it that sets the grand voyager apart from tourist class? Money used to
be the dividing factor, but over recent days Bill Clinton has reminded us of
another indicator. The visiting alien, with enough clout in his pocket, is
spared the irascible welcome of immigration officials. And rather as the rest
of us travel with extra underwear, the US President moves around the world with
an extra plane at his disposal, the first kitted out as a miniature Oval
Office, the second an emergency hospital. America has lost too many heads of
state to the assassin ever to assume the simplest journey will be trouble-free.
The other sign of Clinton's real distinction as a traveller is that he commits
his luggage to the avid safekeeping of bearers, thus avoiding the muscle-strain
of dragging his suitcases to Check-In, then worrying about whether the wretched
stuff will ever make it to the aircraft, and finally hanging about the carousel
at the other end only to discover that the whole lot is stuck somewhere at
Hoboken. Where would shuttle diplomacy be if power politicians were obliged to
make bucket-shop arrangements?
But it is a funny thing about Bill Clinton's bags. As you might expect, he has
truck-loads of them, yet he always seems to end up wearing the same suit. Not
so with overcoats, however. During last week's extraordinary tour of Ireland,
North and South, he appeared in three separate coats in one day: a black Melton
on his Shankill walkabout, a brown trenchcoat in the Falls, and a second black,
but slightly different, Melton in Derry. By night-time, for the big Belfast
switch-on of Christmas lights, Clinton was back in the first coat, this
repertoire of apparel residing on the arms of several aides spread over the
various motorcades. So, if the Comeback Kid mislays one coat somewhere en
route, another isn't far behind.
Unlike royalty, however, Clinton travels with cash in his wallet. In East
Belfast he spent #3 on fruit and a mixed bunch of flowers for Hillary. In
Dublin, as he left Cassidy's Pub, he planted a bunch of punts in a charity box.
Was it all stage-managed? Yes, to some extent, but now when politicians
generally mask mediocrity with arrogance, Clinton's spectacular crowd sense
exposed the lack of true leadership close to home.
And if he never put a foot wrong that, in some way, was because security
officers were barnacled to him like glumly possessive valets. Which one, we
wondered, was the man carrying the nuclear button in his personal organiser?
Was he the Patrick Malahide look-alike, face sharp and hostile as a
searchlight, so suspicious of everything that he probably sleeps with his
earpiece still switched on?
There were moments, though, when a war of nerves operated between the agents
and the President himself. With microphones hidden in their cufflinks and, very
probably, their own land-to-air missile potential tucked into their socks, the
guys in fawn raincoats believe themselves to be the superior presence. ``Mr
President, hurry it up. We're 10 minutes behind schedule,'' one barked at
Clinton as he dived into the Derry crowd, ignoring all persuasion to the
contrary. In Dublin, the President was the one to fish out a fallen child in
the crowd, while a security officer, huffed that his instructions seemed to
count for nothing, trained a gimlet eye on one of Hillary's spontaneous
suitors: ``Jasus, you're looking great,'' the stranger told her, adding: ``Have
you got any sisters knocking around?''
And outside Belfast's City Hall, two agents suddenly found all their reference
points on sanity sliding away as a chap from the Springfield Road told the
crowd Sandy Wilson, mouthpiece of Ian Paisley, had dismissed the gifted
Christmas tree from Nashville, Tennessee, because it was green. ``Honest to
God, what does he want, an orange tree? Well, he can have an orange tree but
he'll find that's mostly green as well.''
Down in Dublin, hours later, that ominous secret service vehicle which prowls
behind the presidential limousine, looking tactlessly like a hearse, was once
again in action, the back window open for agents' easy access to its arsenal of
weapons in the event of any attack. Twenty-five years of violence in Ireland
haven't numbed the shock of seeing men with shoulder-holsters. ``Isn't the
sight of that stuff enough to put the heart crossways in you?'' said a member
of the Garda, with a heavy sigh. And then, in obvious satisfaction, he turned
to the real duties of the day, directing College Green's over-excited Clinton
watchers towards a spruced line-up of municipal WCs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Courage profits boost Scottish &amp; Newcastle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044842</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
Interim   1995-96 1994-95
Turnover #1345m #1011m
Pre-tax profit #155m #145m
EPS   21.0p 20.1p
Dividend 6.55p 6.09p
SCOTTISH &amp; Newcastle benefited from a #9m profits contribution from the #425m
Courage acquisition in the first half, partly because of a 7.5% leap in beer
volumes in its three months under the control of the Edinburgh-based brewery
and leisure group.
However, cash reorganisation costs are higher than market expectations and will
amount to #80m for the full year. Less important, due to the strength of the
S&amp;N balance sheet, is a #70m asset writedown.
Chief executive Brian Stewart said management integration had gone ahead very
well, while the Courage brands had out-performed with John Smith elbowing out
Tetley as the best selling ale.
Some 160 management jobs have gone so far, although details of the full
integration - including the extent of the distribution network closure
programme - will not be announced for a few weeks.
Overall group pre-tax profits in the half year to end-October were ahead 6.2%
to #155m on a turnover advance of 33% to #1345m. The shares fell 12p to 617p as
analysts scaled back their full-year expectations marginally to a profits rise
from #264m to just over #310.
The interim dividend had been raised 7.5% to 6.55p.
Mr Stewart said there was a definite north-south divide, beer sales in southern
England benefiting from the weather to a much greater extent and from a
stronger uplift in consumer spending.
S&amp;N's own production rose just 1% and that was helped by the large number of
brands, such as Becks and Theakstons, which appeal to the more specialised
sectors. The underlying volume position was also helped by the 11% growth in
take-home business.
Beer operating profits were effectively unchanged, excluding Courage. However,
there are continuing benefits from the Chef &amp; Brewer acquisition with the pub
retail side ahead almost 10% at #80.4m. There is much more to come there with
food sales, up a sixth, still below the UK average in what is a decided growth
sector.
The group operates 2600 pubs, assuming that the 100 or so acquired with C&amp;B and
planned for disposal go within the next few months.
Center Parcs had a mixed experience even in Benelux where the Belgian units
out-performed their Dutch counterparts. The British centres more than held
their own.
The leisure division's overall profits were marginally stronger at #50.9m on
turnover of #216m.
Full-year capital expenditure is estimated to be around #200m although gearing
will remain comfortably below 40%.
The dividend total could increase to 20p for a 4% yield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Five years for drug dealer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>News Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975044843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DRUG dealer Alistair Malcolm, 46, who was caught with cannabis with a street
value of almost #11,000, was jailed for five years at Perth High Court,
yesterday.
He admitted being concerned in the supply of the drug at his flat in Commercial
Street, Dundee, and elsewhere in Tayside, between August 1994 and last January.
Rates appeals
OWNERS of more than 1800 non-domestic properties in the Borders have lodged
appeals with the regional council against the outcome of this year's
revaluation exercise. The figure represents almost 28% of the total of 6770
properties, with a combined ratable value of #49.5m.
Crash death
A 26-year-old man died after the car he was driving hit a brick wall during a
police chase in Orpington, Kent, yesterday. The man had to be cut free from the
car, which was believed to have been stolen. He died later while being
transferred between hospitals.
Murder hunt
A MURDER hunt was under way yesterday, after a 21-year-old man died in
Fazakerley Hospital, Liverpool, after he was found with serious head injuries
outside the Garage Club nightspot in the city's Wood Street. The man's name has
not been released.
Irish challenge
THE Irish High Court yesterday gave the go-ahead for a legal challenge to last
month's referendum decision to scrap the ban on divorce. Anti-divorce
campaigner Des Hanafin was granted a petition to appeal the outcome - which
succeeded by just 0.5% of more than 1.6 million votes - and the case is likely
to be heard early next year.
Killing charge
MR John Evans, 36, of Northfield Road, Gloucester, appeared at the town's
magistrates' court yesterday, charged with killing Polish-Ukrainian Iwan
Romanowskyj, 74, between October 11 and 17, 1985. He was remanded in custody
until December 11.
Asda shopathon
ASDA is to allow customers to shop-around-the-clock for 40 hours in the run-up
to Christmas. Stores in Edinburgh, Watford, and Clapham will open at 8.30am
Friday, December 22, and trade continuously until midnight Saturday, December
23.
Santa class
HIGH Street catalogue chain Index has created a school for Santas where, at a
one-day course in London next week, pupils will learn from a master - American
Santa of the Year 1994.
Extradition move
TWO men who face an extradition hearing on charges of terrorism and breaking
out of Brixton Prison, appeared at Dublin District Court, yesterday. Nessan
Quinlivan, 30, from Limerick, and Pearse McCauley, 31, from Strabane, County
Tyrone, are accused of conspiracy to murder and escaping from the London jail
in July 1991, and were remanded until next Monday, when the extradition
application will be heard.
House closure
THE oldest house in Glasgow, Provand's Lordship in Castle Street, is to close
until early February for repairs and the installation of central heating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fraud bid admitted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044844</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DENTIST tried to fiddle his books by claiming for work he had not done.
Raymond Smith gave one patient veneers instead of crowns and said he had filled
more teeth than he had.
Over an 18-month period, Smith overstated the dental treatment he had given to
64 patients, Aberdeen Sheriff Court heard yesterday.
On another occasion, Smith, of Garleston-on-Sea, Norfolk, pretended he had
inserted a gold inlay into a tooth.
Smith, 51, admitted attempting to defraud Grampian Health Board of a total of
#7627.40.
He had had a surgery in the city's West End, in Albert Street, and also carried
out work at Old Mill of Frosterhill, near Oldmeldrum, in Aberdeenshire.
Depute fiscal Sandy Hutchison told the court that Smith's fraudulent scheme
came to light after he submitted claims for payment to the Scottish Dental
Practice Board in Edinburgh.
Smith's not-guilty pleas to four further similar charges were accepted by the
crown.
Sheriff Alexander Pollock, who was told that Smith is not in good health,
deferred sentence for three weeks for social inquiry and community service
reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A word to the unwise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044845</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT started the Sunday before last with a poll splashed on the front page of
Scotland on Sunday claiming that 15 unnamed leading companies would ``quit
Scotland'' if the promised Labour/Liberal Democrat assembly, with limited
income tax powers, ever came to pass.
By this Sunday the Sunday Times had done its own post-St Andrew's Day ``straw
poll'', revealing that four equally-anonymous quoted companies were threatening
to ``relocate under home rule'' while another seven top businesses were keeping
the matter under review.
By yesterday the Scottish Sun - still fighting for independence in modest
12-point type in its masthead - was endeavouring in true tabloid style to name
the guilty men. Scottish &amp; Newcastle, the Weir Group, and Edinburgh Fund
Managers had all, it seems, been seen leaving the premises, raincoats shielding
their blushing faces. None would talk to the Sun about what it was up to.
All this on top of a much-ventilated poll commissioned by the Scottish Chambers
of Commerce on the same subject which has had more interpretations placed on
its findings than the meaning of life. Polls, straw or otherwise, are now
deeply woven into the fabric of our society. There's no escape from their
prescriptions.
But it's worth remembering that what people tell pollsters they will do and
what they end up doing are, often, two quite different things.
Asking a company, in the current context, where it will conduct its business
from under this or that constitutional settlement - as Scotland on Sunday did -
could mean moving the core headquarters team to protect key executives from
additional income tax. It could also, of course, mean relocating the whole
corporate and operational shooting match. But the massive costs associated with
the latter option, in the case of Weirs say, or S&amp;N, would inevitably act as a
major deterrent.
Let's suppose S&amp;N is one of the unnamed ``quitters''. Chairman Sir Alick Rankin
has made no secret of his hostility to home rule in the past. But quitting, on
the grand scale, for S&amp;N means moving brewing capacity, bottling, and
distribution. It also means selling pubs but, presumably, endeavouring to
maintain market share north of the Border once Scottish Brewers was relocated
in, say, Reading or Newcastle.
If Sir Alick or his successor and the rest of the S&amp;N board were to try that
on, the resistance to Guinness stout among Scottish drinkers which followed the
hostile takeover of Distillers in 1986 would look like mere tokenism. We all
remember how adroitly the S&amp;N board played the Scottish card in its successful
defence against takeover by Elders. If it were to move at the mere whiff of the
Edinburgh parliament most Scots say they want, who, among Scotland's drinkers,
would forgive them?
It would be easier for Edinburgh Fund Managers (total staff 150) to relocate,
although the move might require a name change unless it was to one of the other
Edinburghs, in Indiana, Queensland, or Tristan da Cunha. Another problem would
be the ``canny Scots'' cachet our fund management groups like to trade on. Hard
to sustain that image from the middle of the South Atlantic.
EFM, as it happens, has a more pressing challenge ahead than a legislative
assembly in Edinburgh, Scotland. It is 53% owned by the British Investment
Trust, the main trust it manages. British Investment Trust is, in turn, 85%
owned by the two main coal industry pension funds in the UK.
But, with the privatisation of the British coal industry, CINMan, the main
management vehicle for the pension funds, is currently up for sale. Last month
CINVen, the venture capital side of the business, was sold to its management.
And where CINMan ends up - the deal is expected to be completed by Christmas -
could have a far more critical impact on EFM's future than any home rule
settlement.
Just two examples of the complexities which underly an apparently simple poll
question. Multiply that throughout the sample and it's easy to see why lumping
them all into the ``We quit and we're taking 9000 jobs with us'' story-line
Scotland on Sunday came up with stretches credibility.
In that particular poll, Scotland's top 300 performing companies were
questioned. Seventy eight responded. Of these, 12 said they would ``conduct
their business'' from outside Scotland, if a Scottish assembly with the power
to raise or lower income tax by 3p in the pound were created or Scottish
independence within the European Union were ever achieved.
A further three said they would move if Labour-style home rule were enacted.
Five more - we are told they were a different five - said they would leave
under SNP-style independence. The words move and leave are not mine, but the
interpretation again placed on the answers by the newspaper concerned.
That means 58 of the 78 companies polled will stay whatever happens. Twelve
will conduct their business from elsewhere if there is either Labour or
SNP-style home rule. Five more will leave only in the event of independence.
But what are we to make of the three companies who will leave if a Labour-style
parliament is created in Edinburgh, but will, apparently, stay if Scotland
votes for independence?
I can think of one rational explanation. That the trio concerned see home rule,
with taxation powers, within the UK as added cost while they see independence,
whatever the cost, as a new, separate market which has to be served. But,
equally, I can see a trio of companies bemused and befuddled by all the endless
constitutional wrangling.
I have no doubt that some Scottish companies - particularly larger companies
with big markets outwith Scotland - are concerned. I've no doubt some of them
see constitutional change as added cost. Labour will have a job convincing them
that the Scottish parliament's power to raise (and lower) income tax by 3%
makes sense.
But the decision-makers in the companies concerned should remember Sir Bruce
Pattullo's wise words. Whatever their personal reservations, it's people not
companies who have votes. And if the people want change it's not the business
of business to thwart them. Anonymous poll answers which allow the newspapers
concerned to splash ``We'll quit'' threats are no way to encourage a
constructive, open debate about the options.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman is held after #200,000 drug haul</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Police yesterday recovered a large amount of drugs with a street
value of more than #200,000 after an operation in the East Kilbride area.
It is believed that the officers recovered large quantities of cannabis resin,
heroin, amphetamine sulphate, Temazepam, and ecstasy.
A woman aged 29 is in custody following the haul and is expected to appear at
Hamilton Sheriff Court today.
Strathclyde Police said yesterday that although the anti-drugs campaign
Operation Eagle had ended, police would continue to pursue dealers and
traffickers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNEDIN Fund Managers, which has already lost $590m (#384m) of US funds as a
result of top-level departures arising from management disputes, yesterday
announced that another six fund managers had resigned.
They are believed to be moving en masse to Castle Rock, a new fund management
operation set up with the backing of a US regional bank which is thought to
have put in some funds to get the venture off the ground.
Industry analysts, and Dunedin itself, believe that former Dunedin investment
director Gordon Anderson is behind the establishment of Castle Rock.
Mr Anderson said he was not managing director of the new operation, but would
not comment on whether or not he was involved with the venture.
Industry experts believe more money will walk out the door as a consequence of
the apparent decimation of Dunedin's second tier. However, they are sceptical
about Castle Rock's ability to mop up the lost business, if indeed this is its
strategy.
Rolly Crawford, investment trust analyst at broker BZW in London, said: ``It is
a shame to see a house like Dunedin in this kind of trouble and Bank of
Scotland must step in and actually be prepared to spend money to secure the
business.
``That may involve purchasing another fund management company to quickly
rectify the position.''
Among the latest six to leave Dunedin are Alan Clark, manager of Dunedin Income
Growth Investment Trust, and Neil Pirie, manager of the Dunedin Smaller
Companies trust. Emerging markets specialist Euan Rae is also resigning.
The debacle at Dunedin has resulted in the loss of one smaller and two major US
clients, which have moved $590m of funds.
However, this loss has been offset by the attraction of $200m (#130m) of funds
from two new clients and an existing North American client which has confirmed
its decision to give more money to Dunedin in spite of the shake-out.
It was the departure in July of Mr Anderson, who was replaced by Richard
Muckart from Ivory &amp; Sime, which set in motion the exodus from Edinburgh-based
Dunedin.
The power struggle within Dunedin was first revealed with the announcement of
the resignations of chairman Hamish Leslie Melville and deputy chief executive
Alan Kemp at the end of October.
Their departure was a consequence of the intervention of British Linen Bank, a
Bank of Scotland subsidiary and Dunedin's majority shareholder.
The last straw came when British Linen Bank learned that Nigel Barry, head of
Edinburgh-based Dunedin's Pacific operation, and Peter Tait, head of the
European arm, had handed in their notice.
British Linen Bank chief executive Eric Sanderson, who is leading Dunedin while
a new executive chairman is found, is confident that the exodus is now at an
end.
Commenting on the latest resignations, which came on Friday, Mr Sanderson said:
``I took steps in the middle of last week to distinguish who among the
investment staff were committed (to Dunedin) and who were not.
``It was really this which resulted in the resignations of these people.''
The responsibilities of the six fund managers have been reassigned internally
and Dunedin envisages that, at most, it will have to recruit one or two
specialists.
Mr Sanderson said Dunedin had had a 30% surplus as far as staff numbers on the
investment side were concerned.
Numbers in the investment team have been reduced from 35 to 27, which Mr
Sanderson considered adequate given that it was only realistic to expect
Dunedin's growth would be slower than previously anticipated as a result of
recent events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#1000 fine for egg collector</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN was fined #1000 yesterday for a string of wild bird offences, including
possessing tawny owl, kestrel, kingfisher, and sparrowhawk eggs.
Trevor Cooper, 32, admitted four charges of possessing eggs, disturbing a
merlin's nest, and having equipment for preserving eggs.
Magistrates at Burnley, Lancashire, heard that police found the cache when they
searched Cooper's home while investigating thefts from his employer.
Mr Michael Travers, prosecuting, said: ``He took the entire batch of eggs from
the nest every time.''
Cooper, of Burnley, also was fined #100 for stealing tools and cleaning fluid
from the chemical company where he worked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two jailed for cash card fraud</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than 1000 cashpoint customers were filmed secretly by a gang of crooks as
they withdrew money during an ``ingenious'' swindle, a court heard yesterday.
Close-up shots of unsuspecting account holders as they keyed in pin numbers
gave the fraudsters all the information needed to make hundreds of bogus cash
cards. Teams of thieves then ``trawled'' large areas of England, raiding Abbey
National Building society branches. They withdrew #30,000 in one two-day period
alone.
Southwark Crown Court was told that their unfortunate victims did not realise
they had been targeted until they received their account statements or learned
thatmortgages and other bills had gone unpaid.
In the dock was John Gravette, a 50-year-old car dealer from Edmonton, north
London, who was jailed for four years. His son Warren, 27, of Palmers Green,
north London, once a player for Spurs, was jailed for two years.
The men, said to have lived a ``cash rich'' lifestyle on the #60,000 plus that
could be directly attributed to their part in the swindle, had pleaded guilty
to one charge of conspiracy to steal.
Mr Michael Holland, prosecuting, said the Crown accepted the two men could be
shown to have been involved in the conspiracy for four months of the two years
it existed.
``We can't say who the mastermind is. They and the others involved have not
been caught,'' he told the court.
More than 2500 illegal withdrawals were made, which netted more than #601,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#1m for `helpless nobody'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FACTORY worker who pulled a superheated steel rod out of his head after an
accident was awarded an estimated #1m damages yesterday after the High Court
heard he was now a ``helpless nobody''.
The 85-metre-long bar, heated to between 500 and 700C, shot off a cooling bed
at the Sheerness, Kent, factory where Mr Kelvin Page worked in October 1991,
piercing one side of his skull and going out through the other.
Mr Page, 28, pulled the rod out with his bare hands but it had caused severe
damage to both frontal lobes of his brain.
``Remarkably, he was conscious throughout the entire event. It must plainly
have been a most horrific experience for him,'' said Mr Justice Dyson.
Mr Page, 28, who was once an ``ambitious, highly motivated man'', now ``moved
around as a helpless nobody''.
The judge paid tribute to Mr Page's wife, Vanessa, 28, who has been caring for
him since the accident.
``She has clearly done a remarkable job. She has refused to give in despite
sometimes feeling in despair,'' said the judge.
His former employers had not disputed liability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sacred cows fed to revisionist wolves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Macleod</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975044851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEBUNKING is a disease of the age. For the past decade, and more, it has been
the height of chattering-class fashion to bare an idol's feet of clay. Now,
this autumn, Channel 4 has celebrated the trend with its Secret Lives series,
dramatic film-biography of famous subjects exposing their hidden depths of
darkness, badness, and eccentricity.
So the Duke of Windsor is ``outed'' as a Nazi sympathiser, a traitor to British
interests in the Second World War. Marie Stopes, queen of family planning and
author of Married Love, was last week exposed as a eugenicist, her prime
interest in contraception being its utility in a strive for a master race - not
to mention her loveless, brutal marriage, her suffocating upbringing of an only
child, and a colossal vanity. This week Baden-Powell, he of Scouting for Boys,
is due for the Secret Lives treatment: word is that the great man will be
``outed'' as a closet homosexual; a paederast with dark, sadistic tendencies
(though there is precious little evidence that Baden-Powell had such drives,
and none at all that he practised them).
The trouble with this sort of thing is that, so amenable are we to anything
that tickles our own prejudice, we tend to agree with the hatchet-jobs on idols
we despise and indignantly defend the characters of such deceased as we admire.
Secret Lives produced not a scintilla of evidence that ex-King Edward VIII was
an active, self-conscious Nazi agent; they rehashed many ancient libels, and
disclosed abundant proof that he was an idiot, which we knew already. I enjoyed
the Dr Stopes profile hugely, having a peculiar dislike of opinionated and
power-hungry women (I had an adolescence under Thatcher, after all). The
Baden-Powell programme is as yet unscreened; I suspect, however, that I will
find it most tenuous and unjust.
There is the hint, to this series, that this is revisionism for its own sake.
Some bigshot writer, and a team of researchers, seize on a subject, ascertain
his or her historical image, and then build up all the evidence they can to
tear 'em to pieces. Certainly the writers of Secret Lives have picked a
suspiciously fashionable line.
It is trendy to despise and mock the royal family; and the Duke of Windsor (who
cut a ridiculous figure at the best of times) is easy meat. Recollection of the
last war, and of Nazi evil in particular, has given us a horror of racism, and
thus Stopes's work in eugenics can be blasted in outraged virtue. And in our
sex-sodden, sex-obsessed, sex-daft age - and looking back to a figure as quaint
as Baden-Powell - it is hard for anyone in London of the nineties, I doubt, to
think of a gung-ho shorts-wearing pensioner who liked being with boys but
didn't, in truth, feel any sexual atraction to them.
This is not history. History has its own discipline and, in its highest form, a
grim and steadfast morality. In the first, it looks at a subject in his
historical role, and assesses that individual by the ability, judgment and
character he exhibited in that role. In the second, it assesses achievement by
its endurance through time. In the third, it judges a man within the context of
his time.
And underlying all this, of course, is classical methodology - use of
contemporary sources, documentary and archeological; the unceasing search for
corroboration; the moral obligation to separate the truth of the past from the
exigencies of the present. (Still, Ulstermen hate to be reminded that King
Billy went to the Boyne with the Pope's blessing; and that his victory over
James II excited torchlit rejoicing in Rome.)
An example. One of my great heroes is Jean Calvin, a French-born cleric who,
from his Genevan base, produced the greatest theology of the Reformation.
But the historian in me must accept, as proven fact, Calvin's complicity in the
execution - by burning - of a heretic called Servetus, who denied the key
doctrines of the Christian faith. There are extreme Protestants, to this day,
who try desperately to argue that Calvin had nothing to do with it. And there
are, of course, Romanists and their fellow-travellers who bang on about smoking
Servetus as if it was the defining act of Calvin's life.
The fair historian accepts, as fact, an event which undoubtedly happened and in
which Calvin was unquestionably implicated. But he also puts the episode into
the context of Reformation Europe, when Servetus would have gone to the stake
in every capital in Christendom, when Mary Tudor (a woman as kindly as she was
crazed) was burning Protestant after Protesant in Smithfield Square. Toleration
of a minority faith was a concept undreamed off in the West at that time.
Have Secret Lives been fair to their subjects? Edward VIII's woolly, addled
views on wealth and race were unexceptional among Englishmen of his class.
Eugenics, in the twenties, had none of the connotations - post-Auschwitz,
post-Nuremberg - it conjures up today.
In the innocence of a pre-war world, society thought nothing of scout leaders
watching a swimming competition by lively naked boys . . . and so on.
What is even more puzzling is that ``revisionism'' seems essentially negative,
as practised by contemporary writers and broadcasters. For one, if I were
tempted to devote years of my life to writing a biography, it would have to be
on a subject I admired - or at least for whom I had a certain sympathy;
investing all that time and energy in some gleeful, sustained hatchet-job seems
as malicious as it is perverse.
For another, there are quite a few historical figures from the recent past
deserving of a kindlier image in the contemporary world. Queen Victoria was a
woman of considerable charm and ability, with much more liberal views on, say,
race and sexuality than are generally credited to her.
Harry S Truman, demonised today for dropping the Bomb in 1945, was one of the
best-read men ever to occupy the White House.
And so on. Can the team at Secret Lives not find a few characters, for a
change, deserving of new and brighter public relations?
There is one cheering aspect to this. If the trend abides, and deepens, we may
all look to a day when some of our present sacred cows will, in a generation or
two, be fed to the revisionist wolves. Ho Chi Minh, Stephen Hawking, Derek
Jarman, Andrea Dworkin . . . well, libel laws forfend; but I doubt if our
children will view these colourful subjects in quite the reverential light we
shine upon them in our day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#40m jobs boost for Highlands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #40M shopping centre is being proposed for the centre of Inverness in a
development which could bring up to 700 jobs to the Highland capital but which
could mean the demolition of several existing buildings.
A model of the development, which alone is understood to have cost #40,000, has
now been set up in Highland Regional Council's Inverness headquarters for
public viewing. This accompanies the planning application from MFI Properties
which has been lodged with the council.
The development, one of the largest ever proposed for Inverness, would create a
two-storey shopping mall fronting on to Academy Street and covering 167,000sq
ft, with a Debenhams department store occupying 80,000sq ft. There would be 39
further units and a 600-space car park. The ``Academy Centre'' would be
serviced from an underground level.
The development would also create a direct link between Inverness rail and bus
stations which would allow the construction of a covered pedestrian walkway.
The existing bus station would be demolished.
The MFI store and the Carpetwise store currently on the site are planning to
relocate to edge-of-town units. Negotiations are continuing with others on the
site, including the Royal Bank of Scotland and William Hill.
The St Albans-based Redbourne Group are MFI's project managers. A spokesman
said yesterday: ``This project will enable Inverness to face the challenge of
significant retail market enhancements in places like Edinburgh, Glasgow,
Aberdeen, and Stirling.''
Mr John Greaves, Highland region's depute director of planning, said yesterday.
``It is possible a report might go to the meeting on the planning committee on
February 7 or March 20 but I have alerted the shadow Highland Council.''
Mr Greaves said that even if the council was of a mind to grant planning
permission, it would have to consult the public over the closure of existing
streets proposed in the development.
If there were any objections it would have to be sent to the Secretary of State
with the likelihood of a public inquiry. There were also listed buildings on
the site, such as the bank. This meant Historic Scotland would have to be
involved.
Meanwhile, tomorrow's meeting of the council's planning committee will discuss
a proposal from Nairn-based Narden Sevices which has applied to build a #50m
development at West Seafield near Culloden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth challenged over Laggan pilot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR and the SNP have challenged the Scottish Secretary to prove that giving
the people of Laggan control of their forest was not just a pre-election
publicity stunt.
They want him to extend his initiative so that other communities get preference
in all Forestry Commission sales.
It emerged yesterday that the 25 crofters in two Lochaber townships, Inverroy
and Bohuntin, are interested in buying 1000 hectares of grazing land on the
Forestry Commission-owned Inverroy Estate, as well as several woodland
plantations.
Western Isles MP Calum Macdonald, a Labour spokesman on the Highlands and
Islands, has written to Mr Forsyth following his announcement that he wanted to
help the people of Laggan take over and run the 3500-acre Strathmashie Forest,
which would be Britain's first community forest.
Mr Macdonald tells the Scottish Secretary: ``Since 1979, the Government have
disposed of more than a quarter of a million acres of Forestry Commission
holdings on the open market. The vast majority of these has gone to private
commercial interests. Very little has passed into any form of community
ownership.
``Therefore, there is understandable scepticism about whether your announcement
on Laggan represents a genuine change of heart by the Government, or whether it
is simply a pre-election ploy to grab favourable headlines, but without any
real commitment to change the existing policy with its emphasis on sell-offs to
the private sector.''
Mr Macdonald said that this scepticism could only be erased by a clear
statement from the Scottish Office that, in future, first preference would be
given to community ownership over private companies or individuals.
``If you feel unable to make such a commitment now, then I ask that you
announce an immediate moratorium on all Forestry Commission sales until there
is a comprehensive and thorough review of all the disposals policy with a view
to increasing its social and development value to the local communities.
``Such an announcement would truly mark a genuine new departure in Government
policy, and would be warmly applauded by all those who have the interests of
rural communities and of responsible forestry management at heart. On the other
hand, if such a commitment cannot be made, then rural communities will know
that the Strathmashie announcement is, sadly, no more than a publicity stunt;
good news for the local community involved, but without any wider signficance.''
The Inverroy crofters did not want to speak about their project yesterday. A
report prepared for Highland Regional Council, however, stated that they were
keen to examine the potential of the afforested area on the estate, beyond that
of cyclical timber production.
``The possibility exists for some of the current woodland blocks to be
redesigned to give a greater species mix, providing a more diverse woodland
habitat. If this potential does exist, there are a number of opportunities such
as increased access and interpretation which could be developed if the crofters
acquire the estate.''
SNP land spokesman Councillor Rob Gibson said last night: ``Michael Forsyth has
shown by his action, in approving the Laggan woodland as a pilot study in
community ownership, that he is coming round to the views of the majority of
people in Scotland, that local communities should have control of the land and
resources.
``This move must strengthen the case for the Inverroy crofters to own the
woodland on their estate and gain economic benefit from it. But Mr Forsyth must
now ensure that this opportunity is afforded to other communities throughout
Scotland.''
Inverroy is the third group of crofters in recent weeks to make a move towards
community ownership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Iceland and N Brown team up for #1100m Littlewoods bid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE family-owned stores, mail order and pools giant Littlewoods has received a
#1100m takeover approach from a partnership of two other retail groups, it was
confirmed yesterday.
The bid involves a consortium of Iceland frozen foods and mail order group N
Brown.
Sir David Alliance's Manchester-based home shopping company N Brown is offering
#650m. Its part of the deal would be financed by bank borrowings and a share
issue.
Iceland is chipping in #450m in cash and planning a joint venture to own most
of the Littlewoods properties.
Any deal would have to be approved by the 32 Moores family members who own all
the shares in Liverpool-based Littlewoods. The now disunited family will be
voting on these plans and a takeover move by former chief executive Barry Dale
on Thursday.
Last week members listened to the views of Michael Gatenby, a former deputy
chairman of investment bank Charterhouse, about the company's future direction.
A stock market flotation emerged as one possibility.
Iceland already runs franchises in 38 of Littlewoods' biggest stores.
Ladbroke, the betting shops and hotels group, is believed to have been offered
first option by the consortium to buy the pools arm, which would complement its
Vernons operation.
The home shopping division, which made a #73.4m profit last year and commands a
21% share of the market, would be seen as an ideal fit with N Brown, which has
just 5%.
The story of the Liverpool brickie's son who set up a multi-million pound
company from scratch only to see his descendants squabble over his wealth could
have been taken from the Merseyside soap opera Brookside.
But the threats faced by the retailing, mail order and football pools concern
are real enough. It could lose its status as the UK's largest family-owned
company if its 32 shareholders accept one of the two takeover deals on the
table.
A sale would also end its history as one of the country's most secretive
companies.
The firm was founded in 1923 by the late Sir John Moores who introduced the
concept of football pools to Britain. After a hesitant start, the business grew
and in 1932 he expanded into mail order and, in 1937, into chain stores.
Sir John, the son of a bricklayer, maintained an iron grip over the company and
jealously guarded the family-owned status up to his death in 1993, aged 97.
As his influence waned in the years leading up to his death, disagreements
broke out between members of the extended family about the direction the
company should take.
In March, the board fired chief executive Barry Dale for undisclosed reasons.
Mr Dale retaliated by putting together a #1200m hostile bid.
In the same month, Sir Desmond Pitcher, chairman of North West Water and
Merseyside Development Corporation and a leading figure in the City, resigned
as vice-chairman.
Then in April this year, John Moores III, a grandson of the founder, who owns
6.5% of the company and lives in Monaco, quit the company.
Pre-tax profits from the stores, catalogue shops and mail order activities rose
88% between 1989 and 1993 to #90.5m on sales of #1800m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
