<DOCNO>GH951205-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Key moment for Maid trust</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Maid of the Loch Trust was finally assured ownership of the historic paddle
steamer when it received the keys to her cabins at Balloch yesterday.
Members of the trust joined Dumbarton District Council Provost Pat O'Neil, who
has been one of the driving forces behind the fight to save Loch Lomond's
floating landmark from a watery grave.
``This is the first time in my life I've been given a paddle steamer,'' said Mr
Michael Hughan, of the trust. ``It's been three years to the day that the local
council bought her and saved her from the scrapheap. We've been campaigning to
get her back in service ever since.''
Trustees recently were given the opportunity to acquire the Maid from the
district council once they raised #200,000 towards her restoration. The current
total is well in excess of this figure.
The total cost of restoring the ship to her former glory is estimated at #1.8m.
Applications for European Union aid and lottery funding have been submitted.
Musician and broadcaster Jimmy MacGregor, who was on board for the ceremony,
said: ``I'm delighted to see that trust status has finally been achieved for
the Maid.
``I used to sail on her as a child with my mum and dad and have never forgotten
the pleasure a paddle steamer can give you.''
The Maid is the last major paddle steamer to be built in Britain. She was
constructed in 1953 at the former Inglis yard at Pointhouse, Glasgow, and taken
in sections to Balloch for re-assembly.
</TEXT>
