<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drugs dealer is jailed for six years Charge of killing boy is found not proven</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUG dealer convicted of supplying a 15-year-old schoolboy with the class A
drug methadone, was jailed for six years yesterday.
However, a jury returned a majority not proven verdict against John Allan, 28,
on a charge that he had killed his young victim by supplying him with the
heroin substitute.
The prosecution against Allan at the High Court in Edinburgh was the first
since the Court of Criminal Appeal ruled last year that it was competent to
charge dealers who caused death with culpable homicide.
Lord Coulsfield told Allan, of Loaning Crescent, Edinburgh, that he regarded it
as a particularly unpleasant and serious case.
``You are a man of 28 and you were supplying a class A drug, an extremely
dangerous drug, for a boy who had just turned 15,'' Lord Coulsfield said.
Whatever the accused's own drug problems, there was no possible justification
for such disgraceful and disgusting conduct, he said.
Allan had denied supplying methadone to Alan Colquhoun of Hay Drive, Edinburgh,
on July 26 or 27 in the city's Wauchope Square. The youth's 15th birthday had
been on July 11.
Allan also denied the culpable homicide of Colquhoun on the same date by
supplying him with the potentially lethal drug.
The jury heard that the victim was a substance abuser who was known to take a
number of drugs, including methadone, cannabis, amphetamine, ecstasy,
Temazepam, and valium.
Mr Robert Henderson told the court that Colquhoun was no stranger to drugs and
was already on a downward spiral of abuse.
As Lord Coulsfield pronounced the six-year sentence, Allan shouted abuse at him
from the dock.
The ruling that drug dealers could be charged with culpable homicide followed
the case of Scott Russell, 19, a student from Broughty Ferry in Dundee, who was
charged with killing Miss Jill Kerr, 18, by supplying her with a lethal amount
of amphetamine.
Miss Kerr collapsed at a rave disco in Carnoustie and died in hospital several
hours later.
Lord Coulsfield was also the judge in that case and decided the culpable
homicide allegation against Russell could not go to the jury.
He said Russell could not be said to have caused Miss Kerr's death because she
had sought supply of the drug and decided on what dose she should take.
The judge pointed out that Russell had not instigated, suggested or encouraged
the taking of the drug except by the actual supply.
The Lord Advocate referred the case to the Court of Criminal Appeal to
challenge Lord Coulsfield's view on the culpable homicide charge and to seek
guidance for future prosecutions.
The appeal court ruled that dealers who caused the death of a drugs user could
be charged with culpable homicide.
The appeal judges compared it with an earlier case in which the supply of
glue-sniffing kits to children was ruled to be a criminal offence and stated
that consent on the part of the victim, or even instigation of the supply by
the victim was of no importance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Miller Group is biggest Scots private firm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILLER Group, the Edinburgh-based construction and housing giant, has knocked
off motor dealer Arnold Clark as Scotland's largest private company.
Jordans, the directory of Britain's biggest privately-owned companies,
announced yesterday that Miller was at the top of the Scottish list.
In 1994, the construction group made pre-tax profits of #3.1m on turnover of
#359.6m.
The rankings, based solely on turnover figures, placed Miller as the 14th
largest private company in the UK.
Group chief executive Keith Miller seemed a bit non-plussed when he heard the
news. ``Being the `largest private company in Scotland' is a nice tag line, but
what we're really interested in is the bottom line, which is profit,'' he said.
``Our philosophy is, profit margins come first and turnover levels are second.''
Miller will have a better idea how its bottom-line margins are faring after
December 31, the end of its fiscal year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Perjury trial halted by illness</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PERJURY trial was postponed yesterday because of the illness of the accused.
Mrs Jill Thornley, 51, had collapsed in the dock at Stranraer Sheriff Court on
Friday and was taken to hospital.
Yesterday, Sheriff Robert Dickson was shown a medical certificate stating that
Mrs Thorley was unfit to stand trialand invited submissions from both the Crown
and the defence legal teams.
Mr James Kelman, depute-fiscal, accepted that Mrs Thornley was unfit to stand
trial, asked leave to raise a fresh indictment, and asked for an extension to
the 12-month limit on the case, which is due to expire on January 30.
Mr Neville Shaffer QC, defence counsel, said it was quite clear that his client
was unfit to continue with the trial and added that he was not opposed to any
of the requests from the fiscal.
Sheriff Dickson agreed to the fiscal's requests and discharged the jury.
Mrs Thorley, of Knocknar Monreith, Port William, faces charges of perjury and
attempting to pervert the course of justice.
It is alleged that on August 17, 1994, during an inquiry at Stranraer Sheriff
Court into the death of Mr Daniel Lowe, a patient at Hillcrest Retirement Home,
Wigtown, she said her son Robert Thorley was the sleep-in member of staff at
the home on the evening of February 6, 1994, and that the level of staff was
sufficient to take it within social work guidelines, when she knew that Mr
Thorley was not at the home and that the only member of staff was Ms Marie
Blackley.
It is also alleged that between February 6 and August 17, 1994, she induced Mr
Thorley and Ms Blackley to give false information and false evidence at the
fatal accident inquiry at Stranraer Sheriff Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Safety first the bottom line with orang-utan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMERS who have been flocking for their Christmas shopping to Costco, the
American-style discount store in Glasgow's Springburn, have been fair taken by
one of their lines. It is a 6ft-tall stuffed orang-utan, ideal for the weans
for to romp around with.
But one customer, a West End lady, was concerned that the orang-utan did not
appear to have the all-important safety tag as issued by the European Union. So
it was no go. But the West End husband was quite keen and asked the Costco
checkout staff if the beast did in fact have a safety certificate. The staff
said they would check and get in touch.
Thus it was by the time the West Enders got home there was a message on their
answering machine from an American chap who had been seconded from the US to be
a manager in Springburn.
He confirmed that he had been in touch with the suppliers of the stuffed
orang-utans - in South Korea - and it did indeed have the relevant safety tag.
``Due to the large amount of fur on the orang-utan, it may be difficult to
locate the tag. For future information, the tag is located on the animal's
bum.''
So, if you see customers at the Costco store in Springburn lift a large
orang-utan, turn it upside down, and carefully inspect its nether parts, they
are doing so only to make sure it is safe for their children.
Travel in hope
THE Rangers FC Christmas draw offers as a third prize a trip for two with the
Gers on their first European tie in 1996. We will not go into the fact that
Rangers have yet to qualify for any of the European competitions.
We wish to take issue with the sexist nature of the footnote concerning the
prize: ``This package is worth #1500 and a prize of equivalent value will be
available to ladies or non-supporters.''
Friendly advice
DUMFRIES and Galloway Regional Council has established a flood warning scheme
for the Whitesands area of Dumfries, which is frequently in a damp state when
the River Nith breaks its banks. A council explanation of how the scheme works
includes the following: ``Once initiated, warnings will require `good
neighbours' to alert friends using an agreed cascade system.''
Parting shot
JOHN Murtagh, artistic director of Borderline Theatre Company, was deposed in a
sudden coup last week. The sacking was notable for its poor timing on the part
of the Borderline board. He was due to open four days later at the Magnum
Centre as the dame in Babes in the Wood panto which he had also written and
directed.
Also in his pay poke, which he received just before the shock news of his
dismissal, there was a wee homily, an exhortation from Borderline to all
employees about better communication with your co-workers.
Invisible man
PEOPLE say Jim Farry, secretary of the Scottish Football Association, has no
sense of hunour but we have evidence to the contrary. Donald Finlay, QC,
vice-chairperson of Rangers FC has been in constant communication of late to Mr
Farry protesting about the unfairness of various SFA ordinances and treatment
of certain Rangers players.
Mr Farry has faithfully replied but all of the letters have been addressed to
Mr R Campbell Ogilvie, secretary of Rangers FC. Mr Finlay is a man who does not
like to be ignored so he wrote to Mr Farry requesting that at least have the
decency to write back to him in person.
Mr Farry replied to Mr Finlay's plea with the explanation that the SFA always
communicated with member clubs through the office of their secretary. Yes, the
letter explaining this was sent to Mr R Campbell Ogilvie, secretary of Rangers
FC.
The name game
ECONOMICS Correspondent of the Reuters news agency is one Rich Miller.
No hiding place
THE public relations people of Isle of Jura whisky company have caused some
confusion by issuing a newsletter all over Scotland, and perhaps the world,
called Isle of Jura Herald which purports to be a local paper for the Hebridean
isle. One slight giveaway is the address given for letters to the editor - Isle
of Jura Herald, Isle of Jura, c/o PO Box 2203, London W1A 1AB.
Prize people
THE entries for our competition to find a fourth wise man bearing a suitable
gift are covering the Diary desk deeply, crisply and evenly. First off we have
Dr D S Geddes of Prestwick who suggests that Madonna might turf at the stable
in Bethlehem with a copy of her song Like A Virgin. Gordon Forbes thinks that
Gazza would be there delivering a nice little cross.
A Mr W T McFarlane phoned to suggest that, if the provost of Kilwinning were
called upon for Wise Man duty, he would no doubt take an Easter egg. A Mr
Laurence Jamieson called to say that Michael Forsyth would fit the bill,
complete with his gift of 30 pieces of silver. Unfortunately neither Mr
McFarlane nor Mr Jamieson left an address so we cannot send them a prize of a
bottle of Langs Supreme whisky or a Langs first-footing kit.
Jim Haddock of Gourock contributes the thought that the Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble would take along Paisley shawl for the baby Jesus. The
above-mentioned Dr Geddes responds with Gerry Adams turning up with a Christmas
peace message recorded by an actor. Prizes to everyone, after all it is
Christmas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Welsh Water and Swalec agree #872m deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELSH Water and South Wales Electricity have called a truce and agreed to merge
in a cash and shares deal worth #872m. News of the bid propelled Swalec shares
up 57p to 1165p, while Welsh Water gained 16p to 703p.
Welsh Water is offering one new share plus #40.25 for every five Swalec shares,
valuing the company at 940p a share. There is a cash alternative of 930p.
Swalec shareholders will keep their shares in the National Grid company after
the deal.
A statement from the two companies said the equivalent value of the offer would
be #11.34 with the National Grid interest, which would represent a premium of
22% over the price of Swalec shares prior to bid speculation. The acquisition
is expected to be materially earnings enhancing for Welsh Water April 1, 1996
and will enable it to achieve better dividend payouts.
Welsh Water's chief executive Graham Hawker said the deal would allow Welsh
Water to ``gear up the balance sheet quite significantly''. The combined
company will face a tax charge similar to Welsh's 12%. Up until the merger
Swalec has had a 23% rate.
Mr Hawker said the cost savings from merger of the two firms with their
geographical and customer overlap were ``substantial'', thought to be as high
as #30m.
The deal is the second union between a regional electricity company (REC) and a
water company. North West set the ball rolling in September with a #1580m bid
for Norweb. The bid was raised to #1800m and succeeded in November.
While it had been envisaged that RECs would be attractive to outside predators,
it was never thought that a privatised water and electricity company would
merge, resulting in a multi-utility group serving the same customer base.
Water companies have faced big capital expenditure programmes since
privatisation in order to comply with stricter EU legislation governing
quality. These have resulted in cash outflows. Faced with such an outflow, it
makes sense for a water company to acquire a cash generator such as a REC.
Since privatisation five years ago, the cash generating capacity of the RECs
has enabled them to grow underlying dividends by around 15% per annum. In a
similar time, water companies have grown theirs by about 10% per annum, but at
the cost of falling dividend cover.
Given the multiple attractions of owning a REC, despite the prospect of more
competition, there are likely to be no shortage of suitors for the remaining
independent RECs.
n The European Commission is to investigate Lyonnaise des Eaux's #823m agreed
bid for Northumbrian Water. Last month's bid by the French group is the first
takeover of one of the 10 largest UK water companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Code for tenants</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Homes is to consider a code of conduct for tenants throughout Scotland
involved in the transfer of their houses to alternative landlords, it was
announced yesterday.
The move was welcomed by the Freedom of Choice Campaign, which had the support
of Labour MPs John McAllion (Dundee East) and Sam Galbraith (Strathkelvin and
Bearsden).
Its secretary, Mrs Mary Reid, said: ``We have worked for a considerable time
for a code which would protect tenants, feeling that we could complain, but get
nowhere.''
She said the interests of tenants and their rights had to be protected, adding
that the organisation would be delighted if housing stock could be released to
help those waiting to be housed.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said last week he would be willing to
consider the possibility of councils being allowed to bid for housing sold by
Scottish Homes.
The agency's agreement to consider a code of conduct follows talks between its
chairman, Sir James Mellon, and a delegation of campaigners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Death caused by child vandals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHILD vandals caused the death of nine-year-old Craig Bottley in a blazing
flat, a sheriff ruled yesterday.
Sheriff Iain Pirie said Craig died as a direct result of the criminal
activities of a group of children who were completely outwith the control of
their parents. He said: ``Such conduct on the part of young children is
symptomatic of serious social problems, the resolution of which lies beyond the
scope of this inquiry.''
The sheriff was giving his findings after a fatal accident inquiry at Glasgow
Sheriff Court into Craig's death on October 3 last year.
His body was found in an unoccupied flat in Balgair Street, Possilpark,
Glasgow, after children set the tenement ablaze.
But after the ruling, Craig's parents Catherine and Fred Bottley said it was
unfair to lay all the blame on the children.
``The fire brigade and the council all made blunders and now they have blamed
the boys,'' Mr Bottley said.
Sheriff Pirie said it was the district council's intention that the property at
23 Balgair Street be demolished as part of general development.
On the afternoon of October 3 last year, the two remaining tenants left. At
about 4.30pm, three boys between the ages of 11 and 13 broke in by forcing the
``meshlite'' security sheeting from the half-landing window at the rear of the
building.
They made their way to the top flat and scattered rubbish and overturned
furniture left by the outgoing tenant.
In his findings, the sheriff said the three boys went downstairs and met other
boys including Craig.
All except Craig went to a first-floor flat and set fire to a polyurethane
foam-filled three-piece suite in the living room.
The fire took effect quickly and thick black toxic smoke engulfed the first and
second floors.
Sheriff Pirie said: ``Because of the rapid spread of smoke, heat, and fire,
Craig was trapped in the living room directly above the seat of the fire.''
The sheriff then described how firemen were confronted by a hostile crowd of
disorderly children who interfered with the hydrant water supply and breathing
apparatus and rolled lorry tyres downhill at the fire appliances.
He said the firefighters had no reason to believe the boy was trapped in the
building and no-one informed them.
It was only when smoke was clearing from the second floor that the boy's body
was discovered partly concealed under a section of bedroom unit.
Sheriff Pirie said there had been criticism by a solicitor for the family that
the fire brigade and in particular a station officer had failed to inquire
whether anyone was still in the building.
He said the station officer had no reason to believe                   anyone
was trapped in the building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taking wet weather in our stride</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975044863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE may not have endeared himself to umbrella manufacturers as he strolled his
way through Singin' in the Rain but it appears that Gene Kelly was years ahead
of his time.
As he performed his ``terpsichorean delights with cheerful proletarian grace''
in 1952 - his umbrella no more than a prop - Kelly knew that a steady stroll
for shelter is the smart way to stay drier when it's raining cats and dogs.
To flee or not to flee.......that is the question that has for years taxed
scientists investigating man's natural instinct to dash for cover in a downpour.
Now researchers at Reading University have concluded that a steady stroll for
shelter is the smart way to stay drier.
Their experiments show that rapid movement into the path of raindrops results
in a more severe soaking than weathering the storm at normal walking pace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951205-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951205-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951205</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sport Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
