Ice hockey
STRUGGLING Murrayfield Royals have been rocked by the walkout of talented young
forward Tommy Boll.
The Ayr-based player did not turn up for Sunday's defeat by first-division
leaders Blackburn Hawks, and last night team manager Billie Dunbar said:
``Tommy did not appear for training last Thursday and did not turn up for
Sunday's game. I've been told that he does not want to play for us again and is
fed up because he did not get on the ice during the first period of last
Tuesday night's game against Dumfries.''
Royals have lost 17 of their 20 league games this term, and Boll was a key man
in the side.
Dunbar added: ``I want to speak to him about this, but I'm disappointed if he
has decided to pack in, as he was progressing well with us. He won't get as
much ice time with another club as he will here.''
Cycling
COLIN Bark and Julian Hopper, of the Glasgow Nightingale Club, became the
British Tandem kilometre record-   holders, achieving 1min 13.2sec at the
Manchester Velodrome. They will be competing in April for the British world
hour record at the same venue.
Rugby
OXFORD and Cambridge both field three old Blues for the varsity match at
sell-out Twickenham next Tuesday.
Cambridge, favourites to retain the Bowring Bowl, have New Zealander Steve
Cottrell leading them after missing the 1994 game with a knee injury.
Oxford centre Jerome Riondet becomes the first player from France to appear in
the varsity match.
