<HEADLINE>Judge praises fighting qualities Youth wins damages and tributes after accident destroys his boxing ambitions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975044903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JUDGE has praised the courage and determination of a young man who is
rebuilding his life after he suffered severe brain damage in a road accident at
the age of 12.
Lord Marnoch was speaking at the Court of Session, where he awarded Mr Maurice
O'Connor, 19, damages of #207,263.
Mr O'Connor has managed to gain a number of Standard Grade passes and has
recently started a computer course with the ultimate aim of gaining a Higher
National Certificate.
Although he can no longer pursue his ambition to become a professional fighter,
he still regularly attends training sessions at his boxing club.
Mr O'Connor, of Kilgarth Street, Coatbridge, had been crossing Viewfield Road
in the town when he was struck by a van in December 1988.
He suffered a severe brain injury and was in hospital for seven months. He has
been left with marked physical disabilities, the most serious of which is an
involuntary tremor in his limbs.
Lord Marnoch ruled that both Mr O'Connor and the van driver, Mr James Matthews,
of Rhinds Street, Coatbridge, should have seen each other in good time to avoid
the accident. He decided that Mr 0'Connor was 50% to blame for what happened.
The judge said there were a number of positive features about the case for
which Mr O'Connor was due praise.
Apart from his attendance at the boxing club, he had succeeded in obtaining a
number of Standard Grade passes and recently had started a course in computer
application at Motherwell College.
Lord Marnoch added: ``Whether he will succeed in this is perhaps questionable
but his determination to do so is not in doubt.
``He gave a good account of himself in the witness box and came across as an
extremely personable and likeable young man who bore his ills with humour and
fortitude.''
After the accident, Mr O'Connor went to Ashcraig School which, the judge was
informed, is well known for turning out its physically handicapped pupils with
social skills to do their best in the community.
``If that is so, then Mr O'Connor is a credit to these teaching methods,'' said
Lord Marnoch.
``However, it is important to realise that these skills cannot in the end truly
compensate for the underlying physical and intellectual disabilities from which
Mr O'Connor is suffering and which must be regarded as permanent.''
In the damages award, the judge included an element to cover loss of earnings,
after hearing evidence from an expert in rehabilitation that there was no real
prospect of Mr O'Connor obtaining profitable employment in the future.
Lord Marnoch said he had found the expert a thoughtful, careful, and reliable
witness but added: ``At the same time, it would not wholly surprise me if Mr
O'Connor were, in due course, to prove him wrong.''
